GeneralComments: Jess is a very adventurous and bold puppy.  She is smart and learns quickly.  However, she can also be stubborn and have her own agenda. Jess is very in tune to her people and loves to get praise and attention, sometimes that is more motivating to her than food. Jess's personality and energy make her a great candidate for a guide dog, she just needs LOTS of practice and some maturing.

GeneralComments: Gala has a gentle temperament. She is not overly bold, but is very confident once she's found her center and calms herself quickly when encountering new experiences. GeneralComments: When I got him he was a whirlwind, we've put a lot of emphasis on calming him down/settling as well as trying to get him to entertain himself and direct his chewing onto his toys -I'm proud to say that's going fantastically. He's just reached the point where he's calm and attentive in the house about 85% of the time, but he's still not at the point where he can settle well outside of the house (in class, at sedate locations, we've tried to keep the distractions minimal but it's still to much for him to really settle down. He's fine with most distractions if we're actively working with him (heel/sit/down/stand/stay/come/ect). Also, he's very attentive for a good period of time up to 45mins max, but after that he gets extremely frustrated and agitated, stops listening, starts biting and whining (this is really only an issue in class)Other than this, he's great.

From his first day with us, he scored a 10 out of 10 for name response (high praise to those people who worked with him before he came to us!)  He rides beautifully in the car.  So far we have not experienced any destructive behavior.  In new situations or experiences he can appear cautious.  In these situations he tends to quiet down rather than show anxious signs like scratching, tongue flicking, etc. A one year old GEB pup has recently joined our home and has been a wonderful aid in Iverson's confidence.  At the same time, Iverson has not taken on any of his bad habits such as barking and other social skills.  Iverson is extremely food motivated and eager to learn and to please.  He is a very happy and easy puppy and a 100% pleasure to have in our home.

Gladys is a sweet, smart girl who stives to please. I have never seen aggressiion, though excitement is sometimes a challenge. On socializations, especially in crowded or busy places she can be extremely focused. In more casual settings she (I?) is/am more easily distracted. I mentioned cat issues. My 'less friendly' cat sometimes hisses/growls when Gladys enters a room, which intrigues Gladys who wants to investigate. If the cat runs, Gladys may get excited and give chase. I'm usually able to anticipate, so it doesn't happen often. Then a couple nights ago Gladys laid calmly within a few feet while the cat came to me for attention, but its not a pattern of behavior I can count on yet. Gladys is friendly toward my other cat and learning to respect her space. Same with my personal dog.Gladys has improved when approaching stangers, and when she does get excited is more easily redirected. Sometimes Sunday afternoon classes are a challenge; I think becasue she has been crated all morning, and there is limited time to eat lunch and exercise her before class.This morning I saw her first ever hesitation in walking over a grate.

Fritz lacks confidence around traffic. With that being said Fritz really likes to be with me so I believe I can build his confidence. Some unusal objects concern Fritz such as statues.  Fritz is learning to check them out on his own or with support from me when needed.  Fritz is a very sweet puppy.  He has been displaying some separation issues when I'm not around.  If I go somewhere and leave him with my family he whines and cries at the door and window, he doesn't find comfort in my family still being there.  I have asked my family to help him redirect his behaviors and to ask Fritz to go get a toy. Fritz also pees in his kennel when I leave him. It doesn't matter if its 10 mins or 3 hrs the end result is he pees.  When I return home Fritz always acts like I have been gone forever and I may have just walked outside.  I ignore this behavior because I don't want his behaviors rewarded.

Her self control has improved a great deal. When she is excited she can be calmed quickly in a down. She loves to work and has great endurance and will ask to do more work. She will sometimes ignore food rewards because she wants to get back to investigating the world.

She has great self control when she engages her judgement (will wait forever for food bowl) but has had problems using judgement and thus will get highly activated. It has improved dramatically but is a slow process. She does settle down quickly from activation if you separate her from whatever was the problem. She loves to work, has great endurance and a high energy level but will ignore food if activated. Initially she had two speeds, stop and full but now she is mellowing and can operate at appropriate levels when not activated. When you manage her activation levels she is a very good dog.

Overall, Emily is fun to be around and she is a really smart dog and a quick learner. The biggest issue is her inability to calm herself down when she gets excited or frustrated. She gets herself into a frenzy and you can tell she has no control. I've tried increasing the distance and distracting her, but all that seems to do is make it worse.  I've tried standing still and also trying to get her to walk in a different direction which doesn't seem to work either.  She becomes a growling, biting, run around out of control mess. I have to pick her up and put her in her kennel. This is fine if we are in the house, but when we are outside and I have to carry her 2 or 3 blocks to get home it becomes a problem.  She seems to come unhinged and she becomes what we call "hair on fire crazy".  We aren't quite sure what sets her off either. One time she became unhinged because she wanted to eat an acorn and I wouldn't let her. So, I had to pick her up and carry her the three blocks home because she wasn't listening. Every time I put her down I could tell she still wasn't in control of herself. Another time, the situation was pretty exciting - she saw a rushing creek for the first time so it was fast movement, loud noise, and water!  She wasn't sure about it at first so she kept running up to it and then running away. Each time she would get closer and not run away as far. She finally figured out it was water and she was thrilled to death and at the same time became unhinged. I ended up having to carry her the quarter of a mile home because, again, each time I put her on the ground she exhibited the same out of control behavior.  She bolts in every direction, growls, and bites at my clothes. Evidently three blocks away from an acorn or a quarter of a mile away from a creek is not enough distance to allow her to calm herself. Loud noises and different surfaces underfoot do not seem to be a problem at this time. She walks on concrete, grass, gravel, tar and chipped roads, dirt roads, paving blocks, and paved surfaces without a problem.  The only noise I remember startling her was the fire trucks briefly testing their siren and horn one morning. We were about three blocks away from the fire station when, for about a second, they turned on the siren and honked their horn. Emily was startled by that and stood there for a second or two and then she was fine.  We continued on our walk as if nothing had happened. This was the first time she had ever heard that noise. The diarrhea has been a huge issue and I think it has also somewhat impacted her training a little since I was afraid to give her too many treats and when we are rushing to get her outside so she doesn't have an accident in the house, the last thing I am thinking about is proper manners and walking appropriately on lead. I'm hoping that once we get her GI issues straightened out we can get better at the training. I do think her behavior, when she is in class, has improved over the past few weeks. She doesn't seem to be as restless as she was in the beginning and she seems relatively calmer around the other dogs as long as they keep their distance. She still needs to improve a lot, but I think I see a difference in her as the weeks go by.  Tiny improvements each time we attend class. Grant it, to an outsider she probably still looks like a wild woman, but to me, I can tell she is a bit better than she was about paying attention to me and while she still gets distracted, she seems to be able to recover herself a little bit quicker each time.

His stair work is coming along nicely. Dennis likes to be close to us and settles down wherever the action is.Dennis is a twig/stick eater whenever he has the opportunity so we have to monitor his outside play closely. He plays appropriately with other dogs.We are enjoying our time with Dennis he's a lot like his mother.

GeneralComments: Yoli is pretty low energy and an easy puppy to have. She is very good when socializing. No demand barking and can settle after a bit. She doesn't show very much stress when brought into new situations and is given some time to process and get used to her surroundings and what is expected of her. She has a low dog distraction so far and has a good checkin when encountering one. She plays nicely with other dogs when offered a toy, but may neck bite if no toy is present.  I am working on socialization and repeat exposures to build her confidence and also practicing settling in more distracting environments. She offers a very large amount of checkins to the point of staring at me. I am trying to reward with butt scratches and voice praise intermingled with food rewards to try to get her to notice her surroundings more.

Yani is an awesome pup.  She loves going everywhere with me and seems happy to go places.  She follows my commands but does not always follow commands from other family members and friends.  She needs more experience and work in higher distraction areas.  The kids and teachers at school love her.  She is not in her kennel very often because she is so good outside the crate.  I have not had any house manner issues in a long time.  I have left her inside our home but outside the crate for hours at a time without any problems.  I feel we are working on age appropriate issues - distractions on the ground or other animals or people.  She is not always crisp with her commands so we are working on this.  She absolutely loves the water.  We are at my in-laws for Thanksgiving in Ohio where it is between 40-50 degrees and she loved doing retrieves in their pond.  When we are out, everyone is always commenting on how well behaved, calm and easy going she is.  She was very patient and did a long down-stay when I was trying on clothes and shoes in the busy mall!

She sits through church better than my family!  Special things we are working on include stairs and her playing with our released dog, Rhiana.  Mary has given me tips to get them calmer inside and outside the house.  They are getting better.  Our older dog, Vader doesn't really play with Yani, so Yani pretty much just leaves her alone.  Yani was doing much much better with stairs until this latest incident.  She improved so well before, that I think she will quickly move beyond this.

GeneralComments: Krieger is a very laid back wonderful pup who learns very quickly and remembers very well.  Krieger also enjoys going everywhere with me and has been to church, various doctor appointments, restaurants, various stores, and has gone with me to a few GEB presentations to local clubs and organizations. Katie is extremely confident especially on surfaces and in different environments. She has adjusted well to college life and is a pro at settling in class. She can sit through a two hour class without any issues, I do not give her a bone or anything. She is an awesome loose leash walker! She is great in the house and is incredibly reliable, has never gotten on furniture or in the trash. She rides well in the car and stays on the floor the entire time. She is a ball of energy and lots of fun to work with. The one thing we are working on right now is distraction with leaves and squirrels!! She really would like to make friends with all of the squirrels. If I ask for name response and wait she will connect with me and then we can continue on. She is a great pup with a lot of confidence and is great at her skills!

ExerciseType: Walking, playing with other dogs, swimming, tug-of-war, ball chasing
GeneralComments: Jude is a sweet boy and likely intelligent given his ease and willingness in learning new commands and his demand barking while kenneled.He is the eleventh dog we have raised for GEB and the first to defecate in his kennel not due to illness (5 times as compared to say Omaha who had diarrhea due to Giardia). Jude will urinate in his kennel within 30 minutes of having been allowed to get busy and has indoor accidents when he gets excited. He seems very immature and highly distracted around getting busy. As a result, we do not consider him housebroken at 5 months. He did very well on his puppy sits and accompanied his two puppy sit handlers to work where they reported that he settled nicely and did not have accidents while with them at work but they also took him out frequently and never left him alone. They also reported that he barked a lot when put in his kennel in their homes (keeping one poor couple up at night) and that he had accidents at home which improved over time (both sitters had no other dogs in the home). We have learned that he cannot concentrate on getting busy unless on leash and away from the other older dogs. Despite being kenneled within two feet and in sight of the other dogs in their kennels, he barks every time he is kenneled. While he settles down after a while (receiving rewards and treats when quiet) he still has accidents. This has been a time suck for us (regular cleaning and deoderizing of the kennel tray) and has made us rather distrust him in the house (we have taken up some rugs to avoid soiling). Despite being taken out very frequently (sometimes about every hour if he has been playing or waking from sleep), he still has accidents. He will not be allowed to work indoors for another month at least.Jude returned last week at puppy class from his last sit highly distracted and pulling badly on leash although the sitters said he had been easy to handle. It took half the class to get his attention, and even then he was highly distracted by smells. Due to his being bitten by a copperhead this weekend, the raiser had to keep his leash time to a minimum and has not had much opportunity to refresh his leash manners.While we were once resolved to return him to GEB, we have decided that his sweet temperament; ability to settle calmly when alone and undistracted; and willingness to work trump the frustration of his extremely unreliable habits of elimination. We will also overlook our disappointment that like Omaha he seems cow-hocked and unlikely to be considered for stud even if we were to ensure he made his IFT. You know, having raised two broods, we'd really like to have a stud or two and some more grandpuppies to raise ... Sigh.We think over time he will prove to be a sound dog and if medically fit then temperamentally able to handle the demands of working.

ExerciseType: She's a very busy puppy. Fetch, swimming, tug, playing outside, small walks
GeneralComments: Iva is a smart puppy and her attention has really improved over the past few weeks. She's walking better on leash and really likes to check things out, walk on different surfaces., etc. She knows Sit, Down, Stand, Heel. We are working on Close and Over.   I think the hardest thing for her will be ignoring people and eventually greeting politely. We have not been saying hi to anyone unless I know them and we can practice nicely. I pay her really well for checking in with me and holding a command with people around. We have done a lot of people watching and practicing in low key places.   Iva is very busy. She jumps from one toy to another and plays and plays. However, if she gets the scoots you know she is done and needs a nap. She's great in her crate. She is definitely a pup that will become activated if overwhelmed or excited.  She doesn't seem to have issues with body handling or wearing things. She's good and less excited around other dogs.

ExerciseType: Fetch, walking, tug, swimming when warmer
GeneralComments: Iva is doing well. I can definitely see improvement with her excitement around people. She does well walking past people and ignoring them, but if they come up to pet her suddenly she sometimes loses her self control. Also, if you are talking to someone she might try to sneak in a hello. If they use a squeaky voice we are done for, and I move her away. She still licks a lot!! Iva still acts very much like a puppy, but you can tell she is trying hard to focus and control herself. We have had some really great greetings where I'm able to get her to sit while someone pet her, but generally when we are out I have not been allowing her to say hi. She plays great with other dogs, and the cat is her buddy. She is very good about respecting the cat's space and things. She still stalks her toys and sometimes the other dogs. Iva absolutely loves her crate and will go in voluntarily to nap or chew a toy. She is very good at settling when out and does not need a toy. She is good about getting a toy and occupying herself at home. She walks great almost all the time and is enjoyable to take for longline walks, as well. Her body handling is coming along well. She doesn't have a problem wearing things. She also really enjoys climbing and exploring different things. Iva's biggest problem area is her self control around strangers.

Walks, Plays with dogs, Fetch, Swimming

GeneralComments: Inka is a nice pup most of the time, but is always testing/pushing the limits.  Demand barking is the most challenging thing we are dealing with, particularly around our pet labs when they don't want to play with her in the house.  The only way we are successful is to have them physically apart for most of the day.  She is one of those pups that is both pushy/demanding and also build-up in terms of her confidence.  She is easily bored and does best when she has had a lot of physical or mental exercise.  She did well on our trip south last week and had a wide variety of environments to work, settle and play in -- including very noisy/busy environment in Savannah, GA and beach sand and waves on Pawley's Island, SC -- and lots of restaurants, museums, shuttle buses, street cars, etc!  Spent very long times in her crate in the back of our SUV (including 9+ hours on the drive home) and settled with no barking.
Inka is a very nice pup, but can be a challenge - particularly the demand behaviors and barking/whining.  She continues to improve (other than at puppy class!) and hopefully we will get beyond this!

GeneralComments: I feel Ilka is doing well, she still can be sloppy on her commands (sloppy sitting, sliding into a down) but has excellent eye contact and a willingness to please.  She is doing incredibly well on her outings and is extremely patient and settles well. She shows no concern for new experiences, crowds or loud music (the marching band)  I am a bit concerned about her with the kitten, they play quite a bit, the kitten does start it but she does recall exceptionally well.  When she comes in contact with the barn cats from next door - she is interested but does not chase them. She has gotten more silly (jumping on only me and the mouthing thing) now that I am gone during the day but takes just a few seconds to get it all together and back on track.  Overall I am happy with her progress but continually working for continued success!

Dahlia is a real sweetheart. She is very affectionate and attentive. She learns quickly when given clear feedback (treats and praise when making good choices; interrupting and disapproval when making poor choices). She has made progress in all areas of behavior. The housebreaking remains the most strange. It is surprising that she is still having any accidents. But she is trying and is getting better. The counter-surfing improved quickly after getting negative feedback. She has made a lot of progress on LLW. In less distracting environments, she is quite good and checks in often. She was sniffy at first, so we tried to stick to paved areas (parking lots, wide paths, alleys, etc) and to focus on one route. This helped her learn what I wanted. We have now branched out to sidewalks and to a couple of other routes and she has continued to do well. She also responds really well to changing direction (lots of "this way"). She does get distracted easily, especially by movement (squirrels, birds, butterflies, blowing leaves but, most of all, other dogs). She responds well both to giving her time to observe and to head turns. She loves to be treated for check-ins! She seems fairly resilient but might be stressed by high traffic and loud noises that she doesn't know where they are coming from. For example, she was okay with a weed whacker across the street (after she watched for a few seconds) but seemed jittery because of a nail gun up above us. To sum up, she responds well to clear communication and going slow. I really enjoy her and think she'll make a nice dog.

Dream is very calm and can settle pretty well almost anywhere. She is not attention demanding and entertains herself very well. We are currently working on lunging at people as she walks by. She also has a habit of dealing with stress and excitement with her mouth, whether it be eating something on the ground or grabbing at people. It is not a "mean" bite. It is an "I am way too excited" bite and I do not know what else to do. She commonly will grab for a nearby toy when excited.  It only occurs with others. She does not bite at me out of excitement. I am not sure why. She also seems to listen to me so much better than anyone else.

ExerciseType: walks, play time, fetch, low key agility at home
GeneralComments: Over all China is a wonderful pup.  She is average in learning ability speed.  She settles nicely when out.  We have taken things very slowly from day one...not sure if she is up to speed where she should be in traffic, busy locations.  We worked on potty training, house manners, and kenneling a lot past 6 months.  We even work on leaving food on TV trays and coffee tables. China does not get into trash or chew anything, even when our own dog will carry around someones socks, China does not.  Same with furniture, we allow Georgia to get on furniture and China knows her place on her bed or blanket.  She LOVES to be anywhere I am, but her separation attachment has improved.  But given a choice, she would pick me over other dogs and play.  China does fine in other peoples homes.Things I worked on/still working on with her since day one, moving cars, moving or noise making novelty items.  Things we have mastered: potty outside. not in house or in kennel, and excepting the kennel when I am gone.  Still working on kennel when we are home.  I have worked a lot on simple sits and guided downs when out.  Body blocking has really helped her learn what is not for her.  We need to get back into commands like Go Place, Stay for longer.  But she knows them as well as back, touch, sit, down, stand, come.  Duration!!  Of course, this is me that needs to work on it.Need to start testing her in new locations more often.  We are getting out more now that I know I can trust her not to pee when inside places.Body handling is not where I would like it.  She loves everything touched and messed with but only if she comes to you and in a mellow mood.  Otherwise, she is wiggly at first then settles down.  Working on flash touch while out if she is anxious.There are things she needs work on, mentioned above.  I always look at homework or web wiki to find what to do.  I see improvement so I continue.

GeneralComments: Becka is a fun, smart, motivated and very persistent little girl who loves to work. She strikes a nice balance in terms of high energy when called for and an ability to settle without prompting. She can still become activated with unexpected items that may flit by her, like leaves or debris on a windy day, but I've noted that over time and with practice, she seems much more able to maintain control of her response. Becka is all about energy. She can be reactive to little yippy dogs that come out of nowhere (a common occurrence here at the beach in the height of summer) and scamper about, especially if they walk too closely. I find I have the best outcome if Becka remains in a sit as the little dog passes by - she's good about the check-in if I'm given enough time to create  a successful situation including distance and the sit.  Love this pup!!

FoodType: Hills Science Diet puppy large breed
GeneralComments: Becka's a sweet and very smart little pup. We continue to work on her activation when in new/ exciting settings and on windy days. Its not a huge issue - just one that I want to keep tabs on. My strategy is still toI slow things down by asking for "sit" on both sides of the door as a way to deflate - or- if inside, a quick 30 seconds in the crate. She's doing much better with transitioning from outside to in. With all the windy days we've been having, we're working distractions. Settling in the house is also a priority for me - she's doing great. She takes the initiative to find a chew toy and will settle quietly as I work away. Good girl!

ExerciseType: 2 mi. walks and play in yard
GeneralComments: We have not actually done home switches yet. Our only concern is Iko's jumping, she even sometimes jumps into place when asked to "heel" and will jump up on people when "saying hi" at times. She is easily corrected and will sit directly after jumping, waiting for a reward. Otherwise, she is an absolute delight, very connected and has learned every command that I have introduced to her so far. Every place that we have visited with Iko, people have been impressed with her obedience to commands.

No yes/no responses for some of the questions.  She seems to be doing well with most of the skills, but we are having trouble with stand.  We have been working on calm body handling and now are emphasizing feet because of the clipping.  We are working on out - she will drop toys, but won't always drop found items outside.

Ivan is a great puppy. Willing, happy, easy going. He did try to lick butter on the counter just this week. Back to the drawing board to make sure he never gets the opportunity again. It was in a moment of excitability just as I was taking the dogs out to get busy one by one first thing in the morning. But we can usually have food at his eye level and he is not interested in taking it and is great in restaurants and has been good at the other home on a swap. One thing to note- if he can see his reflection in a window (not a mirror) he sometimes barks at it. It will have to be when he is staring for a good while not when he passes by it on a walk. I think this is because he thinks the other dog is staring and perceives it as a challenge even though he is looking at himself. He is great everywhere and a nice companion with good initiative.

Henley is a nice pup. Needs work to build confidence and acclimate to noises. Taking your time with him has allowed him to make good progress.  Settles very nicely at work with me for 10 hours each day. Is able to get plenty of low key exposure and socialization at my job. I have really enjoyed starting Henley.

ExerciseType: Walking / running free in fenced in yard/
GeneralComments: Hadley showed some problems with confidence initially.   Also was not real good with body handling. When handling his hind quarters he would grab hands with mouth. We have worked on these and he continues to  gain confidence. He has improved with body handling  and allows us to pick him up, handle him, trim nails, etc.   He was very excited when I got him out of the kennel.  He is more reactive when I take him out VS Patti.  This excitement is reducing with training.  He settles very well in the house. I have him with me at my office daily, and he settles exceptionally well.  Greets and interacts extremely well with many different employees.  Exposure to new noises, environment without any noted concerns thus far.   On the third day we had him he strained his front foot when he came down on the side of the kennel and displayed limping for a week. My vet checked him out and nothing broken etc.  Basically rested him for a week. Minimal activity. This resolved itself but I have not allowed him to jump up or down getting into cars, or other similar elevations.  So besides his physical size as a pup, and my concern for impact on him from elevations, we are still picking him up to put into the car.    He is good on various under footings, wire, plastic, stones, sewer grates.  He gets along with our family dogs, we have overcome initial interaction problems, and there are still some times he needs a reminder, but overall his interactions are age appropriate.   He is influenced by his surroundings but is starting to gain focus, but it will obviously take more work.  Rides very well in the car, stays very quiet, is relaxed and can be by himself without fussing.      It is interesting that he gets so excited when I take him out of the crate, but does not get excited when I leave his presence in the car, or in the house.     His excitement level is reducing when exiting crate, and he regains his normal self far quicker than our first weeks.  Rides very well in car, settles , sleeps more of the time, is relaxed. No concerns if we leave him in car alone for various lengths of time.   Sleeps overnight in kennel, without fussing.  He is intelligent and well natured.

Hadley stayed with Anne Garretson for 7 nights. Aug 7 to 14th. Ann reports excellent house manners, walked well, interacted well with her dogs.  Ann is still in process of doing sitter report.  Hadley is learning very fast and we are seeing some very nice traits as he develops.  Loves to fetch, good energy.  Excellent in public.  Last weekend had him in a Starbucks for first time, and he remained in a down stay for 15 minutes without any problems. Does good in shopping malls, I have been increasing his exposure to people/distractions by taking him into mall at busy times.  He usually observes other dogs on walks without barking at them. Took him for his first bath at the Car/Dog wash facility and he did excellent.   He is gaining confidence as he matures.  Very nice personality, very interactive with family and numerous visitors to our residence.     During class after initial excitement he calms right down and can interact in class and normally not distracted by his k9 classmates.    Very healthy.  Duration is increasing, working hard on this.   Ken

ExerciseType: Walks/ Free run in back yard and enclosed garage
GeneralComments: Hadley is a very nice pup.  Excellent demeanor in the house. At GEB classes he gets excited upon first coming in but settles in shorter amount of time as he matures.  At the Christmas class did a drill which students and dogs made two lines, he did a down stay and of leash recall to me in solid form.  He remained focused and obeyed without deviance.   The efforts of the members of the Fingerlakes group for various classes / training settings are of great value and benefit to the pups. Does very well in various outings.  I have had him in many malls, stores, etc. Recently he was invited into the United Health Services Emergency Room, where we were in amongst the exam rooms.  He did excellent, many distractions, active movement of people, equipment, stretchers, many new noises.  Many people greetings. We have been asked to return as often as we can.  He does very well with greetings of people of all ages, including many very young toddlers. He now barks at times while inside crate in the car, I think its age related,  buts he like to ride in car.  Will now jump into the car and into his kennel without any problem.  Over the holidays had many people in the house and he was very good interacting with them.  He has great spirit energy and is a happy pup.  Follows us around the house and keeps track of where we are or are going in the house.The halti has been of great benefit in compliance and requires less physical effort to control pulling, barking.   I have been using the halti with less frequency but still use it when I anticipate encountering another dog, or barking situation.

She does get activated by flying insects. She seem to know the difference between work and home.  She settles very well at work, home is a little more work.  She is a joy to work with.

I think Fred is doing fine. I just need to work on things that I haven't done with the crazy events in our lives lately. Things will calm down and I will work on his place and house skills which is really a great thing for both of us. I think he is doing well for his age. Because he looks like an adult sometimes I expect more from him but then I think oh right, he is playing like an 8 month old. I think that he is very smart and knows what routines and patterns are so that he figures out what to do before or as I say the command. I am working on patience with that. I've seen him figure out some complex problem solving.--the dog gate was closed and he couldn't open it from the one side. So he went around to the slats in the stairs to go up, but he couldn't fit anymore since he is larger now. So he poked the gate from the other side while he was in the slats, the gate opened and he walked around and went up the open gate! I see him watching things in the sky or on shelves (appliances, etc) and I think he is accumulating info for future reference! I think this skill can work to a disadvantage when he watches bad behavior like Rigby so I would be cautious about him going somewhere where he can pick up "alternative" house manners!  I think our bond is better lately since I am paying more attention to him than I was. I feel connected but not as connected to him as usual. I think a little bit of that is him--maybe he is picking up cues from me that I haven't given him my 100%. But I am trying--just a little hard when you know down the road I have to give him up. Josefina was more affectionate and Fred is just more reserved with me. Body handling is fine though. I think he is a wonderful dog overall,

FoodType: Iams proactive health- smart puppy large breed
GeneralComments: Dania has made great progress in learning new skills since her last Walk & Talk.  Dania is a very happy dog who loves people and other animals. She has always loved her kennel and is a great napper & all-night-long sleeper, even sleeping through thunderstorms.  Dania no longer inappropriately chews on household items (other than socks.)  She also travels well and settles down immediately in her crate. [We have not practiced Dania riding in the front passenger seat to date.]  When in a learning zone, she follows all commands.  Dania & her raisers, still need to work on social skills, specifically when meeting & greeting new people at home or out and about.  We also need to work on lead pulling.*  When Dania gets close to new people or when picking up scents, Dania will repeatedly pull, but will eventually settle back into a listening zone.*Dania has adapted to wearing the muzzle while eating meals.  We have not progressed to actually having Dania wear it while walking on a lead.

Dania is very playful and loving.  When in the 'zone of learning,' Dania has the ability to master most skills.  However, we feel that we, as her raisers, have not been as consistent as possible in practicing certain skills with Dania.  First, due to the extreme cold conditions this winter, walking Dania to her 'Get Busy' area was very expedited and Dania often pulled on her leash to get back inside the house - which we allowed due to weather conditions.  Secondly, Dania loves to scavenge outside and is continually searching for leaves, twigs, pebbles, etc. anything on the ground.  She has been improving in both of these areas because we have been diligently practicing improving these skills (leash pulling and scavenging.)  Thirdly, Dania loves to chew & gnaw on inappropriate things such as people, furniture, and house fixtures.  We must keep a steady vigil on Dania at all times and cannot leave her unattended.  We recognize these concerns and are truly making a concerted effort to address them by being consistent in practicing these skills with Dania.  Thank you for your continued support.
She is a wonderful puppy.

ExerciseType: walks, catch & retrieve, tug, playing with other pups and running around in fenced yard
GeneralComments: Cindy is a joy to have.  As a first time raiser I am learning so much.  I try hard to make sure she gets all types of exposures and has adequate down time.  Love this girl!Her main two areas I continue to work on are:  Walking without Pulling - Cindy definitely needs time to check out new surroundings. She will sniff and smell and look all around new places we adventure out to.  Once she is comfortable she does quite well and we have made progress here.Also, Cindy loves people and is eager to please but occasionally gets over excited to see people.  We are making good progress here, by allowing her to greet people only when she has four on the floor or is in a sit/down.  She is finally getting the fact that she can't greet people unless she remains calm and is doing much better!Every day I look forward to our day together and love to watch her grow in confidence!

GeneralComments: Clive came to me a little over two months ago.  He has adjusted well to the new house although he was very activated for a few days as he settled.  He has improved significantly with settling in the house and in public.  He can successfully go to a restaurant for 1-2 hours with support - usually settles towards the end (takes a nap).  Because of my work and volunteer work, Clive attends alot of public functions and travels with me 1-2 hours in the car most days.  He is generally good at playdates but can pick out a pup/dog that he wants to 'hump'. He is improving with the cats.  Once moment he is laying next to them and the next moment he could be barking at them.  When he barks, I will separate/barracade him from cats and he gets the message.  Clive has strong foundation skills, is a pleasure to walk on leash, although when he's "had enough" he will start to chew on the leash.  I will then stop, unclip his leash and with his collar, do a guided down and wait for him to settle.  This usually works.  He is a very loving pup who wants to be with me at all times.  He loves to go for rides in the car and to go to work.  One of his favorite things to do is go to the mall.  He likes to run in the yard but not much of a fetcher.  When he's playing, he's not very good about come and out.  We've been working on "Out" and "Take It" and this seems to have help him learn to "Out" things in his mouth.  He is a sweet, happy,willing dog and doesn't seem to let anything 'bother' him.

GeneralComments: Brandon seems to be a soft male, never taking too many chances. Unfortunately he makes some poor choices.  I am trying to balance appropriate manners with building confidence while on socialization outings.  While at home I am trying to find what motivates Brandon.  He is very much on his own agenda and quickly grows tired of being with me and doing what I ask.  So I ask him to "work with me" for 20 minutes then give an hour of free time. Sometimes it turns into 2 hours of free time if he is sleeping.  We will get there.  I am enjoying the slower pace at which Brandon works!

ExerciseType: Walks, play w/ me and my dog, outings
GeneralComments: she has settled in very well, the settles are getting better, she does still bark or become restless if we try for more than 4 minutes. I keep them short and do them often, but if I talk with someone that is when she barks. Short settles do work for calming her down. Sniffing has calmed but every so often it crops up, she will become sniffy if she is excited. As I get to know her everything gets better, I just need to take things slow and let her process. She sleeps till 7am and can spend time in the kennel where she can see me and not see me and not bark, however she will yip on occasion. I am enjoying her very much, the Holidays and Harley will tell us more. She and Asti are now best of friends. Needs work on body handling her back feet in over.

Binzel is sweet and affectionate. His house manners have a way to go, but he has only been here for 2 weeks. He has made a lot of progress in that time. He doesn't get as much exercise and I wonder if that's contributing to his mischievous house manners, although he does seem to be a lower energy pup. He doesn't like going outside to play in the yard, probably because he sinks through the 4 feet of snow and he's freezing! On walks, we don't get very far since he has a lot of work to do to get to LLW. Hopefully, more training and better weather will improve his progress.

Binzel is good with obedience skills; my primary concern has been house manners and home stuff.   1.  On body handling, I can maneuver him into position and touch spots.  However I have been having trouble drying him with towels (mouths the towels and starts to play) and recently nail clipping (mouths the clipper / tries to play).  We have gone back to the first steps on nail clipping.  2.  When Binzel arrived he mouthed everything and we have been working on that by leaving out canned stuff and other things as well as appropriate toys, rewarding for choosing the right toys and ignoring stuff.  He has improved in this regard, but when he lapses he mouths specific places on walls and mouldings or grabs tissues/socks/handkerchieves/shoes.  We have been keeping him tethered to me 100% of the time at home to watch over this.  Sometimes he grabs stuff but has not destroyed anything since chewing the GPS and iPhone cords.  He can settle in the kitchen surrounded by canned goods without mouthing them (occasionally tries to jump up on me - see below).   3.  When he first arrived, he was OK in crate if I left the apartment but if I was home he would whine.  We have improved on this - the previous raisers suggested sterilized bones and frozen kongs.  I can now prepare breakfast and lunch with him in a crate not whining.   4.  Binzel sometimes tries to jump on me and on counters, a windowsill, and one stool (I dont have much other furniture). He can be goaded by the cat into chasing (but can be called back from it too by name response).  We have been working on this.  5.  Binzel sometimes mouths me (we stop play) or during intense play will mouth at fleece objects (jackets, blankets) or ball them up and try to mount them.  He also tries to mount my arm.   6.  We are wondering when it is appropriate to switch to 2 meals per day; and if it is appropriate to go to Iams adult or lamb and rice (several folks have suggested it).       7.  Health notes: Binzel gets hiccups often? Binzel is changing teeth; there appears to be a left upper incisor where the baby tooth is still in with the adult tooth being displaced.

This is subsiding. We  are working to keep her from getting over aroused ;  getting back into stores and public places now that her spotting has stopped and I am teaching her the "touch" game to engage her brain.

-Yahtzee is still sometimes slow at processing her environment.  She's much better after going to a place once though!  She's slow to respond to commands and isn't the most driven dog- whoever is handling her has to be a cheerleader.  I know some dogs are calmer because their raisers are chill but she's the result of me trying to make her an active, responsive dog and she's still lazy and slow-thinking (but I've come to really love it!).  She's not much of a tester though so when she's slow to respond it's because she's distracted or because she's thinking through everything.  She's very dog distracted (stares or pulls towards dogs, doesn't bark though) and can watch a dog walk down the street for a long time before offering a check in- I've started asking her for them sooner but if she gives me the check in it's a very quick one and she refuses to take treats.  -She seems more distracted by things (people walking, sounds) at night/in the dark and takes a longer time to check in/re-focus....I'm not sure if that's normal and I just didn't notice it with Aurora? -She had a fear of grated under footings right before going into heat and was still a bit weary of them after heat.  We've worked a lot on it and she's much better, but you can tell it's something that's been worked on and if she's stressed she really has to be encouraged to go over them.  -She randomly stops walking sometimes and just stands there- I think it's usually when we're in places she knows but doesn't feel like going?  Although I'm not completely sure.  I usually just verbally encourage her to keep going and she does-Yahtzee is very low key and her absolute favorite activity is doing nothing with me :P  She loves snuggling on her terms and is so sweeeet about everything.  She's not persistent about things-once you tell her she can't have/do something she just moves on.

ExerciseType: Walks 3 or 4 times a day, plays with my dog
GeneralComments: Wrigley is an amazing puppy. He is a laid back, easy going dog that stops and thinks before jumping into a situation. He leans quickly and retinas it. He is friendly to everyone and everything he meets. Having a dog already, has been a blessing and a curse for Wrigley. A blessing in that Wrigley has learned how to get along with other animals and has ample daily exercise. But a curse as my dog has taught him some bad house manners which we are working to improve. I can't tell you what a joy it is to have Wrigley a part of our family and how honored my family is to be a part of this organization. As I learn better ways of training him, he learns to be a a better behaved dog.  I am grateful to the Nashua group which meets every Sunday (when there hasn't been snow!). Everyone has been so helpful and supportive.

ExerciseType: Because of his broken toe, he has been limited in physical exercise. He does more slow, short walks and lots of Kongs.
GeneralComments: He doesn't seem to generalize well. He doesn't always seem to carry his "good" habits to the puppy sits.His house manners are fine, but not the skills we've been working on, such as pulling and crate tolerance. Although at home, he will go in by himself just to relax.  He has learned to calm down a lot. It takes him about 10 to 15 minutes at an outing to get his bearings and figure out what is expected of him. If we go in to a building, go out, and come back in, he does much better the second time. I usually find that he has to "get busy" shortly after arriving at a new location. Our outings have been very limited for the past 6 weeks due to his cast. We have not be into any public buildings until yesterday when we went to Pet Smart. I am hoping to get a clean bill of health from the vet next week so we can start visiting places again.

Wrigley has come a long way. He is excellent when he is "on," especially in stores, restaurants, and other social events like parades or Christmas tree lightings, etc. I will sometimes go into a place and if he isn't "there" yet, will walk out and back and he then gets it. If there is another dog present, however, he seems to forget that I am there. But we have been working on this with Kerry. He now can sit at the bus stop when our neighbor walks by with his dog and will ignore him. All in all, Wrigley knows exactly what he is suppose to do. He is very smart. But there are times when he "pretends" not hear. He is getting better. Even if he does break away, say, and goes to visit another dog, he will say hi and comes back to me before I go get him. He used to totally choose to ignore me (or the person with the leash). Wrigley LOVES to play and be around other dogs and people who will play with him. Like I said before, he is an opportunist and will take advantage if it suits him. My one concern, unrelated to this survey, is his fearlessness. He seems to have no sense of danger or caution, especially around cars, and will plunge headlong into any situation if not restrained.

ExerciseType: walking, running, playing with other dogs
GeneralComments: Wrangler is a great pup. He definitely can be quirky at times, but I am very proud of the way he has overcome every learning curve that has come his way over the past year. He's definitely ready for the next step in his journey and I can't wait to see what his future holds. It has been a complete and utter joy to be his puppy raiser.

Such a nice puppy! He is even tempered, patient, sweet, and an all around fun puppy. He is SUPER food motivated, almost to a fault. Sometimes he finds it hard to focus because he works himself up over the food so much. I have to be very careful with my use of food, and that will become even more important as he gets older. He is very willing to connect and cooperate, and I am really enjoying him. I am pleased with his progression, and I have high hopes for his future!

Likewise because of the weather, business travel and our own illness we have only had a few visitors over to meet Woodrow.  Consequently his socialization beyond our home is almost non existent. This is where he needs to improve and we hope that now with his quarantine lifted we can get him out for walks and in town experiences.

Overall he is doing wonderful and has been a joy to our family, but he needs work in walking on his leash and not getting into the cat/other dog food which he has been caught doing several times recently. Also chasing birds is an issue that I am not sure how to address.

Rumple is making progress.  He's improved most in his ability to make a connection with people.  He's relaxing and open to learning because we mix a lot of play within "work" sessions.  He responds best to play with a squeak toy in conjunction with treats.  Rumple might do better at IFT and GEB training with a squeak toy as a reward in addition to usual food rewards.  Rumple has strong dog reactions but mostly because he just wants to say hi.  When he is able to greet another dog he can easily move on.  Rumple continues to be body sensitive although he's made some progress.  He can be inhibited while wearing his vest, although some times it does not bother him.  This area continues to be a mystery because sometimes it is not an issue at all and sometimes he is clearly bothered by body issues.  Rumple may be a candidate for the running program because he is clearly the happiest and most responsive when jogging on the open road.

ExerciseType: Walking, ball play, hide and seek,
GeneralComments: Rafiki is a loving shepherd who likes to exercise and use his mind.  He is inquisitive and curious as well as smart.  He recognizes patterns where we walk and can remember them, thus having us change direction.  He is willing to please and is very food motivated.  He has adjusted well to going out to different locations given the cold weather.  He is improving considerably in walking on the lead and I have improved my technique to make him successful.  Often his curiosity can get the better of him so he might chew the edge of the carpet.  We are working on this part of his house manners.  He comes on command and loves to be engaged in hide and seek.  He likes the students at Hawken and is learning to greet them well.  He handles the crate incredibly well.  He is learning to settle on his own and last night was able to lie down on the floor with me while reading.  We have worked hard on touch and rewarding such body handling.  He is a sweet puppy and we are loving having him.
Rafiki still has some challenges with distractions - things in motion, other dogs/animals, but is getting much, much better.

GeneralComments: Porsche knows all her commands and has good house manners for the most part. Porsche does very well staying connected in public places and I have been able to take her to stores, the mall and even concerts. Porsche does well with greetings however, sometimes she will jump if she is in an excited or energetic mood. Porsche has gone on several sits as I have to travel for work and the feedback I have gotten is positive in terms of her adjusting to new surroundings and having good house manners. Porsche is very social and enjoys meeting other people or dogs.

ExerciseType: Daily walks and play with other dogs

I would say her biggest distraction so far is other dogs however, she is getting better in that area as she will stay connected with me when we encounter other dogs on the walking trails.

ExerciseType: walks, free running in fenced yard, fetch,
GeneralComments: Patricia and I are doing well on all basic commands and building duration.  She is accustomed to 100s of feet walking by, stairs, fire drills, gym class and small, curious children. We have been working hard on walking without pulling and staying engaged on the leash.  In familiar areas, we are doing well.  In new environments, we are struggling.  This week, we are really trying to not jump on people when they approach and remain less accelerated when being pet.  We need work here.  I am also a little unclear on the transition from luring to not luring to get things to work.  We missed the first 4 classes(I didn't pick her up until 11.5 weeks) and I feel we may have missed some very basic tips then.  She is a wonderful, curious, confident puppy and has a great personality.
Patricia was in heat most of August.  Swaps fell through at the last moment.

Patricia is a wonderful dog.  She has a constant undercurrent of energy that at times makes it difficult to settle.  She sort of goes all day and then sleeps all night.  She needs a lot of mental stimulation during the day. She is great with children, never barks, and loves to cuddle at night.  A professional trainer needs to channel her energy into "working" at something.  She responds very well to a firm, consistent handler and enjoys food reward more than body handling.  She is a very fast learner and understands commands really well.  She keeps us very busy!

Oleta showed fear of large rock in water this past week.  We hung out for 10 minutes whereby  she gradually figured things out and  then enjoyed playing in the   water and going on the rock.Also  the past 10 days or so she acts like she never learned commands.  I continue to be firm  and consistent. She tends to bark at deer in back yard if I am not near her.  May bark, whine and/or get excited if someone opens door to come inside the house.She loves people and tends to go towards them when we are working. I remind her to stay focused.

GeneralComments: Ogden is maturing every day and is less and less distracted by outside stimulus. When he gets into the groove, he works really nicely and isn't even phased by other dogs. He has off days where everything distracts him, not sure why. He is unsure about new environments or when things change in familiar environments. He needs lots of exercise and doesn't settle easily, even when he's tired. He has excellent house manners, but is always alert and ready to go.He only seems to relax after the sun goes down.
Ogden can be very distracted and has a high energy level. While this makes working with him more difficult than what we are used to, we are seeing a steady improvement in his behavior.

When "working" Oksana does very well.  People can pretty much walk right over top of her and she will just watch them.  She is very, very alert and struggles to stay settled so we have taken her to church sunday school and coffee shops (both places where we can get up and move around/leave easily).  She stays fairly attentive to me, but wants to be entertained.  I generally bring a chew/bone with me so that she can focus on that and chew out any anxieties that she has.   Car riding is MUCH improved.  She recently starting loading on her own without treats, tori or us to lure her in.  I still heavily treat her with a carrot or a nice chew in the car.  Yesterday she traveled all the way to Cape Charles (1 hour) without any vomiting/salivating.  She did bark on the bridges.  Don't know if there was a difference in the sound the car was making or if she didn't understand why we were high above the water.  I was driving so couldn't really watch and figure it out.  The back seat is her preferred place to ride.  When greeting people when we are out she is usually fairly good.  Sometimes she'll try to jump but tends to be very well mannered.  At home it is a different story.  When she is excited she barks/sings and will jump repeatedly.  We have tried blocking her so she can't get at the person, we have tried blocking her with our knees she she jumps to deflect her.  We have tried holding her in a sit until she calms.  The holding her in a sit seems to be somewhat effective.  But there has not been any real improvement here.  She is highly, HIGHLY athletic and jumping is part of her expression of exuberance.  When out playing and given the chance to really run, she tends to bounce initially before she "settles" into that very streamlined graceful run that GSDs have.  We see a lot of bounce in her play with Tori.  Oksana is a fearless dog in a lot of ways.  It really doesn't occur to her to have issues with underfootings, heights etc.  She is incredibly intelligent and exuberant about most of what she encounters.  There is a silliness to her personality which is quite endearing (But in a refined GSD kind of way, not silly they way you see it in a lab).  And she wants to express everything she is seeing/feeling.  So we get a lot of alert barks about the world around us/her.  She will bark at Tori incessantly if Tori is playing with (or more likely cuddling with) a toy she wants.  When first let out of her crate int he morning or when we have been out there is a lot of squealing.  Its double the fun with both her and Tori are excited and fussing.  Her personality is quite lovely, but really her biggest issues are the (at times) incessant barking, the jumping and the play biting.  I feel like everything else is coming along and improving at a reasonable rate for her.

Mitchell is a great pup. Lovable, very cuddly and affectionate. He demands lots of attention vs. being able to self-occupy himself for long with chew toys. Plays a great game of fetch.  Excellent with all basic commands; less so with manners. Barking at us is still an issue from the very beginning. All solutions a temporary fix. Counter surfing a problem; worse as he grows and can reach more items. We have gates up, closed doors, and take pains not to leave things out, but he still is destructive.  Also, is a very early riser, (5 am), but we really try not to feed him earlier than 6 am.  Adjusting the time he eats at night or adding exercise in the evening doesn't seem to make any difference. With the warmer weather, we plan to increase his exercise time, so that should help.  He is a good sleeper and napper.

GeneralComments: Maury is a pleasure to have in the house. He has an enjoyable energy level and has fantastic house manners. Maury came to us as a home switch in mid July. He seemed to lack confidence and showed signs of stress in new situations. We have tried to give Maury a variety of socialization experiences and believe that he has gained some confidence. He seems to be a "happier" pup than he was (he has gained skills in playing appropriately with other pups, and loves to do so). He still however, sometimes shows signs of stress/lack of confidence when exposed to new or particularly challenging environments (drooling, yawning, and "flopping" onto the floor). Stairs, in particular, have been a challenge for Maury, but inconsistently so. We are unclear as to whether this is due to a lack of confidence or coordination or both. We have seen improvement in loose leash walking and connecting with his handler. We are enjoying our time with Maury very much.

ExerciseType: Walks, Group play with other GEB dogs when we get the chance (none recently due to the holidays)
GeneralComments: I am mostly pleased with Iris's progress. The two areas that I  am currently concerned about are  1) stairs and 2) barking.   I think Iris was doing well on stairs until just recently. Now, she is either tentative, or rushing, bunny hopping - everything but calm. I have gone back to phase 1.  I appreciate the videos. It's great to have resources to refer to. On the other hand, I don't think I have the skills to deal with barking. I was glad to see the issue will be addressed this year. I hope it happens soon!  I don't think Iris barking is excessive, but I am not comfortable with it. I feel myself tense up (especially in places like the mall).

GeneralComments: Fletcher is a great puppy. He is very social and connected. His tolerance for distraction has really improved in the past few months. His impulse control as well. He learns quickly, pays attention, loves to work and does very well on outings. He excites easily, but quickly settles. Loves everybody. Likes to lick people, a lot. We have been working on that, but the behavior is persistent. He can still occasionally dribble pee when his bladder is full if he gets excited, so I always empty him out right before putting on his vest. His housemanners are excellent - I have been leaving him loose in the house this past month and he has done very well, though a bit more excited than when he stays in the crate. He has been a delight to raise and I think he will make some lucky graduate a wonderful guide.

GeneralComments: Farley has been consistently improving in almost all aspects of his training. Overall he is a very sweet obedient dog that has charmed all those he has met, whether two or four legged.

Not sure what a home switch is but we have not had him stay anywhere else but with us so far.  We have noticed a change in is behavior - takes him less time at home to settle but there are times when he is very rambunctious. Those times seem to be getting fewer but we are keeping a close eye on it. We try to play as soon as we get home as he is in his kennel all day long. Today was a funny day - I was going to work but John was working at home. I usually leave last and kennel him and even though John was home as soon as I put my coat on - he ran into the kennel.

Farley has been a very easy dog to raise thus far. He listens very well to both of us, It seems when he is stubborn it is his choice and he knows the difference. That is happening less and less. We have taken him to public events often and he behaves well when there is a lot of activity around. He is curious but always polite to both people and animals. .

Elijah is super smart, independent, wonderful, sweet pup. He likes chase and to figure things out- meaning, he'll drop a bone somewhere for the fun of figuring out how to get it back; he'll take a toy to the far side of the yard and wait for someone to come toward him (not happenin') His housemanners have improved dramatically in the last 2 weeks. I credit management, dragging leash for the past 3 months, intentional training so he learned what it a puppy toy and what isn't, his recent long sit with Carol R, and persistence. We've picked up all the toys. Some rotate for him to play with on his own. Other toys we use for play together. The bucket of toys is available for an hour every few days so he can dig around in it.. We also encouraged bone chewing, first with someone holding the bone. Now often he'll choose to chew on his own. We are also focused on settling here there & everywhere. That too shows improvement.  Dog distraction is a challenge - tho manageable. We're working on that as well.  Thanks for letting me raise this pup!

Elijah is a good guy. He can be nearly perfect in every way, in the house, and out and about. Dog distraction is a challenge tho, my experience, with support, he'll work with me. It's on me to be vigilant and make sure he has time to figure out that the dog 'over there' is not available to greet. Frontal approaches on leash on the same side walk would be unwise. He's smart, funny, engaging, sweet... :-) He also has ideas about what he thinks is fun &given the opportunity will take advantage.  He is still noticeably stimulated by movement, more so if he's already uncertain. Thanks for letting me raise this guy!

GeneralComments: Dandy is a very sweet puppy and we are enjoying raising him.  For the most part he is doing well, I think.  He has gotten more attentive to us I think, and enjoys pleasing us.  He is fairly laid back and I sometimes wonder if he is too much so.  He can be pretty active but also can be pretty "laid back". GeneralComments: Yeoman is a bright, cheerful boy, but is probably a bit immature.  We see signs of maturity improving, and then signs of regression.  It is pretty much "dealing with the dog you have that day" scenario. Yeoman is developing a very nice LLW, so walking with him is quite nice.  He could definitely use more outings with similar age/energy level dogs to help develop his dog social skills.  Unfortunately, his exposure to cats will be limited since our 19 YO cat passed away recently.  All things considered, he is a good boy and enjoys doing the training and work.

Overall, Yeoman is a sweet boy and a good dog.  We are concerned about his ability to self modulate and regain focus in stessfull situations.  His good days are good, but his bad days usually require us to "take him out of the game."  We've seen some improvement in his ability to play with other dogs in structured play, but it does take due diligence on the handlers part to keep the play going in a positive direction.  We are still seeing alot of pestering behavior with dogs not interested in playing with him, i.e. he just can't take no for an answer.An outing today at WalMart went well, but it did require use of body blocking to refocus his attention on his handler.  Did well with people going by but items on shelves were more distracting.

GeneralComments: Yvonne has a small concern of going UP stairs. She does fine going down, but runs when going up. I don®t think it®s a fear, but more of that she can®t figure out how to ™Use_ her back legs slowly. So I have been working on that with her by playing with toys mid-stair and giving her KONGS mid-stair. She does well in class besides being disconnected when entering the room. She is doing better with her body sensitivity. She is fine with wearing pretty much anything besides a life jacket [perhaps because it is heavier than the t-shirts, etc I have her wear]. So I have been having her wear it around the house a lot lately. So far we have had no problems with jumping on beds or couches. People have been the hardest thing with Yvonne, she loves people and becomes very excited and jumps. I haven®t tried the new thing where she is standing when being pet. I think that might help her. She®s gotten really good at settling while I study, she is able to do it for 45 minutes at home.  Thanks! Look forward to seeing you at Walk & Talk!

We've taken her all kinds of places on outings and are finding 45 minutes to be about her settling limit before getting restless.  She hasn't done any counter surfing here in over a month so we've been letting her have the run of the house, but there were a few issues on sits.  It mostly seems like a curiosity thing.  She doesn't go for food but instead likes to check out higher surfaces for interesting things such as wallet & keys at Janet's, chess piece at the Gentiles' and stuffed animals on a bed at our son's.  She then either leaves the items on the floor or brings them to you rather than chewing them up.

Vanda is a great dog.  I have truly enjoyed working with her and I hope she will be successful at her IFT.  At this point I think her house manners are very good, she has an excellent temperment and is almost always calm and well behaved in the house.  I trust her to behave with the exception of dirty socks in the laundry room, which continue to be an issue about once every few weeks and assume she is finding them by smell. Since she is my first dog and we have been learning together, I try not to compare her with other dogs in the program but from what I have observed I worry about the following issues for her training:  1.  Does not always come when called in the yard because she is having too much fun running around. 2.  Overly excited about other dogs.  3.  Overly excited greeting people. 4.  Often gets distracted on walks by smells, dogs, people, sounds etc. but depends on the situation.  Hopefully we will continue to work on these issues over the next few months and she will continue to improve.

She had a hard time calming down in class and barked a good bit.

Squire is making phenomenal progress and is regularly complimented on how well behaved, friendly, and tolerant he is.  Skills I would like to target with him are walking in novel places (he does a lot of sniffing the ground and some light pulling) and appropriate/ calm behavior around other dogs (especially passing on the sidewalk).  He has made the most growth in settling/ not requiring as much attention when we are sitting at home or work, learning new restrictions in our new summer school location (where he can go, what he can touch), and walking nicely on a leash/ decreasing lunging.I'm very proud of his work.

ExerciseType: Walking, running on long leash, playing with tug toys
GeneralComments: Sebastian has made a lot of improvement over the past couple months and his walking especially has gotten a lot better. Most of the time, he is very attentive and enjoys working. However, occasionally he needs a play break while on a walk. If he isn't able to get some energy out, he gets very hard to work with (inattentive, urge to run around, occasional chewing of his leash - obvious signs of stress). We try our best to let him play or run before going on walks to avoid this behavior. Recently, however, he has been getting stressed much more easily. Long walks are becoming harder for him and we aren't particularly sure why. It has only been happening for about 2 weeks, so we were thinking it could just be a hormonal thing, as he is around 8 months of age. We would love to know if this is something we can work on.

Scarlett is a wonderful girl.  Her primary raiser has done a great job with her.  She is willing to try anything and loves to put her jacket on to go on socializations.   She is pleasant to walk and will lead the way with a steady, quick pace.  She does like to sniff, but if given sniff breaks during walks it can be minimized.  She needs to be watched with people greetings because she will jump if if she gets too excited. She is an extreme chewer, but only chooses dog toys.  She can not be left unattended when chewing because she will go through any and everything.  Scarlett is highly dog distracted and it is hard for her to settle when close to other dogs.

ExerciseType: walks, play with dogs, frisbee fetch
GeneralComments: Radcliffe is a low energy, well behaved dog. He certainly is an adolescent now.  He has started marking on walks - doesn't even have to be near anything vertical.  He catches a scent and squirts!  He had a very mild dog distraction, but now needs more distance from other dogs to remain calm.   And he is much more distracted by smells now.  My concerns are his traveling when pooping - hard for a sighted person to pick it up.  Also, since Teddy came, Radcliffe has shown more body sensitivity - growls when he is accidently touched on the paws.  I can body handle him no problem, including paws.  I have noticed this in the last 6 weeks or so.

GeneralComments: Orleans is a high drive, busy girl. She's loving and affectionate. She does not settle well or easily especially if there are distractions. She can easily get very excited and has trouble focusing. She is pretty body sensitive, doesn't like her jacket or the leash draped over her back. Frequently once I have her jacket on her and we are still at the back of my car, she tries to jump back in her crate. Every day is a new day full of excitement for her. She hardly ever jumps on me but when my adult son and/or husband come home, it's like she's starting over with learning not to jump. As a result, she greets them while I'm holding her drag line. Once they are in the house for awhile, she's ok.

ExerciseType: goes to work daily, walks, play in fenced yard
GeneralComments: Mathias is a CHALLENGE! He came to us at about 4 months old with some rather bad habits (jumping, not coming, not responding to his name, and treating my teenage boys like chew toys). He has improved in the two or three months that we have had him, but he is still not an easy pup.   He appears to me to be rather insecure with new experiences - though he does improve with time and repeated exposure. He is highly reactive and this is getting worse lately. If I know someone is arriving, I can keep him focused and quiet, but if someone comes in the house unannounced or knocks on the door, Mathias erupts. He is also starting to bark at noises outside or even occasionally in the house. We do the best we can to redirect and get him focused, but it is not easy. His dog reactivity is getting worse as well. He is not aggressive at all, but highly reactive and barky when he sees another dog.  When out in public - interestingly - Mathias is very good. He is quiet and generally well mannered. I just started taking him into stores briefly and took him to church for the first time this past weekend. He was restless, but did better than I thought he would.  Overall, I find Mathias to be a rather odd mix of insecure, but bull headed and tenacious at the same time.

GeneralComments: Mathias is a CHALLENGE! He came to us at about 4 months old with some rather bad habits (jumping, not coming, not responding to his name, and treating my teenage boys like chew toys). He has improved in the two or three months that we have had him, but he is still not an easy pup.   He appears to me to be rather insecure with new experiences - though he does improve with time and repeated exposure. He is highly reactive and this is getting worse lately. If I know someone is arriving, I can keep him focused and quiet, but if someone comes in the house unannounced or knocks on the door, Mathias erupts. He is also starting to bark at noises outside or even occasionally in the house. We do the best we can to redirect and get him focused, but it is not easy. His dog reactivity is getting worse as well. He is not aggressive at all, but highly reactive and barky when he sees another dog.  When out in public - interestingly - Mathias is very good. Imari is a very friendly, high energy pup. She is great with her commands. She had been attending school with me every day during the school and was great in those situations. She learned how to appropriately greet people which is hard for her exhuberant personality.However, she seems to show great anxiety when around dogs that she does not live with. She seems to be getting a bit better when walking the neighborhood. However, if in the presence of a dog or other dogs for any extended period of time, becomes overwrought and uncontrollable. Class is a perfect example in that she could not settle long enough to complete any task asked of her. Since she is a very strong dog, it becomes difficult for me to control or handle her.Imari also benefits greatly from repeated exposure to all new situations. She has been to lots and lots of places and various kinds of places and situations, and the more she repeats the same scenarios, the more confident she becomes.She is a great dog and I hope can find a situation that will work for her.

fetch, walks, tug, playing with other dogs
GeneralComments: Fergus has definitely been more challenging for us than our last GEB puppy, however he has many strengths.  He is excellent at the vets office I work at, he is tethered to my desk and is always within eyeshot/earshot of other animals.  He acclimated to the work environment quickly and he settles nicely there.  He is very treat motivated and learns new commands quickly.  He is wonderful with the kids at home and has fit into our routine nicely.  He loves riding in the passenger floorboard of the car.  His is a big boy, and very strong, so it is difficult to control him when he wants to charge after another dog on walks.  As long as I catch him before he sees it, we do fine with me distracting him.  He is afraid of walking over grates which we are slowly working on.  He will sit or lay near or partially on them, but does not want to walk across them.  He is still a scavenger, we have been working hard on that by telling him out before he even goes for something as Jodi directed us to do and also reworking areas until he is no longer distracted by whatever may be on the ground.  WWP has been an issue but he is making improvements here with short distances.  We love how snuggly he is and how he tries to climb into your lap when you sit down.  He loves to be near us and we just adore him.

ExerciseType: Walking, Fetch, Hide and Go Seek, pup play 1-2x per week
GeneralComments: Cherish is working hard to be a good girl, and I've seen her make some very impressive strides since I've had her. She still activates quickly but has become much more proficient at processing her stress and returning to the green zone in a reasonable amount of time. She takes stress cues easily from her handler, so I have had the most success using a very moderate tone while working with her as she can become activated by exuberant praise. With practice, she has become much better at working in new locations while minimizing her stress, but she needs small slices and outings in new places have to be kept short in order for them to be good experiences. Her dog distraction is still very much present but she's getting better at choosing to return to her handler instead of attempting to reach the other dog. She is much better behaved when she is well exercised (30 min in the morning, 30 min at lunch, 30 min after work, generally 30 min in the evening) and when she is offered ample opportunity to exercise her resting energy level is quite pleasant.

Vern has made a lot of improvements in the things I struggled with since the last walk and talk.  I find his settling at home is awesome.  His barking at our dog has pretty much stopped and if he does bark a "uh oh" is all he needs as a reminder.  Our meeting and playing with a 2 and 5 year old went really well with supervision, so he wouldn't get too excited we asked a lot of the kids not to run and scream.  He visits a nursing home every week and is very comfortable there.  The ladies even saw a great improvement.  We play with 2 pups weekly in the program and it is always positive, we even get a pack walk in and for the most part it isn't too sloppy.  My biggest concern is Verns excitement when he sees people.  That is our main focus at the moment and we are looking forward to our W & T and hopefully some more improvements.
