ExerciseType: playing with other dogs, running, walking
GeneralComments: Vincent is a very interesting dog. He is very inhibited and has very low motivation and drive. I think the world can be overwhelming for him at times, but it can be difficult to recognize this immediately because he is very inhibited. Consequently, from a management perspective he does very well and often looks like he is doing fine when he is actually checked out or exiting the think and learn zone. I am constantly walking a fine line between not letting him get away with being lazy, but also not pushing him too hard and causing him to check out. I think he has difficulty regulating his stress, and consequently doesn't show any initiative. He is constantly looking to me for the answers. On the bright side, he is a super smart dog and a fast learner. He is also great practice for me in terms of reading dog body language because he is very hard to read. Overall, I think he is a very soft dog who needs a ton of support. I make it worth it for him to show motivation, but he is very inconsistent. My hope for him is that as he continues to get older, I can continue to help him work on his self-regulation and then maybe he will find the world more manageable.

GeneralComments: Triton remains a sensitive soul- He is blessed with a strong desire to please and a love of interaction- He is a joy both out and about town, as well as a good housemate. He is maturing nicely. The one thing I have noticed consistently throughout his raising is that he does best with small slices and followed by repeating exposures- with play breaks and rest periods back in a spot of security such as car or home. He remains a "build up" pup- and needs support when he makes a poor choice- or might have a tendency to shut down. I enjoy him immensely (probably because he is a much different temperament than many I have raised- so he keeps me thinking :) ) (One other note- on his pupsits- the sitters report he takes some time to settle into their homes and completely relax; however- when playing pass the pup or switching handlers on outings- he will cheerfully work with whoever is showering him with affection) :)

GeneralComments: More air sniffing than in the past. Needs a refresher working outside since we have had to do mostly indoor outings during the winter. Still needs to be reminded to play nicely and get a toy though she is much better! Will sometimes growl over high value toys with other dogs but will stop if corrected.  We don't use treats anymore for walking nicely (haven't for many months now). I've been trying to stop when she starts to pull or we change direction or do the head turn. Sometimes walking faster helps her.  Starling's fantastic in the house! She's also great at settling. She's used to spending the majority of the day out with me doing things or at least riding along in the car. Sometimes she whines in the house if she thinks we're being boring.    We are still practicing body handling and wearing things. If she has on something that touches her chest and butt she is fine, but if it is just on her butt sometimes she gets upset.

ExerciseType: Walk, play with homeboy Scout, tug, swim, retrieve
GeneralComments: Omaha is a generally calm, willing, easy dog to raise. He shows independent thought and will do as asked once he feels comfortable. He can be a little impatient and self-release from sits, but redirects well. He is well-behaved in the office and well-loved by all who meet him.  Rick notes that he seems to pass gas more frequently than other dogs we have raised (e.g. when asked to sit). Though I have not noticed this I work him in noisier settings. It might be residual to his Giardia.  He has manageable dog and people distraction, but otherwise shows nothing which would rule out a future as a guide.  We will miss him when he goes up!!

walk, pay with other dogs, play with my kids
GeneralComments: Grant has never been a super confident puppy. He's always been a bit cautious, but would check things out in his own time. However, he's become scared of many sounds. For instance, he never minded the vacuum cleaner, but now he's spooked by it. I always make sure he has the opportunity to leave the room before I vacuum, and he always decides to leave. He may or may not check it out later when it's off and I leave it in the corner. A few days ago my son was playing with motorized hot wheel cars that run on a track. He heard the sound of the cars and ran out of the room into his crate. He's never been bothered by the cars before. We immediately turned it off and put it in a corner. My son has been playing with it when he's far away from Grant. Now Grant is not bothered by the toy at all and will walk next to it. He was troubled a few days ago when he heard the sound of aerosol stay can. W've been spaying it when he's far away from us, and he's clearly less disturbed. His reactions to noises are unpredictable. A heavy book recently fell close to his head, and he never even looked up (not bothered). He's not scared of traffic/construction noises. I think his fearfulness started when we were in a bathroom at a restaurant and a loud automatic hand dryer started. We left immediately. The sound of the dryer and air blowing profoundly affected him. He's an extremely calm dog, so it's easy to see when he's disturbed. He starts shaking, waging his tail, pulling his leash and whimpering. A few days after the blow dryer incident we went to a hospital to pick up medical records. He was fine at first and then became agitated. I still have no idea what spooked him (there was nothing obvious like a loud noise or unfamiliar object). Again, we left immediately. I haven't taken him into a building since that time. He stayed with an experienced raiser for 5 days, and she worked with him. She didn't find any specific triggers either. We've been hanging out in parking lots or shopping centers and walking in new places. He's great on those outings. At home we try to anticipate what will upset him and make sure he has the opportunity to leave the room.  He is generally good with under footings and will walk on most textures. He gets a little bothered if the under footing makes strange noises.   He can be indecisive. He understands basic commands and is compliant, but takes a few seconds to think through the process.   He's also a sensitive dog. He gets upset when we get upset (thin skinned). Therefore, we stay calm and never raise our voices. We give him tons of positive feedback.   His house manners are wonderful.   Anyhow, I'm trying to help him regain his confidence. He's a sweet dog with a great temperament.

GeneralComments: Our other challenge area is dog distraction.  We have gone on several outings this quarter with other dogs (Home Depot, Fair Oaks Mall and the Gym with 4 or more other raisers and dogs, Kingstowne with Ingrid & Colleen and the Marine Corp Museum with her sister Frances & Melissa).  Figgie is totally focused on the other dogs.  Distance from them brings check-ins to me but if we approach them she will pull on the leash to be nearer to them and does not walk with a loose leash.  She can pack walk with them but definitely leans and pulls toward them. On walks, she will focus on dogs approaching us or across the street.  If they are approaching, I will walk off the path to the side and she will remain in a sit until they pass.  She is will also follow me if there is enough distance.

GeneralComments: Erie is smart, confident, and athletic.  She is also persistent.  She has been very healthy.   Erie has good house manners.  She loves to explore and loves human interaction.   Erie has exhibited difficulty with self-modulation and can be very demanding of attention. We see difficulty remaining settled, particularly in the late afternoon and early evening. We have seen improvement in the area of self-control and settling and continued improvement seems a reasonable prediction.  Also, she tends to perform better in this regard when she is out in public, wearing her vest, than when she is at home or other less structured situations.  The RM has provided substantial assistance in working with us on Erie®s ™improvement opportunities_; additional coaching/assistance is greatly appreciated.    Erie seems to us to be a dog that is designed to be a working dog, given her confidence, intelligence, and persistence.

FoodType: Purina Pro Plan large breed formula
ExerciseType: walking, slow jogging, playing with toys with me and playing with mellow lab
GeneralComments: a pleasantly energetic and responsive pup.   playful and  fun companion.  Easy going.  connects very readily and then rearing to go with appropriate moves.   She knows her skills and needs for handler to move with confidence in her.  devoted and affectionate .   On and Off Button excellent in most situations.   Sometimes playing with certain dogs, she gets excited and play turns rough and  she  needs help with Off button.    Once given the support , she settles with a  shake off.    With two transitions from sitter to class setting, she was unable to participate in class appropriatly.   she was totally distracted by other dogs.     As her handler , I was not able to be present . I was so surprised by behavior and couldn't get out of my own way .  Another handler took her and she settled  somewhat/    We are paying attention to transitions with her. However    she does really well when other people work her !   even people who are new to  GEB protocol.    I REALLY appreciate the collaboration with what we see and  the teaching and  support of Pat and Lee-Anne. I think that this little peanut is a winner.   a lovely house companion and traveling companion.   Incredible with grandson 4 yrs. old with downs syndrome.   He leads her around until she says.......Enough!   and she  lies down to end the walk.    What  a girl..... a mind of her own for sure.     My gratitude for yet another wondeful visitor along the way in my life!   I love her and  the  experience   is more alive today than ever.    with gratitude

GeneralComments: Secret has been very mellow since she started her Heat. She is such a joy to have around. She and Manny still get into squabbles together but are easily redirected with a toy. She did very well with our son and his family's visit over the Holidays which included a little puppy who liked to antagonize Secret and then jump up on the couch where she knew Secret would not go. By the end of the visit, the 2 of them would cuddle up in the same comfy bed on the floor and sleep: so cute!! Secret does have that issue of not wanting me to put the socks on her paws. She actually would run away from me and hide behind my husband's chair at one point. She now will let me touch her feet, but I'm proceeding very slowly in this. Secret likes to "lead" when I walk both Manny and her together, which leads me to believe she'd do a great job at leading a blind person. We are enjoying our time with Secret very much. She is a sweetheart and is a wonderful companion!

FoodType: Taste of the Wild HIgh Prairie
ExerciseType: loves swimming (oddly enough, is exceptional at treading in deep water!) dog play, fetch, bone chewing, hide-and-seek, tug
GeneralComments: Mickey has a laid back personality, not soft or sensitive, but gently sweet nature.  He is very thoughtful and patient.  Yet as a teenage boy, he can be goofy and silly, but none of that obnoxious male behavior such as mounting, marking, bullying, etc.  He does experience yellow zone arousal when entering a new environment, when encountering new dogs and when encountering highly aroused dogs in class.   After repeating small sliced exposures, he will quickly returns to green zone.  And then is able to move forward in a calmer demeanor without the need of repeating as many small slices.  In cases such as these, he has been very consistent in demonstrating the same results in his ability from going to yellow to green.  Nice and predictable!  Work in progress for red zone with nail clipping.  Green zone for body handling of the head/neck and body/tail regions and legs.  Great strides have been made in his progress of not picking up non-dog items.  Does a great job with knowing ™out_.   Has never destroyed or ingested items, just likes to pick them up and carry it around.    As a youngster, Mickey had the tendency to yield space, becoming goofy in his body movements .  He has progressed to become comfortable in the green zone when physically manipulating his body into position _ such as when doing the various vet holds.  But still occasionally, enters yellow zone with gentle restraint.  Good results with the work in progress to do shorter snap shots of gentle restraint while his body is relaxed.  Overall, Mickey is well behaved and appears to be confident in all areas of his training and socialization.  My husband says he is his favorite so far, but he says that about every dog!

GeneralComments: Depends on class and where and what is going on how she acts. We are working on walking with loose leash, she is active and doesn't seem to settle well when out.  Liz and I are trying several things.  Currently we are working parking lots and waiting for her to relax.  She rides in car great and exits nicely.  She just seems to hear and see everything.  She doesn't loose total attention from me though.  She seems to need me and will always check in great!!  We are trying to figure out this loose leash, allowing them to investigate vs staying connected better.  She likes to sniff and wants to know what something is that catches her eye, but will check in.  Great in house and our yard, cul de sac and pipe stem and around corner.  We do small sections at a time. She did well in the mall when Liz and Wendy were with us and she does great at the school lobby when picking up son.  But seems active when trying sidewalks at strip malls, need to start further out in lot and zigzag in and take lots of time and breaks.

ExerciseType: walking, playing with house dog, playing/ running in enclosed area with other GEB dogs, frolicking in a creek
GeneralComments: Sherry is making dramatic improvements. Her loose leash walking is improving all the time.  Her episodes of leash biting and attacking me on walks due to getting hyper activated have almost completely stopped. (the creek activates her)  I feel she is stubborn at times with name recall, however, still improving. She is really learning and responding to our routine on her own at times. She is getting better at "getting a toy" when I tell her to, (not always, but better).  we need to work on Sherry not grabbing at my other dog's collar. She has been responding better when I tell her out, but needs to keep working on it.  sometimes when I drop a treat she will eat it, other times she won't (inconsistent).  It's like if she knows we are practicing she won't do it, but if it is truly dropped, she will eat it.

In the house she picks up commands fairly quickly but can still get distracted outside the house or at class. Still need to tame some of her puppy behaviors like occasional counter surfing.   Could use advice helping her settle while we eat family dinner, etc. We always feed her first and take a get busy break if she needs. Sometimes she will fall asleep and/or settle; other times she can't seem to settle - will bark or nip for attention or go from person to person trying to climb up on the chair and potentially steal food. Efforts to re-direct her with toy, kong, ice cube, etc. are short-lived and if we put her in the kennel at those times she will bark and bark.

GeneralComments: Housebreaking and sleeping through the night are the biggest issues I need help with. She often has to pee and poop at 4 am (an improvement from 2am!). I put her back in the kennel and she sleeps till 6am, but never later. She is so smart--she learns the skills in just a couple repetitions and enjoys the training sessions. She knows everything on the list. She is very independent and even dragging a leash in the house, manages to sneak away from me, ninja-like, and get into mischief. She has no desire to be right by my side all the time, but would rather explore her surroundings. She takes a morning and afternoon nap, but otherwise is on the go until she falls asleep while chewing on a toy in the evening. I think this is just normal puppy behavior. I just didn't realize the level of intense supervision that would be required.

ExerciseType: walk, fetch in house, romp and play
GeneralComments: I see improvement in Marie's ability to calm herself and stay in the green think and learn zone every day.  We are making stride in all the areas except the stealing of unauthorized stuff.  I am concerned about the barking.  She does this when she want me to know that she wants something right now.  I do not have lots of puppy/dog experience so I do not know if this is what puppies do and then later with maturity will subside.  We are very proactive to meet all of her basic needs such as food/water/rest,play,exercise to keep her engaged and happy.  I am concerned that she needs to be taken out at night for elimination.  She ready poops and pees at night as soon as she is takes out and goes right back to sleep with no fuss.  We take her out when she asks at night because I have concerns that I do not want to trigger another UTI.  We are both retired so the interrupted sleep is not an undue burden for us. We love this puppy and  we both feel very privileged to be able to work with her in this program.  I realize that we have limited ability and are ready and willing to learn what we need to enhance our ability to train and socialize Marie.  Orlando is our role model.

ExerciseType: Walking and ball play on occasion
GeneralComments: I think he is doing good so far. He still has his challenges like jumping, barking, leash walking and biting but he is getting better all the time. He rarely pees in the house, has never soiled his crate, and has pretty much stopped chewing household appliances. He still enjoys an inappropriate chew toy like a paper towel or shoe when he can get one but he is doing this less and less. Loose leash walking is still a daily struggle, he understands the concept and is getting better but loses focus constantly given the amazing scents on NYC sidewalks. He has gotten a lot better around other dogs, children and things that move. I am able to control him more and keep him in or near the think and learn zone until the moving person is right upon him. He is much better in class as well though barking is still a struggle. He is great with sit, good with down, heel, get busy and close when I have a food lure. Without a food lure getting him to respond is very difficult. He is a great dog, a joy to be around and a wonderful companion.

GeneralComments: Have spent lot of time socializing Landis to other dogs and in other homes since last evals. Started over his foundation classes with Coal & Quentin & currently on Class 7. Partly because I'm behind on teaching Landis his skills not because he's incapable of learning them. (1) Would like help with greetings (again!). When I let Landis say hi & bring him directly in front of person, his nose is at their crotch. I don't think he's sniffing. I'm thinking the solution may be bringing him to people at an angle for now. Anyway, some direction would be great. (2) Body handling. Would like help making sure that he's ok with it. I don't do it as much as I should but I want to make sure that my interpretation of his body language is accurate when I do it.

GeneralComments: Landis has very pleasant personality. Thank you for sending me a great puppy. I'm still trying to figure him out, but have enjoyed the first weeks with him. I need help with when he pops up too quickly on the down command (before I can treat him). I may be doing something wrong on follow me with him when I'm giving treats, so I'd like help with that. I also want to review greetings protocal. I'm only having Landis say hi to person and they can pet him, but I'm not asking him to sit yet. I think it's the right thing for him, but need clarification. He maybe ready for more. Also want to discuss with you & Sherry doing more TTouch massage/balance harness work with him to help with his body handling -- maybe contacting Laura Livingstone for additional help. I definitely want to have you review body restraint handling with us. I think I covered the main things. Oh, he definitely is a scavenger -- moreso than my other dogs, so let me know if I'm giving him too much time to 'mouth/pick up' stuff on the check it outs.

Leon is jealous of people interacting with me and will vie for my attention. He inserts himself between the other person and me, paws me, nudges, etc. On occasion he still barks at me for attention which is, at times, a legitimate signal that he needs to get busy. Other times it is purely seeking attention when my focus is elsewhere - like busy working at my desk.   He loves lap time, body handling and can be easily settled at home. He does not like body handling when he is out on a public exposure, at class or in other stressful environments. In these situations he will decompress if given opportunities for chewing or sniffing. His tolerance for public outings is improving slowly. A few minutes in a brand new place is still all he can handle before he's overwhelmed. When stressed his movements become faster and he is not able to maintain his focus or stay in a position without breaking. Gets stress dandruff, very heavy at times.  He's laying on my feet right now. Leon is a love bug who likes a lot of physical contact.

GeneralComments: Overall Karo is doing well.  She can be on her own agenda at times. She patterns things very quickly which can make working with her difficult at times. Grainger is doing great. There are only a few of things that I am really concerned about, one being hand biting of people. I know that he is still teething, but am trying my best to work on not allowing Grainger to use hands/arms as a way to relieve his tooth aches. The other big thing that I am mainly concerned about is his crate acceptance during the night. Grainger is great in his crate during the day (when I leave for class, eat dinner, etc), however, at night he will only sleep in the crate for about 2 hours and then will bark in the middle of the night. Lately he has been doing this every night, and I have mentioned this at our weekly classes. As recommended, I have tried taking Grainger out to GB and putting him right back in his crate (no play time, etc). Recently, when he barks during the night, I ignore him and he stops completely after about 5 minutes. At home, Grainger has a bigger crate and has no problem sleeping in it. I am trading his crate for a larger size for when we are at school, and will see if his nightly barking stops if he is in a bigger space.  The last thing that I have already made Kim aware in pup class is GraingerÆs demand barking. We have both seen a tremendous transformation in Grainger, for in the very beginning, he would constantly demand bark. We have come such a long way! Now, he only occasionally demand barks. For instance, I could be sitting on my bed or at my desk and he will sit below me and bark because he wants attention. This is only occasional, and we are working on eliminating it completely.

Gaila is doing very well.  We have seen her personality change and some behavior changes since the arrival of Felicia (retired GEB dog).  Her interest in other dogs has reduced (as we previously did not have a dog).  She is more confidendent, independent, and less reliant on human interaction, but does show an insistence on getting attention if Felicia is getting attention.  Her response has never been to growl, bite, or bark, but but rather to jump or push in.  (This seems to be reducing as time passes, and we are stern with such jumping/excited behavior.)   She has played hard with Felicia, and we have been strict with her about pulling ears and biting Felicia's legs during play.   Felicia's arrival has been positive for Gaila, but we have also had to adjust (and are continuing to adjust) as Gaila seems less less responsive to commands and less interested in "listening" to her humans. We continue to seek a "balance" with two dogs in our household, as well as learning to effectively respond to Gaila's new sense of independence and failure to listen.  (Her reduced willingness to follow commands and listen could also be due to her age - 9 months.)   The "girls" have settled in together, very well, and enjoy each other's company.  We have continued to maintain a strict regime - exercise, kennel, eating.  The additional exercise from playing with Felicia has increased food intake.

FoodType: Iam's lamb and rice and Iam's Puppy
ExerciseType: playes with up to 4 other dogs, long leash walks,
GeneralComments: At 8 weeks old I immediately noticed that ôEpic" was very body sensitive. He would shrink away from your hands when stroking his back. It was easy to activate a hind leg itching response also. He wanted very little to do with much of anything, he sat and looked at you or if there was a lot of activity he would go find a quiet place to lay down and entertain himself. His energy level was extremely low. I observed that with other puppies near his age he was not assertive and got "beat up", so he coped by avoiding interaction that became too rough for him. I jokingly diagnosed him as having what I called ôSibling Suppression Syndromeö.  At our house his big buddy Lenny has helped him gain confidence and learn appropriate play. Epic was not very food motivated, he responded to shaking toys and movement. He had/has strong name recognition response. Epic has since become very food motivated and much more confident. I am really enjoying his gentle and sweet personality. You can tell Epic is problem solving by watching the activity of his eye movement.   I wonder if his initial low energy had anything to do with his possible lowered immune system/mite/itching medical condition.

Between the snow, illnesses and an unexpected death in my family there was a period of time when socialization was not as often as I would have liked But the progress she shows when we are on a regular schedule is so encouraging.  She has a sweet disposition and is a pleasure to work with.

GeneralComments: We love Cabot but having him is a daily struggle. He is very energetic and hard to settle. He can never be off leash. Responds well to treats but will repeat bad behaviors to then do it right in hopes of more treats. Hard to increase durations. Waiting for better weather to resume longer walks but also believe he needs to run. I find it hard to take him out because he is so excitable, he is strong and hard to manage. He often ignores basic commands such as name response and come because he is so distracted by everything else.

Berta is a "worker" girl.  She always wants to be around someone, eager to go wherever we take her.  Her counter jumping, barking and jumping on people has improved tremendously since her last evaluation.  Her only issue at this time is dog distraction which we are continuing to work on.  I am trying to take her to places that have other dogs and have her sit and observe and will continue as the weather gets warmer.

ExerciseType: walks and  runs/fetches toys fenced play yard
GeneralComments: Baylor has made much progress since his last evaluation in many areas.  Recently, Baylor made a road trip staying overnight in a motel.  He did wonderful at the motel room and did not have any problems.  During the last month his overall energy has increased and interest/ excitement seeing other dogs during outings.  Meeting Sara/Arnold for Pack Walk and Pack walk with one of our personal dogs.  He's very affectionate, willing pup and seems to enjoy body handling.  We've not had any issues with underfootings (open grates, manhole covers nor metal sidewalk plates) and he seems to enjoy outings.  He has worn a winter dog jacket without concern.  Kelly reported Baylor did well during pup swap around Anya and with house manners in the home.

Randy is a nice pup.  He builds his confidence when he visits the same situation many times.  He is affectionate - likes to be handled and petted.  He likes playing with other dogs and is just starting to like nylabones and toys. He is not a jumper or big chewer.    I am working on teaching him to share.  When my dogs have a nylabone he will bark and try to get it from them .  He usually wins.  I try to have 3 of the same item and this seems to be working.  He is tenacious and will try many maneuvers to get what he wants.

GeneralComments: Phineas has not attended a home switch yet and has had 0 overnights.  He rides really well in the car sitting on the passenger side floor.  He loves his kennel. Kojak has definite guarding issues- He exhibited this first day when I picked him up from Jodi with the other GEB puppies.  Even with the water bowl.  We are working on this everyday with him and my pet dog.  Kojak also has trouble playing nicely with dogs other than GSD Rodeo- He is very rough with his mouth and does not want to play TOY.   Kojak also really changes personality when wearing anything- bandana- jacket-tshirt etc- appears to be the BEST dog ever but is very unlike himself.  NO sniffing no blowing leaf chasing- only calmly sitting by my side.  We are working on that daily in familiar places to warm him up to the idea.   Odd note - Kojak is extremely ticklish- for lack of a better term- His leg goes when you scratch his jaw line and his back has 2 spots and his stomach and his front feet- when chewing an itch on his paws- his back leg goes nuts.

ExerciseType: walks, playing fetch & soccer in yard
GeneralComments: Ken is easily distracted by sights and sounds around him. Lately, when walking, he tends to sniff a lot and will pull. He seems to have a hard time focusing on me and will rarely check in. I backtrack and try to get him to focus more on me than on his surroundings. We have spent a lot of time this winter practicing up and down our street. He does improve with lots of stops and turns, but does better in the driveway and street than on the sidewalks. Also, he seems to crave attention and tries to approach anyone who is near. He can be very stubborn and pull or jump up to see people. It is often hard to get him to focus on me and sit and wait to be greeted. He also is very forceful with our dog. They may start by playing tug, but it can quickly escalate to out of control chasing and Ken often grabs Rylee by the back of the neck or collar.

ExerciseType: walking; walking/running on treadmill; walking up, down stairs; running in fenced in field
GeneralComments: Gwenyth is an energetic, smart, sweet BIG girl! She loves to cuddle with our Golden Retriever; enjoys our "cuddle" sessions, and has settled nicely into our daily routine. ItÆs amazing how quiet she is in the kennel. The animals go to bed around 10:00 pm and I stay up to watch TV. Even though the TV is on and Monty is not in a kennel, Gwenyth settles in and does not complain.  Sometimes during our training sessions she requires time to process a command. If there are other animals nearby, she is easily distracted.  Gwenyth is very "mouthy" and wiggly in the morning just after getting out of the kennel. I usually have a toy for her to put into her mouth and that keeps her from putting my hands into her mouth. I've noticed that she often goes for a toy herself now, so that seems to be a step in the right direction. She enjoys going for walks. The rainy, icy, frigid weather has limited our time to work outside. When I drive her into town to practice walking at the strip malls, I find that there is so much salt spread on the sidewalks that I need to wash her feet when we return home.  Gwenyth enjoys riding in the car. We took her along to Pennsylvania over the weekend and she did very well in the motel.  I really enjoy having her! I worry that her sheer strength can bowl me over. IÆm counting on her love and trust in me to motivate her to focus on our training sessions so she learns how to think about what she's doing and make the right choices.

GeneralComments: I thought we were still having an issue with approaching/getting in the car but it has improved and hopefully, resolved this past week- patience and persistence!! All in all, she is a VERY pleasant pup with a nice energy level.  She does seem very mature for  her age.

ExerciseType: walks, play with other pups, play without other pups
GeneralComments: Crystal has mellowed out significantly in the last few months.  She is a sweet, smart, happy girl who loves to work but settles quickly and reliably when asked to.  Lately she has begun to "test" me when I ask certain behaviors (Kennel, Load up, Go Place) if she doesn't feel like obeying.  I am working through this with her by maintaining the hand gesture associated with the command and waiting for her to offer the behavior.  When she does, she gets rewarded enthusiastically.  If she continues to refuse (avoids eye contact, lays down with her back to me) and becomes distracted I try to re-engage her with other commands and then ask for the behavior again once she is re-connected.

ExerciseType: Walks on a long line through nature trails and outings
GeneralComments: She is a very busy girl and has a difficult time settling and staying settled so we try and do small doses. She also has some trouble settling at home but has gotten better. (I have trouble settling at home too so that could be why). She needs time to check out new spaces but connects well once she adjusts. I think Cindy described her best when she called her a 'party girl'. She can stay calm and focused for only so long and then has to let loose. She likes to be moving around and checking things out and sometimes settles better when there's things for her to observe.

I am not sure who is going to read this or if my comments are appropriate for this purpose.  This is my first GEB experience.  I love animals and I have always had them but never have structured their environment in this fashion.  I am learning alot with Ames.  I am certain he is a very smart dog.  I am certain he has a super personality.  He loves to please and he loves to be connected.  He is a lover.  He always has a smile on his face and he gives love constantly.  I have noticed that he loves the outdoors.  He would stay outside all day in any weather if you let him.  He also loves to work.  When we are in class he is very happy and he does not like to end that experience.  He knows when it is over and his body language will change and he gets a sad look on his face.  He also loves to smell things and he has a very keen sense of smell.  Sometimes he is more distracted by smells than by other animate objects.  If Ames makes it through this program I would like to say now - in case I don't get the chance to later - I think he will be happiest with a person who is very affectionate and who has a true love for him and will hug him and talk to him and pet him constantly. Ames is just a lover.  Sometimes he will go up to Clementine when she is sleeping and he will lay next to her and put his arm around her and sleep.  He does best when he is touching and being touched.

Alden is a wonderful dog and we really enjoy having him in our home.      Alden has not attended any home switches since I received him.  However, this is b/c he was bounced around in his earlier months.  We thought he should have a nice stable home for the next couple months as he adjusts to our home.     Alden tends to get activated when attending puppy class, but we're also working on him settling and staying calm while working.     I feel Alden can overcome his counter surfing and go on to be a wonderful guide for a blind person.  He's really fun to be around.  His energy level is good.  He doesn't sleep all that much at home when we're with him.  However, he doesn't get in to trouble either.  He'll find a bone or we'll play rope with him.      Overall, I think Alden is on the right track to becoming a guide.  We're grateful to have him.

GeneralComments: The biggest challenge Wagner has been having is settling--especially when he is over-tired.  It has taken him as long as 1.5 hours to really settle (and then fall asleep).  He has plenty of opportunities to practice--at home, during piano lessons, at church, at adult Sunday School, at someone's house for dinner, etc.  All are relatively calm, quiet events.  Sometimes he can settle, chew on a bone, and nap, but other times he will continually get up, chew or tug on his leash, pull away, etc.  Doesn't bark or whine at these times.    The evening he jumped on the ottoman with a toy and then barked at me (while I was sitting with my feet on the same ottoman) his behavior was very demanding.  It was a time when I know he was over-tired but couldn't just unwind and settle.

Toggi is an alert, smart puppy.  He seems to have good energy and is atentive to learning new things.  He is easily engaged.  We are enjoying raising him.

ExerciseType: daily walks, plays fetch, plays with released GEB dog who lives in house.
GeneralComments: Toggi has many wonderful traits: he has a nice energy level, loves people, is very attentive, likes to please, and is very smart.  In general, he knows his commands will and responds appropriately.  He plays well with other pups in the program and enjoys having Verdell(our released dog) around.  We are really enjoying raising him.  Toggi does occasionally playbite when very excited and will pick up household items and though often does not chew them will carry them around. All and all we think he is doing well but welcome any help to increase his chances of becoming a guide dog.

ExerciseType: 1-2 long walks per day, playing in apartment, and puppy play dates as often as possible . When were in PA we will run him around the backyard every day 2x a day
GeneralComments: Tobias is really really good! He responds well to corrections in behavior and learns very quickly. He is extremely food motivated which is great for training, but makes food on the ground extremely alluring. He is dog-distracted and since he is used to have 1 or fewer dogs in class that is something we'll have to work on. He also will jump during people greetings so since coming back on campus we have been working extensively on that. We have taken him to a few stores/restaurants (with permission of the owners) and he has done magnificently! He will settle very well and is very good at doing commands there. He does occasionally play-bite but that is also something we've been working on and now in general he just licks. We do have a home-swap planned from the 29th-3rd while we are away. He will be with Zareen and Merrill.

Stewart is a joy! I think Stewart masters tasks fairly easily, and he enjoys practicing. For a puppy, I think his energy level is medium, and he settles easily. My main concerns are polite people greetings, loose leash walking, and keeping him from eliminating on walks.

ExerciseType: neighborhood walks, playing with me and playing with other dogs
GeneralComments: I love this little banana bread. She has so much personality. She does become activated easily and she is very interested in things that move - including air. Just this morning she became excited over the water spilling out of the outdoor faucet which then turned into a case of the zoomies. I think our biggest issues are people greetings, sound, other dogs, movement excites, and she is a bit fussy with the comfort of her body (e.g., leash contact).

ExerciseType: walking, running, playing fetch, playing tug
GeneralComments: Although we are inexperienced and don't have a basis for making this assessment, Ralph appears to be doing well for his age. He goes to work with us almost every day and everyone comments on how well he does.  He settles nicely, he greets when permitted to do so, walks nicely in the building.  Our biggest concerns are: 1. Get Busy is still a little unreliable and unpredictable. He doesn't always go when told, then he'll suddenly have to go a short time later. A couple of weeks ago he peed in the house just an hour or two after he had peed outside. He came running to me frantically as if it had surprised him (leaving a trail on the floor). 2.  He's becoming more distracted while outside--dogs, people, smells--especially in new environments. 3.  He's becoming more interested in things on the ground.

ExerciseType: walking, playing fetch, swimming, tug, playing in the house, playing with other dog
GeneralComments: I'm no expert, but Ralph seems to be doing pretty well for his age. He's got great self control when there's a food bowl in sight.  He settles very well when out in public (e.g. eating or standing talking to someone).   My biggest concerns are: --smelling (sometimes pulling really hard to sniff something) --recall.  It seems to me that his recall (come) should be better at this point, but again, I'm not really competent to judge. --loose leash walking in the presence of other people or animals (like when passing them)

ExerciseType: walking, running, playing fetch, playing tug
GeneralComments: He does spend time in other homes and locations. He is fairly well travelled and never has any difficulties. He also spends time at work away from me with a couple of select people and he always does well.   Biggest issue:  dog and smell distraction.  If there's a dog, he can't focus on anything else.  We can work a smell area until he starts ignoring it, but then when we encounter the next new thing, we have to go through the cycle again.  He is very willful in that circumstance--he will lunge as far as he can and it is very difficult to get him engaged and focused again. These distractions are more significant now than they were when he was  younger and more difficult to manage now that he is 77 lbs of muscle

ExerciseType: walking,playing in house with kids/other dogs
GeneralComments: Quarter is doing well. He is a  young pup with a good demeanor and personality. I would like the opportunity to socialize him outside of class with other puppy raisers/pups to help him more. This week, we have implemented longer walks outside with him which he appears to enjoy. Afterward, he wants to lie down with me to rest. Quarter continues to mouth (not truly bite) and responds to negative sound (uh-uh) to stop. He has retrieved his own toy from family dogs with confidence and is now lying next to the alpha without incident (no growl from alpha, even touching).

ExerciseType: running in the yard, playing with other pets, walking
GeneralComments: Quarter is coming along nicely. My concerns are not coming when off lead, clipping nails, not always responding to kennel as I feel he should. Being at school has been a great thing. He is not distracted by much because he is used to being around things. We are working on his ability to remain in an area when at school. He has not been in school with me everyday the past two weeks due to student testing schedules (he would be a distraction) and him sometimes not wanting to defacate  before leaving for school. On those days, we make certain that we take him somewhere that evening. When he does go somewhere, it usually takes him 10 minutes or so to calm himself and get into t he routine of what he needs to do. He wants to sniff, pull on the lead and is distracted. We spend about five minutes outside of wherever we are to get him into the zone before proceeding into the store.

We usually talk to him until he realizes what's going on and then he's ok. He does not like to be outside in "heat" and Peppy seems to consider "70" or above to be heat.  He would do well in a cooler climate if he were to be outside a lot.

Stepped Peppy down and off of Probiotics as directed by GEB Vet but every we've done this digestive issues have returned.  We have also learned what treats he can and cannot eat and stick to that regiment.  We would like to (for future goals) add duration and distance to the "place" command.  We really need to fine tune his social skills especially with dog-to-dog greeting.  Peppy has experience in a military workplace, college classroom, doctors offices, hospitals (two different ones), multiple restaurants (fine dining, bars, fast food), a tour boat (no sea sickness), and being in a retirement home office setting.  We trust him and he always seems eager to learn.

the biggest obstacle still is around other people and dogs.  He is still very excitable but getting much better about calming down in less time. At only 13 weeks we have not experienced some of the things listed above with Oslo - overnights, heavy traffic, pills, ear cleaning, attending a social (don't know what this is-is it a puppy play date?), home switch, etc.  Oslo seems very smart and confident but is certainly acting like a typical, young puppy with teething and being mouthy/biting when he is excited.  We are almost there with the housebreaking but he can't be completely trusted yet.  He rides very well in the car.  Our biggest issue right now is that he won't sleep in the crate through the entire night.  Not sure if he is getting overheated in the molded crate.  He gets up around 4am but will go right back to sleep if we let him out of the crate.  It's hard to ignore the cries, sometimes barking and work on training at 4am!  I'm wondering if a bigger, wire crate would make the difference.

Still pees in crate if left for two hour or less during daytime, but is completely dry during nighttime crating (8 hours).

FoodType: Iams Lamb Meal & Rice Proactive Health
ExerciseType: 2-3 15min walks, tug of war/ wrestle w dog housemate in yard usually 1 hour per day broken up throughout the morning and after work
GeneralComments: Nanette has been steadily improving on her pulling on leash skills. She checks in with me more often than the first week she was here and seems more settled in at home. She has joined me on many adventures such as going on the metro to a busy Saturday visit to two separate Smithsonian museums. She is excellent on the metro and will wiggle herself directly under my chair and basically fall asleep until it's time to go. She has gone to a noisey pub, it took her 10-15min to settle down but she was quiet and under the table for 1.5 hours. We headed out in time for elimination. She rides beautifully in the car. We went to a dance concert and, again,l it took her 10-15min to settle but once she did she was fine for about 45min. We did not stay in the theater for the second half of the show as she gave a slight yelp of boredom. But we did stay in the lobby contented to wait for our party to exit the theater. Afterwards she settles directly in the car and slept until we got back home. Every outing seemed to have worn her out but once she gets home she is very excited to play with her doggy housemate. Once it is time to go to bed she will settle right down and kennel wonderfully.

GeneralComments: Ludwig dos well with his commands.  His house manners are fabulous and he is very amenable to grooming.  I know he needs work with dog distraction and demand barking.  I am using techniques recommended from the last swap including immediate distraction using commands followed, if necessary, by a leash time out for 20-30 seconds behind a door with praise on release and he has shown improvement in a short period of time.  Dog distraction will require more cooridination of dog outings with others and as the weather breaks this will become easier for all to coordinate.  This winter has been brutal for all.

GeneralComments: We are just starting to work on jacketed outings. We have gone "shopping" in several local locations (post office, library, drug store) during early times when distractions are low. She is doing well.  Mina has difficulty in class, I think primarily due the close proximity of people/dogs. Her connection to me is very fractured and she tends to lunge toward other dogs and people. I bring high value treats and take her out for play breaks, but the intensity is a lot for her.  Her behavior upon seeing other dogs when we're out is dependent on the distance and the behavior of the other dog. She wants badly to greet and sniff, but if they get too close she barks loudly and continuously. If we can approach very gradually, with lots of time to settle between steps forward and lots of rewards for checkins, she can sometimes be successful. But if the other dog barks, she escalates immediately to red zone.  She is a very good girl at home most of the time, especially if she gets daily mental and physical exercise. She is smart, seems to like to please, and responds well to praise.

ExerciseType: Play in fenced yard, fetch, walks
GeneralComments: We are just starting to work on jacketed outings. We have gone "shopping" in several local locations (post office, library, drug store) during early times when distractions are low. I bring high value treats and take her out for play breaks, but the intensity is a lot for her. ExerciseType: Regular play dates with Pixel, walks in the woods, plays in backyard, training around town
GeneralComments: Karise is an enthusiastic puppy. She's a quick learner and wants to please.  She stayed with Val and Jim for a week and a half to evaluate her behavior.  She'll be with Avis Hull for a few days when I have cataract surgery.  Val particularly commented on her lovely house manners.  When she plays with Pixel, they can both get snarly faced, but Karise responds well to "toy".  Her training has been interrupted recently because she had a split heat and was out of action for six weeks.  We still had play dates with Pixel, but she stayed home the rest of the time.  We've started back up this past week, and she's doing well.  I'm concentrating on multiple small slices of various experiences.  We had our first extended walk in the woods today.  Alleluia!

FoodType: Mix of Iams Puppy and Kirkland All Natural Puppy
ExerciseType: Walks, playing fetch, tug, hide and seek, playing at camp
GeneralComments: He is very confident, very intelligent and excellent on the loose lead. He learns what we want quickly and is happy to do anything you ask.  Follows me around the house all day, never wants to be more than a few feet away from me. We have been thrilled with him.  Houston's weak spots:  Name response is poor. Not very food motivated with kibble. Checking in is weak.  He is terrible at greeting people. I need help here.  He jumps and chews on them if we let him close.  Also, Houston grooms and chews us instead of licking us. He has gotten significantly better, not doing the ballistic biting with the kids anymore, but he is extremely mouthy. We are seeing him get better with this each day, but it's still an issue. Houston is terrible at class and very distracted by other dogs. Wow, that sounds like a lot of issues, but I wanted to make sure I put everything I could think of.

Not very food motivated with kibble. Checking in is weak.  He is terrible at greeting people. I need help here.  He jumps and chews on them if we let him close.  Also, Houston grooms and chews us instead of licking us. He has gotten significantly better, not doing the ballistic biting with the kids anymore, but he is extremely mouthy. We are seeing him get better with this each day, but it's still an issue. Houston is terrible at class and very distracted by other dogs. Wow, that sounds like a lot of issues, but I wanted to make sure I put everything I could think of.

Heaven is a terrific dog with many good qualities, but a calm Buddha-like serenity is not one of them. Her energy level is like an ADHD child  on a steady diet of Red Bull. We have a quiet home and she is getting better and will play on her own some but I think she needs a little age and maturity before we see any major chilling out.  She has learned to settle on her "place" while we eat or do other things and has always slept through the whole night until 5:30 AM.  She is frantic about food and always acts like she is starving although she has gained a steady 2 lbs. each week. That makes food a valuable reward when training. In training, she learns quickly when she stays focused but has a pretty short attention span. She is sweet, affectionate, very intelligent, and is getting better every day. We have good hopes for her success.

Hugo is still somewhat puppy like in his demeanor and behaviors.  When he gets excited, takes him some time to shake it off and settle down.  Will still jump on me if something startles or agitates him outside, but this behavior has started to diminish.   The week he spent on a puppy sit with many other dogs and new social and environment exposures has resulted in some real evidence of maturation, and mellowing of the spontaneous explosions of puppyness.  We are starting to see what the adult dog Hugo will become - we think he will be wonderful.

GeneralComments: We have been very concerned about Flossie's biting to the point where I have kept my children away from her. She does not growl, I believe she is playing, but she bites hard and it comes unexpectedly. Over the past few weeks we have worked at stopping the biting and I do see an improvement, but we still need to work on it. The counter surfing is also still a problem.  Flossie seems curious about what is on the counter - usually there is no food out. She just jumps up to look. Mostly she like to drink water out of the kitchen sink despite having a full bowl of fresh water available to her on the floor. Flossie truly enjoys working on her behaviors. She learns quickly and enjoys working, but she can be stubborn. She gets annoyed when asked to go place or down. Often she stands her ground and will not go place or down, she just barks at her handler and won't move. We have been keeping Flossie on leash inside the house to help prevent counter surfing and to stop her from biting.

Declan is working diligently with me on self control, especially in the home environment.  He is unable to enter a home and behave appropriately on his own.  He is easily stimulated,  Introducing him to the home on a leash, asking him to earn the right to be without a leash is a must. We work on settle often.   Declan requires strict supervision while in the house and around other pups.  He instantly mounts other pups and is stimulated by any defensive behavior from other pups.  After 2-3 days of redirection on inappropriate behavior around other pups he can be trusted for 5-15 minutes unsupervised.  Declan walks well on a lead when there is little to no distraction but requires your anticipation to redirect and remain connected so as not to get dragged. Declan is often successful with short exposures.  Declan is willing and I think he wants to please!

Nichole and I have been working hard with Camille at her weak points.  Camille's biggest problems are, pulling, chewing and attention barking.  We have been trying to switch up where Camille stays and has been helping Camille.  When going to class with Nichole she sometimes will bark or whine or attention but Nichole has been working on this and has been able to get her to settle a lot better.  The chewing we think is built up energy when I took Camille home In Binghamton she got to go on a lot of walks and have a lot of exercise and it seemed to have helped Camille out.  The pulling is a work in progress Camille loves to lead and gets over excited we have been taking the helpful advice we get in class and have been working on it, Camille is a fast learner im sure it will only be a matter of time before we can have this issue under way.

ExerciseType: Walks, playing frisbee, playing with other dogs
GeneralComments: Blanche has overall come a long way. She is a very mellow, calm dog, sometimes to a fault. She can be slow to do commands and a little difficult to motivate at times. We are working on keeping our outings exciting and upbeat so she doesn't mope. She is uncomfortable on grates but we have worked on it recently with a crate divider in our living room and that issue has been resolving. The barking at doors  is still an issue, but she understands that if she barks she has to go kennel - although now, occasionally, she'll go into her kennel TO bark when someone comes to the door. She isn't allowed to greet people who come in unless she is quiet. Go get a toy has helped with that.

ExerciseType: Running, walking, play with humans and dogs
GeneralComments: Still seeing some dog reactivity and excitement around strange people.  Responds well to use of distance and slowing the pace in these situations.  Seeing much improvement in Icabod's ability to self modulate in excitable and distracting situations.  Icabod is also settling better in work and social situations with very little vocalization in the past 1 1/2 months.  He and the family cat have learned to respect each other so he is less reactive with cats now.  A very enjoyable pup to raise.

She has a joyous nature and a very happy temperament.

ExerciseType: 25 min walks and mini runs [50 foot run) plus 10 min-ish toy play pulling 3 times a day all
GeneralComments: Great improvement even in the last few days.  Part of it I think is us settling down as a family of four and as new to Puppy Raising...as well as Freddy.   It has taken far far more attention and time during our working at home day than expected, but literally in last days think we've turned a corner.    Our biggest issue is Freddy's desire to mouth, chew everything OUTSIDE ....so hard to give him exercise outside cause he likes to mouth and then chew EVERYTHING.  We live in woods, but have resorted to mostly walks on the cull de sac road, becasue both diarreah bouts occured after day time walks in woods EVEN with us being diligent with 'Out' & treats & doing if before food or after food etc.   I'm assuming he will get better with this!

A great dog, such fun, loves cuddles, very food oriented, will follow you around house literally all day from room to room, we work from home so does not have a lot of alone time [would HATE to have him thrust into crating during a 9 hour work day situation with only a midday break =(]  AND some times [1 brief 3-5 minute moment every 2 days or so] goes into a naughty precocious moment, "I want to PLAY NOW!" and drops down to 'just try to come get me!" stance with his toy or something he has stolen [like a shoe or sock] and would race around the house if you went after him.  Usually will drop with a firm 'Out!' or a treat and 'Out'.    Also if hungry or bored or has to poop will bark very purposely and bark growl very close to you insistently -  including no force nip once or twice in last month - in these rare instances if he has pooped, played, wee'd etc, and its just I want to play, if he doesn't settle I give him kennel up and he goes in and settles [sometimes with brief protest first] quite quickly! [i.e. within a min or two at most]

Diamond is a high energy girl who works better with praise than food.  She loves people usually getting overly excited (def in the red zone)  She will calm down after a few minutes until spoken to again then will spike right back to high even with persons of the family or myself.  Although she is getting better with this she still requires much work on people skills.  Other than people skills Diamond is a good girl and I have no other concerns.

ExerciseType: walks, running with other dogs, playing with me or other dogs with toy/bone
GeneralComments: Conway is a very intelligent, obedient puppy that can run full out but settle anytime necessary.  I have not really seen any issues with his confidence even when I challenge him he will rarely even hesitate to do it.  Sometimes he is a little slower or sloppy with his commands and he is asked to do again better.  He will try to mount (usually my dog Satchel) but I see him thinking about it, positioning himself and I can call him and he won't mount.  I have loved raising him and think he has great potential as a guide.

GeneralComments: We have been one lucky family with Baldwin!  He has not faced several of the issues many of the pups have had to deal with.  He is a very mild mannered, eager to please pup.  We have known from early on that he would go on to do great things.  He is a very quick learner and very food motivated, both of which will make him perfect as a guide dog.  His humping issues seem to have resolved, he does not try to hump the kids when playing like he used to do and has done well with other dogs in the last few months as well.  I feel that at this point dog distractions are his biggest issue, especially on walks but we are working on distancing ourselves so that he can maintain control and that works well.  He will also steal the kids stuffed animals from time to time and they have gotten good at putting them where they are not accessible but if given the opportunity he will take them, although he is quick to "out" when caught. We have loved him as our own and put so much time and energy into helping him reach his full potential.  We know he will make us proud and we are honored to be a small part in his journey.  Thank you for granting us this honor of having him as part of our family.

GeneralComments: Baldwin is a smart little guy that catches on quickly and always aims to please.  His only big issue currently is his humping other dogs during play dates, but he did not do this at all during Forest's stay with us this week.  He tends to do it to smaller/more submissive dogs.  He does great with going up the stairs in familiar areas, but still tends to bolt up them in new places.  He kennels so well for us now that it's hard to believe it was ever an issue.  We are confident that he has a future as a guide dog for one very lucky person.

GeneralComments: Thimbles house manners, aside from some barking and whining, are great.  (She can be laying on her bed and just start a low, sad sounding whining.  We don't know why this happens.  We tend to ignore it, but sometimes it can escalate to barking.  Sometimes if we pet her or lay down next to her, she stops).  Her loose leash walking is inconsistant.  She pulls and smells constantly.  We have been working on this since she was a puppy.  Its a case of 1 step forward, 2 steps back.  We think we must be missing something or not reading the situation apporpriately.  Last weeks dog behavior class helped alot.  We can read her body language and determine when she may be stressed, but we are not always sure what to do about it.

Thimble has improved in many areas over the past few months.  Her crate behavior is very good.  Her counter surfing is much improved.  She is better at not pulling when walking, and is much improved when other dogs walk by, still laying down but often checking in and not pulling towards other dogs.  She pulls when she smells food that is on the sidewalk, or liquids or when you walk near a garbage can.  When indoors, we  need to improve her running off with our shoes, getting paper out of the bedroom garbage pails, stealing socks from bedrooms.  Sometimes when she comes in from outside in the morning she seems to have some stored up anxiety? and will run through the house, sometimes looking for things to grab but if not just running through the living room and dining room as fast as possible a few times.

She is just calm and lovely, and no longer chews on anything, jumps on counters or takes paper out of the garbage pail.  She has also improved on her loose leash walking, and while she could continue to improve on this she pulls much less and checks in much more.  She has gotten much better when she sees other dogs as well, checking in quicker and pulling less. GeneralComments: We love Timmy!  He did a great job with the transition to a new apartment.  He learns very quickly and we've noticed his energy level has started settling a bit (and we have been getting lots of exercise for him.)  He went through a week or so of marking behavior, but we used the advice from the website and seem to have nipped that in the bud.  The only remnant is now he will often pee twice on a walk (usually on command) instead of once.  Is that something to be concerned about?  The big thing we'd love help with is the grabbing inappropriate things as toys.  We've been working with him on this and it's improved, but is probably the biggest issue we're having with him.  Like I mentioned, we followed Maureen's initial advice, and have also started going back to the fundamentals on "out."  Thanks!

ExerciseType: walks, hide & seek, fetch (especially for daily "Ball Therapy" for her teeth), run in fenced yard, play with family dog
GeneralComments: Rumor is an amazing pup!  Once her "extenders" were removed from her teeth and she was able to chew on bones, have toys and play with other dogs, her stress-energy level completely disappeared and she has been very relaxed and mellow!  She no longer barks at other dogs or in her kennel, and her house manners are remarkable.  She has been a true joy to raise - despite the challenges that we faced with the treatment for her "base narrow canines," her sensitive tummy, her persistent barking and jumping, Rumor has truly matured into a wonderful, obedient, sweet girl.  The only negative about this whole experience is that I will miss her dreadfully when she leaves for training in 2 short weeks.  Thank you so much for giving me the opportunity to work with this special girl!

ExerciseType: walks, fetch, play in fenced backyard, play with older released dog
GeneralComments: Rumor is a great little pup, and we have totally loved raising her.  It has been difficult having her deal with so many medical problems, but the Guiding Eyes Vets have been very supportive and encouraging.  Her biggest non-medical issue is that she will bark when she is bored and is around other dogs - this has gotten MUCH better.  I am looking forward to having Rumor return to me so that we can begin training again!!!

ExerciseType: walks, hide-and-seek, fetch, run in fenced yard, play with family dog
GeneralComments: Rumor is the sweetest girl!  Although it has been a challenge with her teeth, especially not being able to give her any toys or chews, I have found great joy in connecting and interacting with her in many different ways.  She absolutely loves to practice her obedience skills, go on outings to explore new places, and attend puppy classes.  Her "mouthiness" has decreased dramatically over the last few months, and she no longer even attempts to put her mouth on furniture or hands - and only occasionally tries to bite on her leash.  She has also gotten MUCH better with her dog distraction, although she still will occasionally bark at another dog at class or on an outing.  I am so looking forward to her treatment for her teeth be finished so that I can again spoil her with toys, Kongs and nylabones.......and hopefully be able to introduce her to safe and appropriate puppy play with the other pups on program!

Peony is a very friendly and energetic pup. She is doing very well with all the basic commands such as sit and down. We are working on stay. While she does not go on furniture, she has been putting her paws on surfaces to reach objects such as news papers or towels and tries to lure us into chasing her. She also loves our cat, but wants to play too ruff. The other thing we are working on is greeting. She tends to get very excited and wants to jump on people. Peony is a very sweet and happy pup and we are really enjoying our time with her.

Peony came to us approximately 7 weeks ago after her first raiser had to give her up to return to school.  She has made improvements but continues to display poor house manners.  At about the same time that Peony came we also adopted a new house pet dog from a shelter who is 3 yrs old. They are friends but both can be possessive.  There has been ongoing issues of who is the top dog.  When we take Peony out for walk or outing it takes her a good 30 minutes to adjust.  Once she is calm she listens very well and is eager to learn.

ExerciseType: walking, playing on long line, fetch
GeneralComments: He's doing really well! He's sweet. We are working really hard with him. He is mounting some of us in the family and we try to discourage it by telling him to sit. He gets over aroused like we learned in class. Need some tips on how to calm him when he gets like that.  He is doing much better with heel. He is sleeping well. He loves to play and go outside. He likes to do what we ask him. He loves to be with people. He is a scavenger/sniffer. He demand barks at our other dog. They are both getting along fine now, but she doesn't want him in her bed, etc. He barks when she chews a bone and we try to distract him and give him a bone. He is a bit jealous of her we think. We are really enjoying him. He is super sweet except when he gets hyped up and nips and tries to mount. Hope this helps.

GeneralComments: Liesel has been a challenge for me. She is not a confident dog at all.  She can be pet and touched in any way with no problem but the second you ask her to wear something she melts.  We've been battling diarrhea and demadex the last month or so. I don't know how to help her gain confidence because she is not very motivated. she has no toy drive other than fetching a tennis ball which she will not do if she is stressed or somewhere new. she will take food but its not enough most cases.  Ive done several 1 on 1's trying to help her best I can. Shes a great dog and is a joy to have in the house if there is no pressure.

She is a really nice puppy. It has been hard with only working with her on the weekends but i feel we are not far from being on track. She does have some funk behaviors im learning to work around such as she is hesitant to approach  almost anyone minus me directly.. she will no come straight to you... i have been working on this starting by squating down and working my way up but it has only solved me not my family. she will come to them but she will come to thier side or their back. She also will alert bark or almost fear bark when we are walking down town and there is a person off in the distance.. we have gone 3 days now and today she did it once and then was fine with the rest!! ( YEY for imrovement!!) She is a slow processor ( takes a while to think ) about what she is asked. but in time she will do it. Not very food or toy motivated expecially in new places or when she is nervous. so finding what helps her has been tough but she is good with physical attention which is something i need to learn more about. Very high energy but a VERY nice and sweet girl!! she will be a lot of ful to have full time.

Took direction from other volunteers.

ExerciseType: running, walking, fetch, running up and down steps
GeneralComments: Fiesta has been consistently improving with all her commands and obedience training. She settles well  during the day and sleeps well in her crate at night.  Her counter-surfing has improved and she does exceptionally well on her outings to the mall and other places we visit.  She will pull occasionally when on the leash if she sees another dog so she can get distracted, but this too has improved over the months. Fiesta did have some stomach issues a few weeks ago which involved throwing up every few days, but the vet ran extensive tests and did not find any digestive issues.  The Vet felt it t was possibly stomach inflammation due to ingesting an acorn or stick???  After treating with medication and feeding Fiesta low residue food, she has improved and the throwing up stopped.  We just started giving her Iams lamb and rice 2 days ago and she just threw up yesterday.  After speaking to the Vet today, they recommended continuing with Low residue food for the next 2 days and Very SLowly introducing the Iams back in her diet over the next week.  Her energy level is fabulous and she seems confident and happy.

FoodType: Low residue + 1 spoon of canned pumpkin
ExerciseType: Walks, play time with other dogs & people, mental exercise (drills)
GeneralComments: Did extremely well on his 2 week sit with the Wanek family. He had lots of practice settling and going to sleep in new areas with new people, which has been something that we've been working on.  What I am writing is how he was up until two weeks ago (just picked him up today): He is very friendly with new people and happy to see them, but will not sleep near them. When we leave him with family members (while I am still in the house, but otherwise occupied), he does not lie down and settle or nap.  Crating is still a challenge. He will settle in the crate if someone is in the same room as him and he can see them, but has great difficulty when he can't see them.  His diarrhea problems seem to have resolved. After he gets settled back in at home, I plan on transitioning him off of low res. He is gaining weight steadily now (over 23.5 lbs as of 1/10).  I think he is ready for a vest.

When we leave him with family members (while I am still in the house, but otherwise occupied), he does not lie down and settle or nap.  Crating is still a challenge. He will settle in the crate if someone is in the same room as him and he can see them, but has great difficulty when he can't see them.  His diarrhea problems seem to have resolved. After he gets settled back in at home, I plan on transitioning him off of low res. He is gaining weight steadily now (over 23.5 lbs as of 1/10).  I think he is ready for a vest.
Daria is a very sweet, friendly, and willing pup. She is a pleasure to raise.

We are enjoying Daria greatly! We find that she tunes in to her handler(s) more than other pups we have raised, even in distracting situations. She has a pleasant manner around the house - loves to cuddle and be with her people. She has also been more confident than we anticipated. One challenge for Daria has been her interaction with our dog Obie - she tends to frequently chew at his ears, jowls and tail - we have used distractions, time outs, and positive reinforcement and she has improved in this area.We are really enjoying raising Daria.
Daria is a wonderful pup.  She has had multiple experiences with us and with puppy-sitters. She has preformed well. Her expression of stress can be very subtle.

ExerciseType: Walk, romp with homeboy Scout, tug of war, swim.
GeneralComments: Chaz exhibits high drive, independence of thought, and a huge desire to please (and play, and eat). He is always ready, willing, and able to get going and gets bored if a working trip, walk, or play date is not in the immediate future - however and very importantly - he will settle down with a toy and play until it is time to go (our unofficial command is: "Not yet - soon").   He is extremely social, wants to meet everyone, wants to play with every dog he sees, and has generally charmed everyone with whom he interacts. His enthusiasm is well-tempered and the few times he forgets his restraint, he corrects quickly and willingly.  The two things that would be of concern as a working dog are his high dog distraction and his great unwillingness to let you fuss with his paws, especially to trim his nails (a first in the the now 9 GEB dogs we've raised). We are confident the genius trainers at GEB will overcome both barriers to his success as a guide (dare we even hope stud?).  We will greatly miss Chaz and he has already charmed one potential partner, Mario Bonds, who plans to retire GEB Guide Sidney (whom we raised and look forward to welcoming home later this year).  We remain proud, honored, and lucky to be working with GEB and the tremendous dogs produced and trained there. We look forward to upping our game with the 10th pup.

ExerciseType: Running, walking, swimming, some gymnastics (jumping up on structures)
GeneralComments: Chaz is a lovable, eager, well-mannered, enthusiastic dog (like so many GEB pups). He has been a pleasure to raise.  He learns quickly and will try just about anything once, but will refuse to do things that he really doesn't like if he didn't like it the first time (jump off a pier, go through a long slippery play tunnel on the jungle gym - short ones are OK).   He seemed to take a little longer to mature than the other dogs we have raised and lose his attachment to his primary raiser. Now he can now be handled by other people, though still looks for me when separated, but no longer whines or looks distressed. Our class exercises made a huge difference.  Chaz has the drive, initiative, and interest in working as he gets bored easily and is always ready to go when he sees his leash, vest, and pack being readied for an outing. One of our puppy sitters put him in outfits for Halloween and reported that he enjoyed the process.  The one area that I cannot achieve improvement is in clipping his nails. He has always disliked having his paws touched, but allows us to wipe them before entering the house if we don't linger too long on a paw, otherwise he feints a bite. He writhes and howls if I attempt to clip his nails, and even with my husband holding him and feeding him treats, he still gets very upset. Luckily his nails do not grow very much (compared to our own dog Scout whose nails must be trimmed every week). A sitter touched his feet without issues, but the problem is if you linger on a foot for too long (say long enough to trim the nails). I feel rather defeated on this issue (I clip the nails on many of the dogs who stay with us and have had no problems - even when they are a little unsure at first. Only one other dog - a beagle/dachshund mix - had the same loud and boisterous reaction to having her feet touched for trimming and I gave up so as not to upset her too much).  He settles very nicely and has charmed every human he meets. We would love to see him bred.

ExerciseType: Play with homeboy Scout, chase toys, walk, swim.
GeneralComments: Chaz is a spunky, eager, loving pup who is often so impatient for his next challenge, task, or outing, that he can forgot to empty his bladder or bowels when given the chance, and will hurry into things until he is asked to take a moment to settle and check-in. He is a go-go dog, and yet, when he is asked to settle at your feet, he will happily occupy himself with a chew toy and fall asleep. He is always ready and willing and can be a great companion.    His feet sensitivity and lack of elimination awareness are his two worst issues, but have been improving over time. Clipping the nails has gotten a little more dramatic, but touching his feet to clean has improved. When asked to GB he will sit and then want to rush on to the meal or play or walk and then realize that he has to go, so we plan for that when working with him. This has made us a little concerned about overnights, although those have not been an issue in the past.  All in all we love him, as we have all eight other dogs we've raised for GEB, and think with more work he has guide potential.
