ExerciseType: Walking, retrieving toys with older dogs in the yard, some wading/swimming.
GeneralComments: Chaz is a lovely, calm little fellow. When in the house he is well mannered and responsive. Walking on leash he seems at ease, curious, and engaged with his surroundings. He readily approaches strange things and likes to explore. He can keep up with the big dogs (GEB Sidney who is visiting and home boy Scout) and holds his own showing confidence and willingness to challenge them for toys.  Sherry, Janet, and I observed that unlike other pups we've raised, Chaz is quite unhappy when handled by another person; he yelps, pulls away from the handler, and rears for me whether I am hidden or in plain view. We are working on that issue in our one-on-one sessions and have a home stay planned in the next few weeks.

FoodType: Evo or Orijen Large Breed usually Red Meat
ExerciseType: Walking, retrieving toys with older dogs in the yard, wading/swimming.
GeneralComments: Chaz is a sweet, calm puppy with a very pleasant energy level who walks nicely on leash. He is willing to follow commands and has become bolder about going into challenging situations such as retrieving toys in a surging stream. Due to several injuries and some travel, I have not given him as much exposure as would be expected at this age - our outings have been limited. I see no reason, however, to thing that he will not thrive with increased exposure as he is curious, observant, and willing. He likes to take things slowly, so we are matching his preference in our outings and find that he settles well after initial exposure to new things (no dander or scratching). We are very much enjoying raising him and think he has what it takes to become a guide.

FoodType: Iam's Smart Puppy / Iam's Low Residue transition
GeneralComments: Overall, I think Sidney is doing very well. At home, he doesn't beg or bark or chew or have accidents. He loves to learn and after just a few repetitions he has it down without the need for a lure. My biggest challenge with him has been a growing independent streak coupled with natural curiosity.  His behavior away from home is a little different. He's easily excited around other animals, but surprisingly good with strangers (he's calm, quiet, cooperative and well-behaved in stores and at the vet). Class seems to be the most difficult time for Sidney. He's barked a few times, won't settle and doesn't respond to commands he knows inside and out in every other situation (at home and elsewhere). Last week, he also peed twice in class, which is difficult to understand given that he got busy right before class started, and again after the first accident about 20 minutes later. Still, it's my fault, I'm sure he was giving me some signal which I missed because I was also distracted.

GeneralComments: He's doing great. There was a week in late Feb when he was so bad it was like he was a different dog. He was humping everything, destroying everything in sight, digging, barking, acting out and generally giving me his best Alpha impression. It passed as quickly as it came on and he's back to being the sweet, well-behaved puppy he's always been. I'm hoping it was just a one time thing and not a sign of the hormonal changes to come. The main issue Sidney has is his ability to be alone and entertain himself. His response to commands is also a little unpredictable lately.

FoodType: Mix of Purina ONE & occasional Low Res
GeneralComments: Rodeo is an enjoyable pup to raise- He has a few challenges that we continue to work on- but overall- seems to be a pleasant pup. He is beginning to show an increase in sensitivity to traffic. He also has a tendency to scour the floor/ground for anything available to pick up-- even crumbs, etc-- (appears more of a coping mechanism than desire to scavenge-- this was seen since very early puppyhood-- and makes some improvement, and then falls back into needing work again, etc-- and his other big challenge is relaxing with a calm head/mouth when being petted-- he tends to get aroused and swivel head/lick/and occasionally mouth...

Rodeo is an enjoyable pup. He is making progress in all areas. He had some initial "car sickness/quesiness" which has improved with exposure. He shows some arousal around dogs- which is improving using 3D's and PackWalk/parallel play. Human greetings are also a challenge-- excited to greet everyone. Although he can be a little sensitive at times- using short exposures and plenty of breaks, and repeated exposure- his confidence seems to improve with time... Love Him!!!! Medically- his only challenge is soft stool/diarrhea as he transitions off low res. He gets pumpkin added to food, and a probiotic digestive supplement (Lactoquil) which seem to help a bit...

Rodeo continues to be a fun dog to raise. To list his current top two challenges: 1. will raise hackles on back if aroused-- such as hearing dogs barking in distance, seeing unusual action out of reach (such as leaves blowing in distance), etc-- but if given time- he will self modulate; 2. he does have a tendency to be "oral" and "olfactory"-- picking up things (grass, mulch, crumbs on floor, sniffs in new environments  etc-- seems to exhibit this behavior as a displacement type behavior...Both show improvement at times, but both challenges have re-surfaced at times throughout his raising-- especially when he is tasked with new challenges...

ExerciseType: 2 - 2 1/2 mile walks, frisbee, ball, outdoor play with other dogs
GeneralComments: Patty continues to be a very sweet, loving, and highly energetic pup.  She is extremely intelligent, is aware when she is not acting appropriately, but, seems to be that rebellious teenager on occassion when she jumps on the counter for the cat or takes something that doesn't belong to her.  Her demeaner changes when she puts on the Guiding Eyes vest, she seems to know that it means she is working.  She behaved politely at both Pet People and the Captain's stadium outings.  She was wonderful as the mascot at the Willoughby classic car show this summer.  When out in public, she is a good representative of the program as people always comment on how well she behaves for being only 1 year old.  Patty will be participating in the Disability Awareness Group presentations at Progressive Insurance in October.  I have high aspirations for her future success.

GeneralComments: Patty is a wonderful, even tempered pup.  She has been a pleasure to raise for Guiding Eyes.  She is highly intelligent and very willing to please.  She does, however, still have her puppy ways at times, and can tend to get overly excited.  A redirection of this energy, and away from the other dogs in the house, typically works.    We will surely miss her and our house will feel very empty once she leaves.  But, knowing the job we raised her for, will make the emptiness a little easier to handle.

ExerciseType: Running on a log line in the field, fetch, walks
GeneralComments: I'm not really sure how to answer the house manners question since house manners contains so many different parts and some of them he's really good at and others not so much. Like food bowl manners, not chasing people, and crate acceptance he's really good at. But for like get busy and chewing he's not. So that's why I put a three for that.  Then for the leash stuff on leash inside he will come when I call him but when we get outside where there are more distractions I have to call him a couple times before he comes. With out a leash on is different though. Inside when he is off leash he comes but I don't have a fenced in yard so I don't know if he would come off leash outside or not. For the furniture like I said he's only just gotten big enough to really be able to reach to jump on it so it's something new that we have had to start working on.  Then I didn't know what to say about the home visits because he has sort of been on four home switches. Kerry's house to the Paulsons' house to Michelle's house and finally to my house.

I am working on all of the things that have low scores on them. I am asking my instructors what to do and also other raisers what to do and am trying what they suggest. For eliminating on walks I will stand outside for 20 minutes telling him to get busy and he won't go so I think he doesn't have to go and we start walking and we get half a black from the house and he goes. Like I said up in the section for comments the streets I walk him on are empty the majority of the time so I walk him down the middle of the road so he cannot sniff anything but he still goes. And he goes because he can smell everything from there anyway. He has a fabulous nose. I put him in his crate in my room and then go out to the kitchen and open a jar of peanut butter and not two seconds later he is barking because he can smell it and he wants it. When we play hide and seek I don't call his name anymore because he smells something of mine and then he tracks me. I did not teach him that he taught himself that.

Meyer is really sweet but does have a lot of red flags. His bad habits include the poor potty manners and the countersurfing/stealing. I will say re: the countersurfing that we've made some progress in convincing him that we do not like it, plus we're better able to anticipate when it will happen to try and prevent it. He is clearly stealing things that we value, like the remote or our phones, or things he wants to eat or play with, like his toys that might be out of reach. He is extremely smart and tuned into us. He shadows us everywhere and is very responsive to our commands for the most part.

Loretta is a great dog.  Her only issues are chewing bedding in her kennel when left unattended.  Therefore, I put no bedding in her kennel.  She will bark when in the kennel if we are out of the room and she can still hear us.  If we leave, she does not bark (I set up a recorder to check that one.)  She also torments our older dog wanting to play - biting on his collar.  She adapts well to new situations and loves meeting new people and dogs.  (Although, she can get a bit too rambunctious.)

ExerciseType: walks, toy play and appropriate dog play
GeneralComments: I have some concerns with Knight as I feel that he is easily stressed. He demonstrates signs of stress even when walking down our street (which is a quiet neighborhood). We are careful where we take him to ensure quieter environments with short positive experiences which we repeat with similar variables (ie. time of day etc). His stress level seems to escalate quickly even when working in the same parking lots or our neighborhood and we are careful to end them before he enters the "red zone". I am concerned as he does not appear to become more comfortable in these repeated experiences. In the last month he has started to "loose his brain" while at home-puppy scooting which he has only done several times before (ie. last eval) when he has gotten too stressed. I have discussed concerns with Belvie and we have trialed giving him more kennel time throughout the day as well as play time alone with "special toys" (ie. skinzees and other toys that seem to provide him an outlet). These techniques have seemed to help his stress at home.

GeneralComments: Justin is not the most confident guy so we tend to work in short spurts. He has real attachment to me in class, so its difficult to work him in class because he will bark at me. Bad house manner things have just started popping up, so we are working on that with supervision and rewarding good behavior in the kitchen. He doesn't have a high energy and is easy, in that sense. He bites pretty hard at class when taking treats and everyone complains about it, so we have been trying to work on that, but its not getting through too well. He has awesome check ins and WWP is usually pretty easy with him, especially if he's on a long line.

ExerciseType: walks, play dates, play with me in an enclosed area
GeneralComments: Gilda is a sweet, really well behaved dog for her age. One of my main concerns is her confidence level. She is not generally confident in new situations (like construction, bus rides, sirens). Usually her behavior just changes subtly, like her ears prick back. I have been trying to combat that by giving her repeated, positive exposures until she is confident in that situation and then working our way up to more distracting situations. Usually after she has experienced something 2-3 times it is no longer an issue. She is also very attached to me. I think she would benefit from some time listening to someone else (like maybe swapping dogs in class). Gilda tends to get concerned when I leave the room or am working with another dog. She tries to shadow me around the house and will sometimes open doors and get around other obstacles to get to me.

Guava arrived Oct 27 (as of today Nov 23, 4 weeks).    I included notes from her previous raiser and RM Nicole as a baseline:    - Her name response is great!  - She has average energy and can get overwhelmed in too busy of an environment for her.  Raiser lives in a quieter area of Manhattan if that is possible and Guava does well there.  When there was a bike race in her familiar area she became overwhelmed and needed to take it slow.  - She is reported to have minor crating issues but the raiser lives in an apartment complex and has never had any complaints.   - She went to the beach on a long line and tended to pick on the younger shepherd that was with the group.  - She gets excited about people rather than dogs.  She can self modulate well but needs to work on greetings.   - There are two short videos of Guava playing with GEB pup Karat (11 wks old) and then GEB Mandrake (8 mos. Old).  Guava initially played well with Karat for about 5 minutes or so and then Guava started grabbing on KaratÆs neck, ears, etc and was being very rude. We separated the dogs but Guava kept going back at Karat.  I then had Guava play with an older dog (Mandrake) and they played very appropriately with a toy for about 10-15 minutes.  Not sure if your potential raiser has other dogs at home but I thought I would share that info in case it mattered.  - The biggest thing that I observed about Guava is her noise sensitivity.  As youÆll notice, where we were filming was a pretty busy area in Manhattan with lots of cars and general noise.  Guava seemed fine with this constant noise as she was able to work well with Julia but she was definitely very aware of all the sounds around her û her ears moved around a lot.  There were a few moments when she would hear a sudden loud noise (a motorcycle for example), which would cause her to startle/rush a bit but she seemed to have good recovery.     In comparison to her previous evaluation, not much has changed.  The following is what I am seeing now (one month later):  - no crate issues  - attention barking just for a few minutes when left alone where humans and dogs are insight. Then will settle quietly.  - makes "bunny ears" (ears straight back and laying against head) when alarmed by loud sudden noises.  Recovers quickly and will re-approach objects emitting noise  - No prior history was mention about body handling.  That is one big thing we noticed immediately when we first got her. She does not like to be restrained.  Specifically when rolled on her back, extreme stiffening of her body.  - But oddly enough, will allow you to handle and hold her toes during nail clipping.    - Is unforgiving for quite some time after being released from being restrained.  - have found food does not work as effectively since food gets her too aroused thus adding more stress  - have found successful progression with doing many frequent quick "catch-and-release" method of restraint  - very rude dog play with Brady and Anders, lots of neck biting.  But plays respectfully with older dogs like Leonardo, Ensign, Champ  - I take her to my Dulles Gateway puppy class and she interacted and played politely with the other puppies. She is able to work with any handler. She is an amazingly quick study!  - loves riding in crate in the car  - knows her behaviors  - on socialization outings, super well behaved and responsive to name and loose leash and settling  - good energy level.  Requires average level of exercise and low energy level indoors.

Specifically when rolled on her back, extreme stiffening of her body.  - But oddly enough, will allow you to handle and hold her toes during nail clipping.    - Is unforgiving for quite some time after being released from being restrained.  - have found food does not work as effectively since food gets her too aroused thus adding more stress  - have found successful progression with doing many frequent quick "catch-and-release" method of restraint  - very rude dog play with Brady and Anders, lots of neck biting.  But plays respectfully with older dogs like Leonardo, Ensign, Champ  - I take her to my Dulles Gateway puppy class and she interacted and played politely with the other puppies. She is able to work with any handler. She is an amazingly quick study!  - loves riding in crate in the car  - knows her behaviors  - on socialization outings, super well behaved and responsive to name and loose leash and settling  - good energy level.  Requires average level of exercise and low energy level indoors.

The biggest thing we are working on now is polishing his house manners. He seems to have them down, but will regress every once in awhile. He also tends to act up in the house when he thinks we aren't paying enough attention to him (for example, he is most likely to steal a shoe off the floor when I'm talking on the phone). He is doing MUCH better with the loose leash walking and not picking up rocks and licking cracks. However, this is still his first reaction when he is in the red zone, or if he is bored. (For example, I notice sometimes when we are waiting for the T to come or if we are just sitting somewhere and not really doing anything, he will put his head down and start licking dirt. Generally, though, he will look up when you say his name and that makes him stop. Or sometimes I will start talking to him and that will help him stop.)

He is very good when out in public. He attends class with Rachael and I at least 3 times a week, and has a great settle. We have even brought him to two plays at Robsham theatre, he slept through both. We have also brought him into the city, into various stores, and he rides very well on the T as well as on public buses. Our biggest obstacle right now is working out certain house manner issues (stealing items, sticking head in trash). We are also working on jumping when over-excited during people greetings, he seems to be making some progress. He no longer jumps on us (myself, Rachael, our roommate Alexis), when greeting us, but tends to do it with visitors.

Bette is a very easy and happy puppy.    We are working on continuing to build confidence in traffic, on stairs and in new situations.  She is a tongue flicker!  When excited, she definitely straddles the green line, but can almost always self-modulate.  There are two people that she absolutely loves and all bets are off when she sees them, but she has made great progress in ignoring people when we are shopping and in other scenarios where there are lots of people and distractions.  Nothing makes her happier than seeing the jacket and leash come out -- except for maybe seeing the treat bag being filled:-)

Bette is a sweet but at times very "activated" pup.  She is eager to learn and has done well tuning in and being in the think and learn zone, even with distractions, when she knows there will be treats.  As I told Carrie, she has been extremely slow in figuring out stairs.  At first, if it was more than one step, she would simply jump over the other step.  Gradually, she could handle 3 or 4 at the most.  Had no interest in the flight of stairs at home until last week, when she surprised me by coming up on her own and then followed me down, with no barking or whining.  She probably went up and down 10 times that day, so excited to discover the 2nd level of the house!  She now goes up and down happily, but is still sorting out her "technique"   As instructed in her paperwork from GEB, I did not attempt to lure her in any way.  I think she'll be fine, but got off to a very late start with stairs.   She also does not like to be held or handled and that has been true from the day I picked her up at the CDC!  She is the first pup that I've raised that wasn't a dream to handle!!!  She will let me hold her and love on her when she is sleepy or just waking up from a nap and so I am trying to seize those moments.  She is getting better with me, but will not tolerate it at all with others.  All in all, another great GEB pup!

Trent is very well behaved and responds to all of his commends on the first or second time of me asking. He has trouble focusing around other dogs and sometimes ignores me completely. I am trying to be more exciting than the other dogs while working with him, he has gotten much better than when we first started. He barks very often. We have recently started doing puppy pushups when he barks. He does not enjoy these, but it seems to be helping. After a few sets of these, he stops the barking. While walking he tries to pick up rocks, leaves, and sticks. If I tell him "out" he will normally drop it and keep going. I've started leaving him out of the kennel while I shower, he does not do anything wrong. I often get out to find him laying by the bathroom door right where he was when I left. He can be trusted to not do anything wrong when alone or not given full attention, besides grabbing paper towels out of the garbage. Those are the only things he will take out of the trash. He's very sweet and loving, but he is constantly touching me, whether it be chewing a bone next to me, laying a paw across me/laying on top of my feet, or sitting in my lap if i'm on the floor.

ExerciseType: swimming, retrieving, playing with other dogs, hikes, walks
GeneralComments: Sheena is an incredibly sweet, sensitive pup with a nice energy level. She's easy to work with and eager to please.  At times Sheena seems to have an acute visual and auditory sensitivity to her environment. Even on walks within the neighborhood she still continues to need to stop and watch people come out of there houses, stop and observe other dogs, etc.  Once she has taken it in, she's ready to move on.   She continues to have dog distraction within the classroom setting but when out working with other pups she seems to handle it fine.  Sheena can quickly go into the yellow zone during an outing and many repeat exposures have proven very beneficial for her.

Sheena is a terrific addition to our home & we are throughly enjoying her!!

His energy level is  manageable and his  barking is a problem only when he is frustrated - usually when there are other dogs around. Outside of class he settles well almost all of the time now wherever we go but as soon as we pull into the parking lot for class, he's wired and doesn't come down. I really have to dig my heels in when she starts to pull because at that point she doesn't even respond to high rewards.

ExerciseType: walks and runs around and plays
GeneralComments: We switched with Janie for a week. She's a 1 yr old, and very mellow. It was amazing to see such a difference in the levels of 'energy''/stimulation. I felt fine letting Janie be free in the house and unsupervised (ie: leaving the teenagers bed room door open), but with Jerome, I still feel I need to keep an eye on him all the time.  We have 'baby-proofed' the house, so there really isn't much for him to get into, but I still have the urgency to watch him.  DId not feel like that at all with Janie, actually I felt like Janie was just like my dog, hanging out. Jerome is walking fairly well on the leash, again comparing to Janie, he's much more 'active'. I guess the age has a lot to do with it as well.  Karen (swap mom) has said that Jerome is licking her other dogs ears and mouth, and he does the same with my older dog only, and chews his ears.  I thought this was something he only did with my older dog due to Newton (old guy) not being able to tell him to back off, and get out of Jerome's grasp.  Jerome will not lick or chew my lab, but likes to try when he wants to play.

I felt fine letting Janie be free in the house and unsupervised (ie: leaving the teenagers bed room door open), but with Jerome, I still feel I need to keep an eye on him all the time.  We have 'baby-proofed' the house, so there really isn't much for him to get into, but I still have the urgency to watch him.  DId not feel like that at all with Janie, actually I felt like Janie was just like my dog, hanging out. Jerome is walking fairly well on the leash, again comparing to Janie, he's much more 'active'. I guess the age has a lot to do with it as well.  Karen (swap mom) has said that Jerome is licking her other dogs ears and mouth, and he does the same with my older dog only, and chews his ears.  I thought this was something he only did with my older dog due to Newton (old guy) not being able to tell him to back off, and get out of Jerome's grasp.  Jerome will not lick or chew my lab, but likes to try when he wants to play.

ExerciseType: Walk/ Playing with our Golden Retriever
GeneralComments: When we first got frontier he was very excitable and would play bite but I found taking him for walks the problem went away.  Until we left him with a sitter he was very nippy.  When we returned the first week he would get over excited and run around crazy and jump and nip at me (thinking he was playing) Not playful in my eyes.  After a few days things got under control.  This past week he was growling at my golden retriever and biting his tail when I told him to stop it started again he runs around my dining room table and at me biting at my arm four times till I could get him to stop.  It is like he snaps!  The next night he had something he should not have I told him out and when I went to take it he nipped at my arm again (playful to him).  It seems like he gets to this over excited stage and goes nuts!

Bill is a very sweet, smart boy. However, his energy level is overwhelming and sometimes unpleasant. I come home from school each day at noon and take him either on a walk, to the park or to the mall until about 2:30. When I come back from practice at 5, we go for another walk or just play fetch at the house. He has endless energy and even after tons of play and work, he has a very difficult time winding down. I try body handling each night, but it just stimulates him even more and we've made little progress in that area. Recently, Bill has become very demanding. If I am doing homework he constantly nudges me and has started growling. I have tried verbal corrections, the 'go place' command, and ignoring him, but nothing seems to be working so far.

ExerciseType: training, playing, retrieving, playing in water, walking
GeneralComments: Adora will have her first overnight next week.    Adora is smart and a quick learner.  She loves people and loves to snuggle.  She is growing quickly.  Adora is confident and well behaved in most situations.  She has been to wineries, museums, schools, parks, and stores and enters all new situations confidently.    Adora can be fearless.  She is confident enough to stand up to our Mastiff/Rottweiler and not back down.      She loves to "lead" our other dogs, taking them by the collar or leash and pulling.    She is still having accidents occassionally.  Adora is easily excitable.  Excited people make her extremely excited and she can be hard to pull away from the situation.    Adora is very food oriented, but picky.  The food rewards have to keep increasing.  She will not work for dog food.

Adora is younger than the other pups.  She sits, stands and downs with one food reward.  She makes many checks in on follow-me, and always comes to her name being called no matter what the distraction is.  She will sit for quite some time in close.  Adora prefers to be close and have human contact whenever possible (she is snuggly).    She is still having accidents in the house (pee only).    Adora had a rough first two weeks with diarrhea.  She isn't able to eat the Iams, and she had a main diet of Chicken and Rice.  We have switch her to the low residue and Puppy Chow, and we are phasing out the low residue.  Adora is doing well on this diet.    We are working hard on house manners including staying off counters, out of the dishwasher and leaving other other dogs alone when they are 'up" (couches or beds).

Talent is growing into a confident girl - whose developing a lot of spunk!   We continue to work with her alarm barking. Its gotten much better - its not a constant thing - seems very situational - mostly inside my home and especially on a windy day when the house is creaking and making funny sounds.   Last night we came upon a strange person in the shadows, a summertime neighbor looking for a cell signal. He's a big burly guy and Talent alerted me to his presence - hackles up, she was ready for any and all contingencies. When she saw who it was, she was a wiggle worm - so happy to see him.  Still no signs of heat - doing a lot of grooming back there though.

GeneralComments: Susie is a great pup, I love seeing the progress over these past 10 months that i have had her, especially in the last few.  She is putting 2 and 2 together.  At her previous W&T we discussed her stress level when out in the community.  Robin was able to see this as Susie would drop and tune me out.  I continue to give her time to relax, know where she is, and bring a stress relieving toy with us.  She is much better but still does a "drop and tune out" , especially when we leave a store.  Many times an outing will consist only of checking in with each other for a short period of time and then come home.

GeneralComments: On Susie's papers when I received her at 8 weeks it said give her time to think.  She still needs time to think when we first arrive somewhere. I work with her to check in and reward her generously  Susie is a strong willed pup and challenges me to work with her to get the most out of her.  We both enjoy outings and exploring new places.  Susie is a wonderful pup to raise and I have learned a great deal from her.

He is doing great. He walks loose-leash much better than he used to. He listens well, and he stays attentive for much longer than he used to. He does get distracted easily, especially in new places. We have been taking him out about 4 times a week, but we have been trying to increase that to 5 times a week. With more socialization, we are sure he will improve on his attentiveness as well as his manners around new people. He knows all his commands and does them with ease. His duration on all of his commands have improved but with new handlers, we are told he still needs work. We also have some concerns about him "humping" other dogs, specifically Tamara's three. He also occasionally attempts to "hump" people if we are on the ground playing with him and he gets excited.

Micah is really great with commands and house manners. He is learning "Go place" very well, and can do close with ease. We need to practice greetings with him as well as appropriate biting, as those are his weakest areas. Aaron is a bit weaker with loose leash walking, but we are practicing that with him just about every day. Since we have gotten Micah, we have noticed vast improvements in his "bad" habits and we have eliminated most of them. We still have problems with Micah putting his paw up when doing commands like over and come.

ExerciseType: fetch, playing with other dogs, walking
GeneralComments: Micah has improved on his 3Ds since last eval. We've participating in lots of classes which has helped. Have tried to increase the outings to be more challenging but not overwhelming for him. My work has been busy during April & my time with Micah has diminished b/c of that. He also injuried his leg which had to be rested for couple of weeks. Should be able to spend more time with him next month (May). Greetings are better but not perfect. He will get aroused & try to nip but it is less often than it was. Don't always set it up for him to be successful every time.

ExerciseType: walking, fetch, playing with other dogs
GeneralComments: Micah passed his CGC test on 10/27!!! Yay for us! So, he's shown enough improvement to do that since last eval.We've used check it out A LOT with a gradual drop in the need to use it or the length of time needed to use it in new situations. I need help with greetings -- not sure that I'm doing them correctly with Micah at this point. Depending on person, he may want to get mouthy with them. We're working on his durations for sit/down/stay. It's better. I've added few new commands (get dressed, back). Not done go place at all.Started working more on his body handling & it needs much work. His dog play has improved, but still have to watch him for getting too rough/aroused in his dog play. Overall Micah is much improved since I got him at last eval. We still have alot to work on but I'm very proud of Micah.

ExerciseType: fetch, playing with other dogs, walking
GeneralComments: Have seen improvement in Micah since last eval, but at slower rate. His duration & ability to handle distractions with his commands have improved. His people distractions seem to have gotten worse in the past 2 weeks, but I think his dog distraction has improved. Body handling has little improvement (mainly due to my lack of doing it). I still don't have his people greetings where they need to be. We did the people pack walk prior to the holidays & then didn't do it over the holidays. It seems like Micah's at square 1 with greetings. We definitely need help with that. Also, I need to discuss with you Micah 'poking' me to get my attention. I think I've handled that completely wrong. His behavior/interaction with my dogs (& other dogs) during play is great. I still see dander when we go to new places, but he doesn't need to do check it out as often or as long as he originally did. I don't think that I'm pushing him too hard. I'm pleased with his progress overall.

Overall, he is a fantastic dog. If I were blind, this is the dog I would want to have guiding me. One thing I should mention - last week - he had a very strong negative reaction to a skateboard and skateboarder. Backed away, barked once. The kid was very understanding, got off the board and let Nordic investigate. He did, cautiously at first. Then the kid resumed skateboarding and we watched for about 30 minutes at ever decreasing distances. After about 15 min Nordic had completely recovered - could be within a few feet and ignoring the activity. We will follow up with repeated careful exposure.

After about 15 min Nordic had completely recovered - could be within a few feet and ignoring the activity. We will follow up with repeated careful exposure.

Moose walks well on lead when prompted to and with enthusiastic encouragement throughout the walk, but when the handler is silent he does not focus on them and will pull.  When he is excited and playful, he wants to play immediately and will paw your leg, sometimes biting  feet or pants.  He takes to new handlers very well and is eager and willing to work with a variety of handlers. He has been some new sitters' first sit and they have reported having a very pleasant time with him!   Most of the time he settles well and will sleep through college classes.  He is a gentle and submissive player with other dogs, always carrying a toy. He plays very well with the teeny puppies.

Since it often results in scavenging I have decreased the amount of checking out that he is allowed to do (unless it's truly novel) and rather than moving forward in a new place we just hang in one spot until he becomes more interested in me than the floor.  Suggestions?

FoodType: Purinia One Puppy chow Lamb and Rice
ExerciseType: Supervised runs in fenced in pool area. Plays fetch. Nightly walks.
GeneralComments: Kismet  has settled into this family very well.  I was quite surprised since her kennel evaluation mention she was timid. Our Airedale passed away ten days ago and Kismet looked for her for the first few days but did not seem to stress over it. She loves to please us and will curl  on any family members lap when we are sitting on the floor. She learns quickly and follows me arround the house. Her average sleep time in the kennel is 8 to 9 hours. Her average kennel time during the day is about two hours. She rides well in the van, truck or PT Cruiser. She will sit or lay on the front floor board or be content to ride in her kennel in the back sit. She has shown no signs of stomach distress while riding in any vehicle. She settles well in a busy enviroment. This was noticed last Saturday when she attended my son's basketball games. We sat in the first row courtside and she layed on the floor nicely. Once in a while she would get up to check out people going up and down the bleachers. Her hearing is excellent and sometimes she hears many things that I don't. I think she is very confident young lady without any aggresive tendencies what so ever. Our largest obstacle right now is the transition from the lamb and rice puppy chow to a high end adult food. We are gradually adding adult food to her meals. Once she can tolerate the adult food we will feed her twice a day. She has behaved very well at our vet's office and he has commended us on her behavior. So far it has been a great experience for us to have such a wonderful animal share our home.

Godiva is going through an adolescent type period. She knows all of her commands and is routinely quite cooperative at home, but often acts silly at class ex. rolling completely over when given the command "over" and she is very distracted by other pups at class (so it is a challenge to keep her attention focused at class). She would play until she was exhausted if we allowed her to, but she will settle readily once she is reconnected with us. Very loving, will follow us from room to room without being called.

GeneralComments: Gaston is the most responsive of the three pups we have had.  His biggest difficulty is being distracted and the biggest distraction is dog distraction - he wants to play. Rides on front car floor well.

GeneralComments: Gaston is very social and well behaved with people - staying in Sunday worship for 1 hr. 30 minutes; coming forward with handler for communion and not trying to "steal" the bread and last week went with handler to receive offering row by row.  Will lay still in fast food restaurants.  Often in the office when visitors come and no longer needs to be crated in the office unless I leave him alone. Not a problem in the house at all.  Major difficulty is being around other dogs - improving but still needs work.  Does still pull at times when we begin walks.  Will now let the older dog finish his food without jumping in to steal it.

GeneralComments: Even with the amount of crate rest and restrictions that Fargo has had lately, I'm happy to see him step right back into things.  He seems a bit immature still as there's much that he hasn't encountered. He approaches things with a willingness to investigate and a general happiness to be out and about again though.  His favorite thing right now is people greetings, especially if they will pet him.  He is a sweet boy who tries super hard.  He has been a joy to get back to work with.

ExerciseType: walking, ball, play with other dogs
GeneralComments: Denton does very well if given the time he needs to check out an area and kept at the distance that he needs. He has had more success in the smaller black dog group than in the larger class setting; however, he did very well in his last regular class. He works very well in the smaller group of five dogs. Maintaining the distance that he needs keeps him focused and working well instead of frustrating both of us. We regularly do both people and dog pack walks, both of which seem to be good for him. We are going to be starting Sherry's Canine Good Citizen class next weekend, which will give us more opportunity to work around dogs in a controlled setting.

FoodType: Purina Pro Plan Large Breed Chicken
ExerciseType: walking, ball, play with other dogs
GeneralComments: There has been minimal to no pulling on walks since we got Denton. We have been working him in a no pull harness in areas with high distraction levels; however, he rarely tries to pull. We are now able to work him with his regular flat collar in areas with few or no distractions. Lunging has not been an issue. He has done well working in a group of up to 4 dogs. He has also done pack walks in groups of up to 4 dogs. Denton does not seem to know commands such as close, over, stand, and back. Those commands still need to be taught. We have already started teaching go place. Need to work on duration on all commands. Also need to continue to increase check-ins and name response.

GeneralComments: Anders is a very affectionate pup.  He loves his toys and is very oral -- always has to have something in his mouth, even on walks.  Anders loves to play with my two released labs but plays rough.  He is a bully, play bites and will stare and crouch down as they approach.  As mentioned above, he recently started to mark on walks as well as certain indoor areas as well as lift his leg.  Anders has alot of energy and willl zip up and down and all around w/o a care in the world.  Anders is very bouncy and tends to tune you out as he explores his surroundings.  Once he is totally satisfied,  he will settle down nicely.

GeneralComments: Autumn can be Awesome and responds readily to handler. She loves to go places and tries very hard to please. It's hard for her with her abundant energy, but she tries to control it.  She is a happy pup who loves people and likes to show it. Sometimes she will barks in class, but is quiet when out and about. She needs more work on her people greetings - hard in Woodstock as everyone is a trainer wanting to show me how and what to do - so much fun! If they don't want to train her, they say it's OK if she jumps. People are more of a challenge than Autumn. We are getting more exposures now and I hope to see great improvement in the near future.

ExerciseType: walks, playing in yard, working on fetch
GeneralComments: Alfred continues to have problems interacting with other dogs. He lunges at dogs who pass him on walks and has bitten others in community run at class. Currently I have chosen to avoid these situations and am now concentrating on several areas where he may benefit from improvement: 1-getting/playing with toys; 2-calmly greeting guests at home; 3-sitting and waiting at doors, especially when leaving rooms and going outside to play; 4-coming when called when off-leash; 5-polite play with our dog. I am trying to be really consistant and he is responding well, especially waiting at doors, even when our dog charges through, and coming when called. I finally found a toy he likes and we have been practicing a lot of 'get a toy' and fetch.

ExerciseType: walks 1/2 mile in am & 3/4 mile later on- plus training for day in Town etc.
GeneralComments: Simba is a very quick learner. He handles new situations very easily, but has a tendency to keep his excitement inside. Once he gets home he will play hard with Jethro as a kind of  'release'! He hears songbirds and will listen to them. If I whistle or use a wistle he gets very excited. I am exposing him to lots of sounds. If he is unsure he will hold his ears back (much like a horse does).  We walk to visit horses alot. He is happy to see them and has been muzzle to muzzle with them. I do wish I could video him while I train him. He is a joyful player (like his Mom, Irena). He settles very well in the house- I am working on outside 'settles' where he is weaker.

ExerciseType: stair play inside, play with pet dog & 1-2 mile walk daily
GeneralComments: My biggest concern is Simba is very attached to me. He comes looking for me now more often than he used to. My husband reports that Simba looks for me even when he's home with him & I'm away.  He has a tendency to 'talk' (not bark- though he will do this occasionally,too) I am trying to eliminate this behavior.  His stair regression- is somewhat worrisome. He did stairs perfectly well until 7 months old. Now, I must plan carefully where I take him, so I don't get stranded.  He is a gleeful, sweet, playful dog- but is less confident than Jethro or Hamilton (2H08) were. Simba learns in a very gradual way (he gets there- but needs time to process).   He does love being touched and will stand very still for brushing & massages!

ExerciseType: Simba walks 3 miles a day. He plays with our pet dog & trains in public daily.
GeneralComments: Simba has developed a fear of some stairs that he has walked up successfully months ago. His sense of hearing is acute and makes metal rampways  a concern for him. His first ferry trip to Martha's Vineyard was easier for him than the 2nd one to Beacon, NY! The Newburg-Beacon Ferry had a very long approach over 3 different metal underfootings. Two moved in the water- one didn't. The ferry was LOUD in Newburgh. Once Simba had walked over the ramps to get to the ferry-his return walk was 'no problem'. We walked back & forth over all the metal underfootings again and again. He was happy and responding to commands and settling beside the other 2 dogs. He seems to take longer to process new experiences- and it is his sound  sensitivity that overwhelms him (I think). Hamilton & Jethro never hesitated when I would take them anywhere- if I was going- they were going with me. Simba, on the other hand just stopped at the deck of the Newburgh Ferry- even though I walked forward- he would not come until he managed to process the noise and what was expected of him. He is less adventurous and more tentative than the other pups I have rasied for GEB.

FoodType: Iams Puppy Chow (transitioning to adult food)
ExerciseType: walking on a leash around the town, occasional play in a fenced in dog park (with no other dogs)
GeneralComments: One major thing that we'd like some advice on is how to keep Payson from getting into things at home.  I don't think Payson needs more exercise, although he might calm down some once he is eating adult food with less protein.   We are also concerned about finding other dogs for him to play with.  He is friendly to dogs, but we want him to have more practice in greeting dogs so that he will learn to be more polite.  We don't know any people with dogs, so we are trying to think of ways to find different kinds of dogs for Payson to greet or play with.   Overall, we feel that Payson is progressing well.  We are constantly impressed by his improvements.  He is a great pup and we are really glad he is part of the family for the next year or so!

FoodType: Iams Lamb and Rice Adult food
ExerciseType: walking on a leash around the town, occasional play in a fenced-in dog park (with his friend Scarlett or alone)
GeneralComments: We have also noticed Payson sniffing more lately.  Sometimes, he is difficult to reconnect with during a sniffing session, if he is focused on an interesting smell.  We try to avoid this happening in the first place, but sometime he gets very focused on a smell very quickly.  For example, in the elevator, he sniffs the carpet very intensely.  I try to use the leash to restrict his options so that he canÆt reach the floor as easily, because he usually is concentrating too hard to respond to his name.  Usually he will pick his head up with a great effort and look at me, and his teeth will be chattering and his lips flapping aroundùit seems like his body is trying to continue sniffing while his brain is trying to respond to his name being called.  This teeth-chattering thing seems kind of weird to us, and we wanted to see if this was a normal behavior and to ask how we can help Payson keep from sniffing.    We would also like some help working with Payson on getting over his sporadic anxiety about stairs, and his skills in performing commands at a distance.    Otherwise, we have noticed a significant improvement in PaysonÆs house manners and his ability to control his excitement level (especially in public).  We are hoping Payson will be eligible for his puppy jacket at this walk and talk.  We are very proud of his progress!

Eventually, she will calm down with the new/late dog in the classroom setting, but it will take longer than it did the first time to get her back into the think and learn zone. GeneralComments: Until earlier this month, Laurel was making progress practicing skills for duration and increasing levels of distraction but came into heat on 11.09  She's been a little impulsive at times (pulling towards grass, shrubs to sniff) while on lead but frequency has decreased past couple days.    Initially she visually scans and aware of the socialization environment. She does relax and will walk well on lead.      We had been able to meet and pass dogs in town but due to her heat avoided such areas.      Looking forward to Laurel being out of heat and re-introducing her to our Florida neighborhood and socialization experiences during the holidays.

A great dog - possibly the best of our 8 so far!  Latka has exemplary house manners and is extremely responsive.  She loves to learn new things and is always very eager to please.  The only possible weakness we've noticed is that she can be quite sniffy, especially when working outside.  If she loses focus because of some scent it can take a while before she tunes back in again.

The problems that caused Latka's homechange to us at age 18 weeks have all been resolved and we find her to be a wonderful pup who is very sweet, responsive and eager to please.  Through repeated exposures she has learned how to interact very nicely with other dogs.  We've made great progress with the demand barking as well by ignoring it and seeing that good things happen only when she is quiet.

Both sitters did not have problem w counter surfing or garbage,  I use stern voice if he goes near garbage or begins to look up at  counter.  He tolerates vacuum  but not totally comfortable. I give him 1 or 2 minutes to air sniff when we get out of car which seems to help him  calm down.  "Check it out"  turns into sniffing usually.   Strong urge to sniff . Still working on body handling and not pushing nail clipping. Neutering has helped greatly.   Able to settle on his own usually.

ExerciseType: play on long lead, fetch , plays in house  nicely
GeneralComments: Walks when he has a bowel movement and goes four to five times in a line or semicircle. Noise-using socialization tape. Still unable to trim nails. Has improved on body handling  since last eval. I am now able to touch his body and give him hugs for a short period of time.  Dog distractions- at times will become aroused and may bark, lunge, or pull. MARKING, MARKING, MARKING! Very disappointed and surprised about incident on 1/25 when he jumped on counter and ate the bagel. Currently, I don't take my eyes off of him when he is off lead. Name response and recall have improved.

ExerciseType: playing ball, chasing toys, walking  , short hikes
GeneralComments: Linus and I are still developing our relationship. When he first came we were not able to do ANY body handling. Used Flash and treats.  Improving.Marked 3 times first 2 days. Came back from sit and did the same. Sitter said he marked 1 to 2 times each day.  Demand barking has improved. Horrible house manners but showing improvement. Less lunging but need to be on toes. Can llw but pulls a lot. Might we consider harness for a little while until I get him under better control. We passed CGC test but Linus was not 100% on task with me. I am still proud of him for coming along gradually and trusting me more and more.  Thank you!!

GeneralComments: Recall and name response 40-50%. Still easily aroused, but slowly improving. Eye contact and trust gradually improving. Whines loudly in crate when I take Linus outside first. Stairs- still needs some work, but has improved. T-touch harness I stopped using in December. Still need to be very aware of surroundings and distractions in case he decides to lunge or pull. Has a very fast gate. If I speed up my pace, he tends to go faster. Seems like he has the desire to get from point A to point B as quickly as possible. During this time, he appears to be more focused on getting to point B vs tuning into me. How fast is acceptable?

ExerciseType: walks, dog play, yard play, ball
GeneralComments: Belva is a smart, quite sensitive dog. She is very attuned to the emotions of the people around her and offers her support when she senses that something is not quite right. She is of lower energy and lower drive than most of the other dogs I have had. This makes her easier to work with and take places because she stays in think and learn mode more easily. Her socialization is going very well. One challenge I have with her is to keep her motivated and enthusiastic about her work. You can see this in class when she is much less cooperative at the end of class. Her severe food allergies make using high value treats difficult. A 40 minute walk is about all she is up for, even less on a day where the temperature is above 70 which she considers very hot. Lol  She is a very thorough, thoughtful sniffer û especially around dog smells. It seems like if she were left to her own devices that she would get lost in the smells and sniff endlessly. This is not much of a problem inside, but can be a problem outside. I have found that giving her clear direction about the sniffing is a good approach to take with her. Her mode of choice when we walk in the neighborhood is to walk to the extreme left of the sidewalk with her nose hovered about three inches above the grass. She has learned that IÆm not pleased with her stopping frequently to get a good long sniff anywhere, but this is her compromise so she can still enjoy the lovely smells but keep moving. I have taken to having her walk in the middle of the sidewalk where she will keep her head up better.  Nail clipping continues to be very challenging. She hates it so much. When I get the clippers out she tries to sweet talk her way out of it with wags and kisses. She will lay down for me and I can usually get one done (not always though). Occasionally, I can do another one, but more often than not, after cutting one nail, we have to backtrack almost to the beginning in the desensitizing small steps that lead to the actual cut. Many times she is just too nervous and will get to the point of not wanting to lay down any more. Again, without high value treats it is hard to find something very rewarding for her after getting a nail cut. Her best reward is to put away the clippers which usually gets a very enthusiastic response from her.  I have a note about her eliminating on command. Belva can go for a very long period without needing to get busy. With the dew on the grass and the sprinkler system going during the summer we learned that she does not like to walk on the wet grass. First thing in the morning taking her out I find that if the grass is wet she wonÆt leave the deck. If pick her up and take her out in the yard she stands there looking miserable and may even pick her feet up and shake them like dogs do when the pavement is too hot. The good news is that she can hold it just fine so I donÆt worry that this will lead to accidents in the house. She may, however, wait until the afternoon until she will go. Her record is not going until 3:00. Under normal circumstances, if I take her out any sooner than 6 hours, she wonÆt go. She may just lay down and look at me. So in answer to the question, does she eliminate on command, I have a mixed response in that she will go û if she feels like she has to - you have to be aware of how often she really needs to go out.  BelvaÆs food allergies are severe. I have emailed Dr. Sandler and got permission to feed her a food that is sold both at PetSmart and Petco. Luckily, I have found something that she tolerates pretty well. The huge problem with her is that almost all grain free foods use white potatoes in the formula. Belva is highly allergic to white potatoes (itching, chin acne, blood in her stool). I have been adding various foods that are ingredients in dog foods as a single ingredient added to her regular food to see exactly what she will react to. The choice of dog foods that she can tolerate is very limited and usually very expensive. I plan to continue to experiment with ingredients so I can give Dr. Sandler as much information as possible when she goes up for her IFT since this could be an issue for her as a guide.  All in all we are enjoying Belva immensely. She is a very nice, sweet personality to have in our home.

Belva has matured into a very nice puppy - not perfect, but generally easy, which is a welcome change of pace for me. She is somewhat in her terrible teens and consequently can be somewhat slow with her commands, but generally not bad. She has food allergies which I have been in contact with Dr. S to work through. Nails continue to be a struggle, but we are muddling through. I am able to usually cut one or two nails at a sitting before she has had enough. I settle for that. I want to make note of her energy level. Now granted, I usually end up with the high energy dogs so perhaps I am somewhat biased. She is usually good for about a 20 minute walk before she starts slowing down to a very slow pace. This is even if it is only 70 degrees outside. I feel like she will end up being some little old lady's dog or perhaps she is destined for the autism program.

Belva is a sweet smart girl. House training was a breeze and she learned her commands very quickly. Jane had her pegged though. ôNeeds repeated exposures because she can be activated in new situations. Take steps to return to Think & Learn Zone.ö I find her to be excitable and easily distracted. We tried to have an outing with Barney and Siobhan at a quiet park and as long as Barney was in sight, she was unwalkable no matter what I did. We have had another outing with them in a big empty parking lot where she was okay as long as Barney was a considerable distance away. That is an extremely low level exposure. She is far from being able to do a ônormalö age appropriate outing with another dog. She is the dog that is barking and lunging at class, after all.   Sniffing at dog smells is an issue. Unless I give her some clear direction that IÆm not happy with all the sniffing, she is off and gone no matter how many puppy parties we have. She is worried by dogs barking, even in houses.  We have been working at quiet strip malls to get her to walk by people without engaging them. She is very excited by people. She has just started being able to do this, but only after we have been out for over a half hour at a familiar place and she has really settled. We have also gone outside Target to watch people going in and out of the store during the week when there are not so many people. She is only able to do this for short periods before she needs a break where we walk away to where there are no people. She is able to settle and have an occasional person walk by. People greetings are difficult since she is so excited by people, especially children. She wants to chase after joggers.  Belva is going to take a lot of hard work to build her up with small increases in exposure levels. I am concerned that it is taking so long to get her to walk by people.

Alan continues to be a "velcro dog" following us from one floor to another. His house manners are excellent-- he sits nearby while we eat dinner sitting on the floor in front of the TV. He initially will walk over to see what we are doing, then he will go to his place and settle while we eat.  Alan can get overstimulated playing with other dogs. He tends to hump often and needs constant redirection. He has not had made playdates recently.  Personality-wise, Alan is very mellow and sweet. We think he would make an awesome Autism dog due to his large size and his desire to always be near his person.

He tends to hump often and needs constant redirection. He has not had made playdates recently.  Personality-wise, Alan is very mellow and sweet. We think he would make an awesome Autism dog due to his large size and his desire to always be near his person.

Alan remains a sensitive pup. We continue to work on his confidence.   While we were out of town for a month, resource guarding was observed by both Jodi and Cathy. This behavior was also observed by Barbara during a four day sit. It appears the guarding happens only with other dogs, not with people. The guarding has been observed with water, treats and around a kiddie pool. We are continuing to closely monitor this.  Alan recently starting barking in response to nothing (not demand barking). He will get up from sleeping and get up and run and give out a singular loud bark. He also did this once in the middle of the night.  Now that the weather is warmer, we've noticed that Alan gets hot very quickly. We have tried to plan his walks early in the morning.  Alan is a velcro dog and follows us from one floor of the house to another. He is confident laying on his dog bed in our bedroom while I work in the office as long as we are on the same floor of the house. If I go upstairs or downstairs, he almost always follows. It is difficult for him to remain in a stay from one floor to another. His stays otherwise are good if we are on the same floor of the house.  Prior to our vacation, Alan's WWP was excellent. Now he is more distracted on his walks--maybe due to him being a teenager now. He actually walks better when he is tired.

FoodType: Purina One Adult Chicken and Rice
ExerciseType: Walks, Runs in Yards or Tennis Courts and in House Chasing toys
GeneralComments: Since Wicker went through heat she is less excitable than in her puppyhood, but she still cannot settle easily at all. She definitely has very high energy, whether it is nervousness or just not wanting to miss anything fun. But she is still a lover and always picks the 'feet of the evening' to lie on for her after-dinner nap. She just needs lots of activity to be most happy. Then she will snore contentedly. Most bad habits are gradually improving-and I mean gradually. But there is some improvement all round as she grows up. And oh what a sweetie. we love laughing when she turns on 'the look'. Like a kid who thinks "pleeease' will get extra treats.

ExerciseType: running, fetching ball, playdates couple X/wk
GeneralComments: Wicker is very smart. She is learning calmer behaviors very quickly. Our no-nonsense rule is sitting at the front door calmly until free because we live near a busy street. She learned that very quickly and always sits and waits for leash and door. She's picking up close and heel quickly  too.  Our learning curve may be slower than hers. She suddenly goes crazy, biting and grabbing; we are finally figuring out when that will happen to avoid it and what to do. Now we can really get going on stopping the other over-the-top puppy behaviors. She is so 'mouthy', 'out' will be as hard as LLW with her. Her think and learn lasts only about 15 minutes post-nap, but knowing that is good. Progress is being made.

ExerciseType: runs; loves ball chasing; walks; playing with other dogs
GeneralComments: Wicker has overcome many 'fears'. She now is calm about noises and sights that used to make her jump and new noises or sights (like thunderstorms and street cleaners). We still work on being calm with kids and all greetings. It's so hard when some people want to pet and I don't want to be impolite; I avoid people if I think they will 'like' jumping, but go to people who have worked with us before. I feel like Pavlov and intermittent reward sometimes. She's doing some things, like sock stealing, that were overcome, but have come back. The barking is back and really bad. We have to get rid of it. I'm sure it's demand. I'm trying to come up with more activities for her; she could use a fenced yard for running a lot. In spite of the burning high energy, she is also a high affection dog who wants to be on the feet or close by. If we get on the floor, she's on the lap or falls asleep with head on leg- please don't move; I'm comfortable now.

Thoreau is a dog who likes activity. He is happiest when he's wearing his vest and walking around town, going into stores, etc.  He is a great llw'er.  He is very sweet.   He does not have a discernible prey drive.  I am working on the concern about kids by taking him to the library (children's room), a playground and a farmers' market. He is not comfortable with physical contact with young children.  He has several types of barking: needs to get busy; don't know what to do with myself and am a little anxious; and demand.  He does not alert bark! He does most of his barking at work. He does not bark at home after work or on the weekends.  It is hard for him to spend a full day at work, even with an hour of exercise mid day. He tends to be barkier in the afternoon, but this is slowly improving.

He does not alert bark! He does most of his barking at work. He does not bark at home after work or on the weekends.  It is hard for him to spend a full day at work, even with an hour of exercise mid day. He tends to be barkier in the afternoon, but this is slowly improving.

1) body handling: we\'re making good progress, her limitations have decreased some, but still need work. I am arranging with a co-worker for Rumba to be used for animal restraint trainings that will be happening soon for our new vet assistants. Our hospital believes in the less is more approach, and will keep it positive for Rumba.    2) separation anxiety: for the most part Rumba handles me leaving her side pretty well, but when she\'s anxious she\'s very anxious - i.e. barking, crying, trying to get loose from her crate or tether. At work I move about the premises over the course of the day, sometimes I\'m in my own office and other times at the reception desk. When I am on duty at the reception desk Rumba either remains in her crate in my office, or I move her to a pen elsewhere in the hospital, or I tether her beside the reception desk. She is doing very well at the reception desk, as long as I don\'t have to walk away from the area. When I walk away she is very disruptive and anxious. When she is penned vs in her own crate she will settle, but gets very upset if she sees me walk past.    3) distractions: Rumba is fabulous if there are zero distractions, but has a lot of trouble staying focused in the real world. Distractions include other dogs, cats, strange objects, new environments, fluttering leaves or garbage, people approaching or walking nearby, and of course dog scents. I\'ve had a tiny bit of success when I can anticipate that something is going to grab her attention, but that\'s IF I\'ve already got her focused. At class it takes a good 20-30 minutes of class time before she\'ll focus, and then her learning zone limit is about 10-15 minutes before she stops working. This issue has made it hit or miss whether a community exposure will be a success or reinforce her lack of focus.    4) fear after dark: Rumba has not out-grown her fear of stange objects. It is apparant at night and makes me wonder about her vision. She barks, growls and runs away from things in the darkness that are familiar to her, like the doghouse that has always been there, or a toy she dropped in the yard earlier in the day.

GeneralComments: Pastel has a very sweet personality.  I'm still concerned about her interaction with other dogs and her reluctance to be around areas with multiple activities occurring at the same time.  She trusts me so I am very conscious of her body language at all times.  Anything that is a one on one, she learns very quickly.  She will usually carry through with the same activity in a small crowd.  Put her in a larger crowd, and she shuts down.  I have about 12 months left to get her to have the confidence she needs.  Slow but sure is our motto.

GeneralComments: We've done all that we can for her.  She's the best mannered at home and riding in the car that we've had since we started raising pups.  She's much more confident at walking and sitting outside at night.  However, she still continues to be very stressed outside walking in unknown areas, sitting while we talk to friends outside in a group standing around her, and being near motors.  We now think that the motor issue is because her hearing is very good and the noise hurts her ears.  She has a tremendous play drive.  Wish we could have done more.  She's a good girl.  Doesn't look like she sees GEB as her place to bel.

ExerciseType: free play with my dog, fetch, walks
GeneralComments: Louie is a boisterous, loving puppy that will activate quickly when interacting with others (especially if eye contact, talking to him, handling, etc).  However, when we go places (including office settings with close contact with others walking right by him) he can ignore and stay settled.  He will lie still while I do body handling, clip nails, even let me put ice pack over his eye and muzzle when recently stung by insect.  He needs his daily exercise but spends hours sleeping, chewing bone, etc.  He does well sitting and watching activity - can get fairly close.  When not overly activated he is a wonderful walker, staying right at left side with no pulling.  While challenging at times, he has been an absolute joy to raise!

Nice  puppy.  Very good "settling" at work. Great house manners, good alone in yard, confident and willing worker, no health issues, no fear issues.  Biggest concern is mild mouthing and play biting when greeting new people.  Seems to do a fair amount of scratching around armpits and inner flanks but skin appears healthy, no rashes, reddness, irritation or dryness.  Our climate is very dry and he is bathed regularly with a high quality shampoo.  Moderate to lower energy, enjoys daily exercise but is okay if you skip a day or too.  Adapts readily to new situations, has traveled and flown with me.  Plays well with other dogs, reads and responds well to other dogs' body language and play style.

ExerciseType: Tennis court running, hide and seek, fetch games, loose leash walking; a bit too energetic
GeneralComments: Joanie is a dog with great potential who has unfortunately been bounced around to several different homes -- we are the 4th home in 7 months and it is unclear how consistent her training has been.  She walks phenomenally well on leash when jacketed, but is not mature enough yet to sit still for long.  Does not know settle, place or close commands.    Joanie seems quite smart, but seems to have great difficulty understanding the heel command.  She does well when guided into position by hand motion and with kibble, but is then unable to perform the command at all without a treat.  We have had Joanie for 8 days now.  When we first received her, she knew only how to sit from a stand position (sit down), but not how to sit from a down position (sit up).  She did not know the stand command at all, either verbally or by hand -- by 7 months that's a basic command she should have mastered easily.  So we are essentially starting almost from scratch with Joanie, and focusing right now on just the basics -- sit, down, stand, stay -- and working patiently with her on consistency.    She is stubborn and undisciplined, but that is probably due to the number of home changes she has had and trying to adjust to yet another home and another set of raisers.  However, we are committed to working with her consistently and patiently on the many areas where she needs improvement.  She is affectionate, lovable  and in some areas can be quite eager to please.  The two biggest areas of concern are the significant concern of not just jumping on people but of jumping toward the face, with an attempt to play bite people's faces.    Closely related to that was my observation two days ago of her being very friendly to a group of 4 small children who came to the porch, but then  growling and starting to bark when one of the children moved away fast and started running.  Again, these comments should be taken with some measure of consideration.  We have had Joanie for only 9 days, and these are initial impressions only.    It may be worth noting that Joanie's original raiser lived in a retirement community, and her most recent sitter, with whom she stayed for 4 weeks, also lives in a retirement community, so it's not clear how much exposure Joanie has had to children.

Walking and watching; puppy play at Potomac Kennel and PSTA.
GeneralComments: Fauna is working diligently.  Thank you to Liz, Jean, Jane, and Jodi.  Focusing on minutes watched rather than miles walked, i.e. locating reduced impact areas and watching traffic and/or people while in sit, down, settle, etc.  Also, significant amounts of (supervised) undirected free time when home rather than specific direction, i.e. "place" here or "kennel" there.  Much improvement.  Fauna likes to jump on walls (2'-4') when permitted/directed and play on playground equipment.

Focusing on minutes watched rather than miles walked, i.e. locating reduced impact areas and watching traffic and/or people while in sit, down, settle, etc.  Also, significant amounts of (supervised) undirected free time when home rather than specific direction, i.e. "place" here or "kennel" there.  Much improvement.  Fauna likes to jump on walls (2'-4') when permitted/directed and play on playground equipment.

ExerciseType: Several walks a day of about half an hour. Playtime is essential too as she does better if allowed to have some outside playtime with a ball or some tug toys.
GeneralComments: It's hard to say how Fauna would be in class. She is not overly dog distracted so I don't think she'd have a hard time but really unless I proof it I am not entirely sure. She has made such nice progress in the last few months. I'm pleased at how well and how quickly she is able to settle in many different situations. When out and about she is a dream to work with. She still needs some time to process in new environments but is adjusting more and more quickly as she gets older. I'm especially pleased with how her attention seeking behavior is abating. I am seeing progress there every week. Less nudging my arms when I am working, less trying to climb onto my lap if I'm sitting. These things were pervasive when she came to me. She can simply settle no matter where we are now. Every week brings a new pleasant surprise in what she can handle. She has an affectionate nature and willing personality. I hope with time she can gain even more confidence.

Ajax is an exuberant pup with a big heart! He tries his best, but his tendency toward arousal presents a challenge for him to stay in TLZ. He has made great strides with repeated exposure, and works well in areas he is familiar with... He does show some signs of stress (lip licks, yawns, shake offs)- but also seems to be able to work thru some of the challenges. He also is challenged with body handling and people greetings--needs continued work on those areas. Enjoyable pup who always tries to please handler.

GeneralComments: Tori is doing very well.  Her back sensitivity is improving.  She still bites at her vest, however she is able to work in it.  Before she couldn't listen to command in her vest, but she is usually quite responsive.    Between having Pano and being in Heat, Tori has had a lot of down time over the last 3-4 months.  She is currently limping again, but not so bad that I need to medicate her.  She just do very short walks and working trips that don't require a lot of walking (i.e. to the restaurant/coffee shop, movie theater etc) and have a lot of people watching opportunities.  We do best to tire her mentally, if not physically, when she has pano.

I have had Tamara for almost 3 months.  She is a very sweet loving dog.  Tamara is very visual and is easily distracted.  She can be somewhat on her own agenda in areas with higher distractions and requires a fair amount of effort on the handler's part to keep her engaged.  Her skills overall are pretty good.  Basic commands can be slow when she is distracted but we are working on her being more consistent.  She seems to do well with wearing things and being handled.  She is willing to work with fellow raisers in class but keeps a close eye on me.  I feel like we are at a plateau so I could use some suggestions to get us over the hump.  She plays well with other dogs and is doing much better with our cats (persuing has greatly decreased).

Basic commands can be slow when she is distracted but we are working on her being more consistent.  She seems to do well with wearing things and being handled.  She is willing to work with fellow raisers in class but keeps a close eye on me.  I feel like we are at a plateau so I could use some suggestions to get us over the hump.  She plays well with other dogs and is doing much better with our cats (persuing has greatly decreased).

GeneralComments: Missed a couple of classes due to getting lost or not getting the email about a change in location.  I will work on this.  Tetris has begun to mature and act less puppy like. I do not leave him unattended except to go get something from another room.  Needs work on dog distractions, duration of staying in positions, and continued work on appropriate chewing.

GeneralComments: Pilgrim is an active puppy, a little stubborn and headstrong.  He is making real progress with his skills but will have lapses.  His behavior out and around is quite good.  Can't settle for too long at this point but he exhibits signs that this will improve with experience.  House manners at good level now.  He was slow to housetrain and had problem with chewing---first shoes, then chair legs---but we have moved beyond this stage.  He's a good puppy who likes attention...a big time kisser who would love to be a lap dog!

GeneralComments: Merrick is a very intelligent, strong, healthy dog with a great personality.  Very confident, and affectionate...great to have around.  We have been socializing a lot recently and he plays very well with other dogs and people--very social and "happy.":  It's becoming less difficult for him to calm down in class.  We try to visit the CDC weekly to practice settling, and he does very well on practice sessions.  Very excited in class environment.  He can be obstinate when he doesn't want to do something and expresses it by laying down flat on ground.  Can be jollied/cajoled out of it. Very responsive to training when issues have arisen. Prefers to be with people.
