ExerciseType: Walks, town outings, BDA running w/ friends & house dogs
GeneralComments: Kaiser is a good boy! He will benefit from lots more exposures to other dogs during town walks now that the weather is great and other dogs are around. Last week he was perfect when barked at by a mini schnauzer off lead running at him. After the dog was contained in the owners arms, Kaiser sat opposite him 20' away at a park bench and calmly settled. BUT today he barked in Rheinbeck at several large dogs on the street, not more than 20' away. My biggest revelation was a stuffed lion in a store window staring at Kaiser. LOTS of barking! We moved back away, got a settle, and then moved a little closer. Each time he move too close too fast, he began a low growl. So we wouldd stay back at a comfortable distance till he settled, and then move closer. I think it was more than 5-6 minutes that it took to get him to the window for a calm "check it out". This is Kaiser's biggest challenge . We are also working on a sudden recent concern he has about getting dressed. Lastly, I continue to work on his excitement when he is going out at noon to play. Sometimes we just work the hall and go back.  But we really are enjoying him!

GeneralComments: Kaiser is a doll! He's easy to control, and doesn't require alot to keep him connected. Our only problem is occasional barking at unfamiliar dogs, which won't happen the next time he sees that dog, and recently he has been giving a low growl, (more like 'talking') when he sees something novel. The novel thing may be a person standing still, a kid with a balloon, a janitor with a big rolling cart, etc. He makes a quick recovery. When he barks at unfamiliar dogs it usually stops if he can get him a littler further away and let him check the dog out, then get closer.

Jessica is a good girl most of the time and in certain places where she knows it counts. She will bark at my house dogs when frustrated and barks in her kennel when she decides its time to get up. She has come a long way with this, but is still a work in progress. Great house manners, polite greetings with people but a bit demanding in nature with certain things. Puppy politeness poker works well with her. She is a fun pup to work with as you must be one step ahead of her.

Jessica is a well behaved, calm lab. She can be the perfect little dog but still has her "little barky side" that she came with at 12 wks old. She has made great progress and understands consequences when she gets out of her "learning zone."  Jessica is good at work, on public transportation and every place you take her. Her biggest issue is letting you know when she doesn't like something or when she wants a toy that another dog has. She does respond well to correction and has come to learn she doesn't get everything she wants. Overall she has some really nice calm attributes and we have enjoyed raising her!

GeneralComments: Davis is doing very well and is naturally, a sweet pup.  His biggest issues right now are getting anxious when meeting "new" dogs and people who come over and use high, excited voices.  Also, we see a difference when our other dog (6 1/2 yr-old chocolate) is with him.  Davis gets more excited then rather when he is alone.  Cutting his nails is the other issue.  Otherwise, Davis is responding to our commands, learning new ones easily, and getting more used to just verbal commands.  We continue to try and take him to a lot of places and on out trips.  He is a great rider in the car and stays very well in new places.  Should he get his jacket, we will expose him to more places, people, and distractions.

This sweet pup continues to develop his confidence. Though he can be a bit wary and hesitant, for example with stairs or grates, he will usually try new things if he is given time to approach on his own and choose whether or not to try.  Once he tries and we celebrate, he is quite pleased with himself and eager to try again.  He has made a lot of progress in the last couple of months and I'd expect that he will be a thoughtful and confident guy by the time he is ready to return to GEB in the Fall. Other than that he is a great pup at home and on outings, good on leash (with support),  listens well, settles well, etc.

ExerciseType: Play with Nick and Betsy and walks
GeneralComments: Bethanne came to us with issues. However, I have had more fun with her than with Pasco or Patina. So, I am confident, that with time, we will bring her skills up to a higher level. However, she is a very high energy puppy that does not handle separation very well (at home); and when aroused, (this happens very quickly) is difficult to calm down.  People greetings and puppy class are going to be a challenge for the next several months.  I think that she is very smart and does try hard. I believe that she is immature, for her age. However, she has begun to make lots of progress. I have taken her to work, Church, Starbucks, Giant Food, Safeway and Harris Teeter. Her behavior is fair to good at Starbucks and the food stores. Her behavior at work and Church is good. She is very easy to ôdropö and is very difficult with LLW, especially outdoors. So, staying connected is something the two of us are working on. :)  John and Bethanne

ExerciseType: Walking and play with Nick and Betsy
GeneralComments: Bethanne is a very cute, lovable, high energy puppy that everyone seems to like on sight. She is also very smart. In many respects, I believe that Bethanne is the smartest puppy that we have raised.  Even with all of her initial issues, she has continued to demonstrate that she can learn.  Please note that the introduction of a prong collar has made a significant difference in dealing with her issues, such as, pulling. Bethanne is a well behaved puppy with the prong collar, not so well behaved without it. I work her about 50% of the time with the prong collar, 25% using just her flat collar and 25% using the prong collar, without attaching the leash to it. The leash is attached to her flat collar.  I think that she has made progress with us. However, there is still much to learn.  John and Bethanne :)

GeneralComments: Wind is a sweet pup and is really well behaved/confident in both familiar and unfamiliar places.  Her biggest challenges at this point in time is staying calm when seeing other dogs/animals and when strangers approach her.  She is easily excited in these situations.  Also, her "come" skills have regressed and she blows me off completely.  The BIGGEST challenge for Wind is the sniffing -- her sniffing often seems uncontrollable and she cannot focus on anything else.  Also, her busy nose also sometimes interferes with her ability to walk places -- if someone is smoking near a door, she will not walk into the door, if the elevator in our building was just cleaned and it has a strong odor, she won't get in the elevator (without some convincing).    Health wise -- she has been vomiting recently in the middle of the night (checked with vet and will continue to monitor).  Also, her ears seem to be a bother for her.  She had a nasty double ear infection a couple months ago and since then, she tends to shake her head a lot and prefers not to have her ears petted (although there doesn't seem to be evidence of another infection at this time).

Wendy did well with Dominion's Gingham at an outreach program involving 1st grade class. She could use more time around children.  We've enjoyed raising Wendy because she is bright, energetic gal. Wendy recently came into heat and during the last month we experienced increase awareness to sounds especially at night and overall excitement. Required us to use patience and wait for her to respond at times.  That said, at times when she becomes excited, she self-modulates which is very cool.      She can be olfactory including mild air scenting especially walking in small towns where dogs have eliminated on every object.  Increase use of you, faster pace, high value rewards somewhat help.  Her level of comfort on stairs has improved. Wendy prefers to move out and continue to work on "settle" in different situations that can be of challenge to her (Mall).  Began taking Wendy inside a grocery store last month, going fine.

GeneralComments: Rosemary has a tentative side to her.   One moment she appears very confident and grounded.   Other times she acts as though she is in another world.    She needs time to process and she has taught me a new level of patience and giving her breathing room!  Excellent with obedience and walking on loose leash.  Recalls off leash are excellent.   Playing with other dogs , she can sometimes get very aroused  and needs to be given time out.  fabulous with young children.   interactive and appropriate.   Lots of experience with children and stays calm and settled.   Settling is a specialty of hers.  She is a lot of fun to work with out in public !   She has been a challenge because of her quirky nature but the past month with Pat and Kerry's  guidance has been a great help.  Not doing the work for Rosemary.   Allowing her to take responsibility!   I learn from each of these pups for sure!   She has not liked vacuum cleaner but now follows me around and settles with toy in the room on her own when I vacuum.   She adapts in her time and not with my interference  .  excellent house manners in any home that we have stayed.

GeneralComments: After the last class in Portland we discussed the fact that Rave had changed and become timid or worried.  She seems to be getting better now that she is reaching the end of her heat cycle.  Curious thing - she will not walk thru rain puddles when we are out for a walk yet will run thru the surf like a crazy being.  Underfootings seem to be a problem for her.  Also, doors that seem to her to have the possibility of closing when she is going thru them - she will balk and wait until she is very certain that it will not close on her.  She is finally jumping into the back of a van - tho having a kennel there is somewhat questionable for her.

GeneralComments: Sitters and other people have commented that Riley is very well behaved and is very good in the house. I have been taking her to many different places and into restaurants. She has done well walking on a loose leash and sitting when people ask to pet her when we are at stores. She is very good with kids and even stayed in her settle while some little kids tugged her ears and touched her face. She even sat quietly while a little boy, who had Downsyndrome, petted her.  In restaurants she is sometimes distracted by new smells or crumbs on the floor but she does settle nicely. Also, she will settle nicely at church.  She is getting better on her stair tracking and door manners. She knows all of her commands but we are still working on being able do them in high distracting areas.

GeneralComments: We have had Opa about one month.  He is a very loving dog.  He enjoys walks and playing ball in the yard.  He has a good energy level and sleeps all night.        We are working very hard with him on LLW.  He tends to walk in front and wants to pull.  He has made some improvement.  He has a horrible time if he sees another dog on a walk. We generally go the other direction to avoid the dog if possible.  If he sees another dog within about 10 ft. he jumps, leaps, barks and carries on until the dog is out of sight.  We will continue to work on this in hopes that the high value treats in combination with him getting older will calm him down.       Opa can not be left unattended with items on the counter or table.  He has taken glasses, a wallet, gloves etc..and chewed them. (Needless to say he has trained us to put everything away.) Opa has a bin of chew toys, bones, toys etc.  We continue to remind him where his toys are and praise him when he takes his own toys.     We have already seen some improvement in these behaviors in the last few days.

GeneralComments: Dolly began having a limping issue with her rear hind leg on August 16.  Per GEB vet, she was seen by our sponsor vet who prescribed an anti-inflammatory and told to rest.  After completing the medicine, limping began again.  She was subsequently seen by the GEB vet mid October and was diagnosed with suspected soft tissue damage and mandated crate rest for 2-3 weeks and given Rimadyl.  After the Rimadyl was finished, she began to limp again. I drove her back to the GEB vet November 5 and they had her seen by their Orthopedist.  She was diagnosed e with having lumbar/groin injury and  received a laser treatment  and Rimadyl and again placed on strict rest.  After the medication was finished, she began to favor the leg again, although not limping outright. I was given permission to have her seen by a local orthopedist for evaluation and laser treatment.  Orthopedic Vet confirmed previous diagnosis and was prescribed Rimadyl and Robaxin.  This vet recommended 4-6 weeks of weekly physical therapy/laser treatment and home exercises.  First treatment was Monday 1/2.  As a result of all of this, Dolly's training and socialization has been severely compromised.  Stairs continue to be an issue.  She still goes up and down closed stairs like a young pup, with two hind legs scampering together.  She is fearful of open back stairs.

GeneralComments: Christy is beginning to display good maturity at home and on outings.  She recognizes that she's going out somewhere special when we pull out the GEB Jacket.  She responds very well to all commands in all settings, and is increasing with her confidence at the Mall, the Train Station, the grocery store, and on our walks.  We've introduced her to the children play ground and she is showing confidence in negotiating various obstacles.  She plays wonderfully with other dogs, never growls / bites / mounts other dogs.  Always with a toy playing keep away or chase games.  We've also used a local fenced in tennis court to teach commands off the leash, which she is responding to very well.  Christy has the best temperment of any large size dog, I've owned.

GeneralComments: Adrienne is a very sweet girl. She is very smart. I am finding more ways to keep her interested in working because sometimes she doesn't always see the point. She does well is class but can sometimes be vocal towards the other dogs. She is very sweet and playful and loves to be with me. She gets along very well with our other dogs and does great in the neighborhood. When we intially god her she was very afraid of cars driving by but she has gotten a lot better with this. She has been car sick quite a bit so she is hesitant to get in the car. If you feed her a meal in the car she hops right in but for some treats--even high value ones--she won't always get in. This is something I continue to work on.

GeneralComments: Adrienne continues to improve in some areas but struggles in others.  She has shown concern in town house like setting where many things appeared to be moving towards her (it was a lot for her to take in).  She had a severe reaction to a woman that she saw at a Asst. living place when I was out of town.  She shows great improvement when things move in small slices.  She has also shown some concern with people that she feels are odd - man on CC skis was able to approach, 2 approach better (he had taken his ski off) 3rd time she sat at his side as if to look out for him.  Will get overwhelmed with group play but fine if she is introduced while in the T&L - her and the other dog.  Still is not happy about riding in small cars with a tight space but does fine on a plane, in or out of a crate in my van.  She can walk through tunnels or bike racks.  I have really worked on her neadiness and she has made great strides and is more relaxed.  She is a sweet girl and gets along beautifully with my released lab Frannie.  Loves to swim and play catch or fetch, be petted and be with her people.

ExerciseType: walk, fetch at tennis courts, swimming, socializing
GeneralComments: Adrienne is a sweet and well behaved GSD.  She loves to be with her person but is willing to work with other people.  She does best when I am not too close.  She has made huge strides with her comfort in riding in cars/vans.  She rides beautifully on planes, shuttle and bus.  She has also made nice strides with her "neediness" and no longer comes to me for reassurance (nudge under my arm to be petted).  Our biggest issue is concern with dogs that come into her space quickly and rudely.  After she has "met" a dog even if they are excited initially, she is fine. i have not put her in pup play since because I couldn't be sure that I could call her out if she went out of the T&L zone.  She has done well with all family dogs on swaps too.  She loves to swim, play fetch, puzzle toys and nylabones or stuffed bones.  She is calm when out in public and in crowds.  She is great company.

GeneralComments: Tahoe was with Siobhan de Courcy and she wrote this up about him.  April 22, 2011 Some thoughts/suggestions/observations from my time with Tahoe  This adorable boy has been a delightful visitor.  He is friendly, responsive, cooperative,  easily engagedùa great, medium-energy pup! I havenÆt identified any significant ôissuesö or problems. He got along well with the other dogs and with the cats, has good (age appropriate) house manners, kenneled easily, was quiet in his crate.  You are doing a really nice job with him!  IÆll share my experience and offer some suggestions.  I will send this to Michele, as well, and urge you to consult with her on all of this.  The two things I would focus on if I were you are:  --TahoeÆs interaction with Nate.  I was so surprised to see Tahoe greet Nate!  While being excitedly greeted by a pup who grabs your clothes and shoelaces and jumps on you may seem cute now, as Tahoe grows this will quickly lose itÆs appeal.  Better to help him make better choices now.  As I suggested to Nate, calmly and kindly redirecting him should help him to improve his greeting.  Call his name and give him a verbal and hand signal for a command he knows, immediately praise him for responding and give him a treat. You can also find a toy to play with to help him occupy his mouth.  Giving him attention while heÆs biting and nipping and jumping is reinforcing that behavior.  The only time I saw Tahoe exhibit these behaviors was with the other dogs:  he greets them by grabbing the side of their face or neck with his mouth, or jumping on them.  The dogs were pretty quick to let him know that a little of this went a long way.  --Tahoe seems a bit timid and he is very sensitive to and uncomfortable with some sounds.  While he may be comfortable around your home and yard, he needs careful exposure and support in order to help he be comfortable in many different environments. His daily outing should be planned to include careful and well-supported exposure to new and different places and sounds.  A pup that is comfortable in his environment walks happily alongside of you, he doesnÆt lag a few steps back as Tahoe can do.  It is important for him to be exposed to many things at his young age. IÆd be happy to discuss this more with you and/or to go places with you.    IÆll start by responding to what you shared on the puppy sit form* and in conversation, and then IÆll tell you about my experiences with him on outings.   ?

The two things I would focus on if I were you are:  --TahoeÆs interaction with Nate.  I was so surprised to see Tahoe greet Nate!  While being excitedly greeted by a pup who grabs your clothes and shoelaces and jumps on you may seem cute now, as Tahoe grows this will quickly lose itÆs appeal.  Better to help him make better choices now.  As I suggested to Nate, calmly and kindly redirecting him should help him to improve his greeting.  Call his name and give him a verbal and hand signal for a command he knows, immediately praise him for responding and give him a treat. You can also find a toy to play with to help him occupy his mouth.  Giving him attention while heÆs biting and nipping and jumping is reinforcing that behavior.  The only time I saw Tahoe exhibit these behaviors was with the other dogs:  he greets them by grabbing the side of their face or neck with his mouth, or jumping on them.  The dogs were pretty quick to let him know that a little of this went a long way.  --Tahoe seems a bit timid and he is very sensitive to and uncomfortable with some sounds.  While he may be comfortable around your home and yard, he needs careful exposure and support in order to help he be comfortable in many different environments. His daily outing should be planned to include careful and well-supported exposure to new and different places and sounds.  A pup that is comfortable in his environment walks happily alongside of you, he doesnÆt lag a few steps back as Tahoe can do.  It is important for him to be exposed to many things at his young age. IÆd be happy to discuss this more with you and/or to go places with you.    IÆll start by responding to what you shared on the puppy sit form* and in conversation, and then IÆll tell you about my experiences with him on outings.   ?

GeneralComments: Tad in my opinion is a very confident happy pup. The first day we brought him home he was initially aggressive towards our family dog at times, and we have seen that problem go away.      When we took hold of Tad to stop him from biting the family dogs face he became upset and displayed an  "edge", by growling, and getting mouthy when not allowed to have his way.  We have been working on that and he does not show the aggressive behavior he did initially.  The two dogs have now bonded and we just need to curb his normal puppy enthusiam at times. He now is compliant with verbal commands and stops going after the other dog.          From day one Tad did seem familiar with a kitchen setting, and it appeared he may have been given some rewards previously in a kitchen setting.  As example when the fridge was opened he came running to it with great interest.  Same with stove when we were using it.   We have worked on kitchen manners and it appears that his initial behavior is resolved.    He demand barked also from the first day we had him.  We did notice that he had what looked like teeth marks on his nose, like he had been in a scrap with another pup or cat.          These behaviors just made us feel that he was allowed to get away with inappropriate behavior before and we addressed it.        Tad has had numerous previous playtimes with GEB Tana 16 months and GEB Fred 9 months, and two other GEB dogs and they have interacted very well.     Tad last month was handled by students in PPPC and accepted commands and acted appropriately with numerous students.   Tad was at the Cornell Vet School Open house, and interacted very well with all ages, handled  by very young children,  did not display any stress or frustration at any time.         Tad at home gets to play in fenced in yard area a few times a week with a ten year old male lab, and a female Lab pup a month younger than him  He interacts very well with both these dogs, and has not displayed any aggression, and is well mannered with both the older dog and pup.   We have been working on his barking and  is doing much better as he develops.  I have been setting up distraction situations with people and other dogs, working on his barking and command compliance.   He can be headstrong, but once he understands what is expected he then increases compliance and barking etc, reduces.     Tad is a very intelligent pup, is good natured and calm in the house.  He is an normal level active pup that requires excercise and interaction & play time with other active dogs.   He does have an edge to him when he does not get his way and gets frustrated at times.  This behavior is associated with his interaction with our family dog, or when he is tired.   As when he is given a time out, he does settle down and does not display that type of behavior.    I can only relate it to a time out with a child, as Tad seems to learn not to repeat that behavior, when he and our family dog are brought back together again.   I trust Tad (95%) with our family dog now, just need to monitor his normal puppy play / behavior.    He is very good riding in the car, and accompanies me to my office, right now a few times a week.   The more exposure I give him the better he becomes.

Is a very gentle pup. No aggression at all. Loves to play and interact with other dogs.  In my opinion is a bit slow in maturing mentally. In the past few weeks have seen him increase his attention span, and maintining his focus on handler.  With the exception of three bouts of pano, he has been a very healthy pup.  Loves to be with people. He is extremely good in his crate in the house. Gets along very well with family dogs, "respecting their food bowls, and not poaching"  Our small family dog can climb all over him, even when sleeping and it does not phase him.  He has been a vocal pup since we first got him, but that is improving, but not totally resolved. Does bark at unfamiliar dogs.  He does not sniff the ground excessively. Very solid on all types of flooring, surfaces, stairs, and in elevators. Does very well when boarding and exiting public transit busses, and rides very well in cars. Does well around shopping carts, and disabled persons in wheelchairs. Does well in shopping malls, with his focus increasing as he ages.

GeneralComments: Sherry is a very bright puppy.  She does have a very strong will, however. She has learned many new commands but will often wait for lures/treats to perform.  She is easlily distractable and on walks, you must watch her carefully as she will try to pick up bones, twigs, wrappers and other "delectables".She showed this sign on her very first evening walk. Also, in the house she finds papers/mail/tissues irresistible even when toys/bones are present. Her biting problem persists but some of the GEB suggestions are showing hopeful signs of succeeding.  She is very attached to me her raiser. She "gets busy" outside but will occasionally have a "peeing" accident inside (see # 32 & 44).  She will urinate on grass or cement but usually do #2 only on grass.  She is 3 1/2 months old and it is hopeful that the problems will get better as she matures.

GeneralComments: This is one great pup. He certainly responds to a work ethic. Right now he's easy to over-excite and if that happens it's not so great. If we take it slowly he handles everything beautifully. in Richmond in the 4 apt in our building there were 4 other dogs- barky, and noisy. While Petey was great and not noisy, I know it had its stress for him. We had lots of city exposures and training ops. One concern is sometimes an inability to settle without direction. He can and does do it often. Out in the park, me reading a book... 20-30minutes, he might not ever just lie down and relax unless directed and might even whine then (now that I think about it). If directed, mostly fine. I think, Pat, you saw that in class in January.

I've had Dora about a week She had a solid sit and a pretty shaky down when she came to me. We have been working hard to get her up to speed on her weekly progressions. She is a very fast learner and extremely food motivated. She is already working on Week 4 exercises at this point. She can do everything in familiar places and we are working on unfamiliar places. She is smart enough that you have to be careful what she is learning. 'Out' became a fun game of running up, grabbing something off the ground, dropping, and then getting a treat. She is a dog that you have to stay a step ahead of. Her house training is going well. The only accidents we have are when I am not paying enough attention. She is great in her kennel. When we are not actively engaged she likes to go and hang out in her kennel. I am working on rewarding her for hanging out with me. We are enjoying her very much!

Dora is my 8th dog and she is not a beginner pup. She has energy and distractions that we are working through. She does better the longer we are out. She is able to work nicely at the strip mall level. She is good with traffic and small animals. Her LLW is good with low distractions, particularly when we have been out a while. We are working on her settling in a down position and making progress. I had her out at a fairly busy place and she was mostly settled nicely for ten minutes. She is very distracted by dog smells and can lose herself in them. She is able to walk by a dog who is across the street with food. We can also sit and watch successfully. Although we have little barking at home it is a problem when we are out. If I stop and talk to someone she will bark. She is not trying to get my attention, because she is facing the person. She will continue to bark even if the person tries to pet her. If someone approaches her, she will sit for food and greet nicely, If they stay to talk, then she barks. Even if I move away from the person to give her some room, she continues to bark at them. She can settle and let people walk by without barking, she can also just walk by people and do fine. Another problem I have with her is that she is terrible at class. She barks and lunges at people/dogs and it isn't until about the end of class before she is in a thinking/learning frame of mind. Class is no fun!

GeneralComments: As a new raiser who has had Dixie for just a few weeks, I believe she is adjusting well.  She is sleeping all night, eating well and is a very sweet puppy who loves being with you.  At this stage, she loves to explore and can easily be distracted by smells, nuts and things to eat  on our walks,etc.  She will drop whatever she has in her mouth when told "out" and patience is required when waiting for her to return.  Greeting people needs to be worked on more.  For things that shouldn't be done like play biting and jumping on the couch, the word "Uh oh" and "I'm not very happy" has become connected to something that she shouldn't be doing.  Most of the time she will stop when this is said.  She is so smart! It doesn't take much for her to understand what you want. I will miss her, but hope to babysit on a regular basis and to stay in touch with other raisers.

GeneralComments: Tyler is making steady improvement as he matures. He also shows an inner drive to have something in his mouth to carry- for instance- upon entering a room, or exiting his crate- his first action is to go find a toy to carry around--He is an enjoyable pup to live with- Loves playing fetch, and playing with other pups.. Pleasant company..

ExerciseType: Walking downtown, lots of running after and fetching ball and toys, loves to play tug, and recently began responding very well to "out." He plays well with other dogs, no aggression or biting. In the office, he is great most of the time settling and enter
GeneralComments: Troy is very willing, can focus wonderfully, walks in the city on a loose lead, places on grates, "stays" in high foot traffic areas inside and out, recalls quickly when focused, is not barking in the office much at all any more, is staying focused on me much more now in the office with other people all around, checks in with me a lot during walks, can correct his own position on walks, spits out pieces of bark and sidewalk stuff he picks up-without me telling him to now, can play outside - with the chickens and horses loose in the pasture and not pay them any mind , has never tried to leave the yard (he would tho, if another dog came around), and has had really good walks in Colonial Williamsburg with other dogs on leashes, but just as often has "bad" days when other dogs are just too much for him to handle well. He's brilliant when he's good and yet has to be removed from class or other dogs when he can't control his excitement. "Approach and retreat" seems to work to help him handle these times, and I'm highly hopeful it will help him get over his emotional response when dogs are around. Our new outside classroom should give us the room for approach and retreat. It's not about the task when he is over-excited...it's about having the patience and several strategies to help him through the behavior with his dignity and confidence intact. Troy is amazing...he's a very quick, smart, willing, affectionate, friendly pup with some challenging inconsistancies and over-excited reactions to other dogs, but we will work hard to get past those so he can put his talents to the best use.

GeneralComments: He has greatly improved since we received him in November. His play-biting is much better, and he's learning to sit with greetings. He gets very excited whenever someone new pays attention to him, but if strangers walk by and don't talk to him, he'll settle fairly quickly. We've enjoyed learning all about him and we love playing with him. He's kind of a goofball when he's in play mode.

He has greatly improved since we received him in November. His play-biting is much better, and he's learning to sit with greetings. He gets very excited whenever someone new pays attention to him, but if strangers walk by and don't talk to him, he'll settle fairly quickly. We've enjoyed learning all about him and we love playing with him. He's kind of a goofball when he's in play mode.

Overall, Roger has been very pleasant to work with in the past few months. His walking is still progressing but we've been really happy with how much he's improved. We are struggling the most with his greetings of people and his excitement around other dogs. This is a problem both indoors at our house, and outdoors when new people approach him. Their baby talk really provokes him to start jumping and going nuts. When people ignore him, he's generally calm -- so when we settle in new places, he has typically done very well. When he's very distracted, it is hard to get his attention.

We are struggling the most with his greetings of people and his excitement around other dogs. This is a problem both indoors at our house, and outdoors when new people approach him. Their baby talk really provokes him to start jumping and going nuts. When people ignore him, he's generally calm -- so when we settle in new places, he has typically done very well. When he's very distracted, it is hard to get his attention.

Roger was neutered in January and has recovered fully since then. He remains high energy in new places, around new people, and around dogs, but we have seen some improvement in his ability to check back into us after initial distraction. He remains eager to please and very treat motivated. His behavior in class remains relatively poor: he is distracted and excited by the other dogs and he needs about 20 minutes to settle. In addition, he is completely crazy for Janet Newcity, and when he hears her or sees her he yelps for her with joy. We're not sure what to do about it but it makes class very challenging.

GeneralComments: Ray is a delightful dog, eager to please, yet able to settle down quickly and take things in stride. He can be low key, and sometimes has to be nudged on a bit on longer walks. He is sweet, willing, and responsive, though a little distracted by smells, people, and other dogs. He tends to drink a LOT of water and sometimes has small discharges of urine in the morning before we get outside which for his age is a little unusual. Overall, a great pup to work with and we believe he can face the rigors of guide work.

She will try to get away with certain behaviors so the handler must be persitant/consistant

Lindy is very sensitive to disapproval.  Examples: PPP - if she doesn't get what I want - she shuts down.  If I am disappointed in my other dog and reward Lindy because she is being good she spits the kibble out.  If I stub my toe she looks 'guilty'.  If the water in the shower is too hot and I make a noise she will leave the bathroom.  If she is eating kibble and I make any kind of negative sound she will spit it out. If you jolly her she recovers.

In our oppinion Klute is highly intelligence and easily trainable.... however, he has a tendenciy to overfraternize with other dogs and some people.  He has had an extremely hard time learning to sit when encountering people and has missed out on opportunities due to this.  We have had to turn and walk away when it is clear that both he and the other party would enjoy getting together.   Given the chance to observe the situation first and when people do not approach him or make direct eye contact he does much, much better.   Also, Klute is a sniffer. When on hard surfaces or indoors he is learning...but on grass he wants to concentrate on smells if allowed.  Working on this every day.   You can see him trying to work out the issues.  He is a very sweet, friendly dog but still is a bit puppy like.  .

ExerciseType: Walking, Running, play with other dogs
GeneralComments: Overall, I think Hanley is progressing well.  He gets many compliments from the public for being well behaved for such a young pup.  He is a very intelligent pup, so keeping him interested and engaged does require some imagination at times.  Hanley is also very confident, so is willing to try most anything you are trying to teach him.  Hanley is definitely a "little boy" despite the large frame for his age.  It definitely helps to have him exercise before engaging in training so that he can burn off some excess energy.  He has areas where he needs improvement, but I'm confident that he will get there with time, patience and continuing training.  He's been an awesome pup to raise.  Everyday with Hanley feels like a gift!

ExerciseType: fetch is favorite-running in tennis court or fenced area with other pups-any dif't toy is worthy of a happy run thru house
GeneralComments: Calla was very excitable when she came. She had a lot of trouble focusing in any new environment. I'm convinced that the early "follow me" training is paying off. Her progress is impressive. We continue to challenge her to public walks in Frederick and noisy places wherever we can take her. She's really smart, quick at new things, attentive and tries hard. Meeting other dogs is really difficult for her. I can see progress with people and places, so I'm sure the other dog problem will improve. She's the kid in the room who can't quiet down when she's tired-she just gets more wired until she gets in trouble, then collapses.

We have tried breaking it down into shorter more frequent sessions but this doesn't always work.

GeneralComments: I've been pleased with Marjorie.  She has been easier to work with than either Barton or India.  She is not as impulsive and doesn't pull like they did when on the lead.  I feel confident that I can see her through to her IFT.   However, I need to know that others have faith in me, as well.  If I sense that others are doubting me, then it affects my confidence in myself as a raiser and then I start second guessing and losing my self assurance.  Just as Jim says, we should trust the dog, the raisers need to be trusted too.  to be honest, I'm very nervous about this IFT, as it feels like there is so much riding on it.

FoodType: Iams. We are in the process of switching from puppy to adult Iams.
ExerciseType: Daily walks. Playing run after ball in stairway. Running and jumping after frisbee or toy on long leash in back yard. Going for 1/2 mile jog  with "Papa".
GeneralComments: Manny is a very sweet, smart, gentle puppy. He does need our full attention when wide awake and out of the kennel or he will quickly get into trouble.  He does try to eat sticks outside a lot which then makes him vomit. We follow the GEB protocol for vomiting, which says to withhold food for 12hrs. This seems to exacerbate the problem, because Manny is more hungry then and tries all the harder to get sticks:)!  I am also working on riding in the car with Manny in the passenger footspace. He tends to jump up while I'm driving, making things dangerous. I put things on the seat to prevent his jumping onto the seat. I have been stopping the car when possible when he gets up and I put him in the kennel ASAP( in the back of the car) if he doesn't go down or sit. I think we're making progress on this.  Keith will be starting to teach again next week, so Manny will be in the kennel for longer periods now on the days that Keith and I will both be working.  I am looking forward to the Walk & Talk! Thank you!

Lyle is a very laid back puppy who is benefits from repeated exposures. He will do anything but it needs to be on his own time. A few months ago he refused to go up the stairs at the train station or at my work [within the same week] but had no problem with other flights of closed-back stairs at home or in other settings. After repeated exposures with treats and positive reinforcement he is willing to attempt all stairs after rushing up initially. We have been working on slowing down ascending the work and train stairs. Improving with repeated exposure. He will attempt only the first 2-3 steps of closed back stairs.  No other issues noticed. Walks nicely on a lead with only occasional pulling. Great on all underfootings, and in traffic in city and in towns. Settles very nicely in church, work and restaurants, responds quickly to re-direction and is very pleasant company to have on outings.

I also think that I have not been spending as much time with her on house manners as we have been with her commands.  We are trying to keep focused on that too.

GeneralComments: Harris is a love!  Very fun, very affectionate, easy to train, very responsive, very trustworthy.  Can take him anywhere!  Most recently, when we are out training, he has been more pre-occupied with his own sniffing parties of things like sidewalks, bushes, corners of buildings, uprights, etc.  No behavior of marking.  Although still capable of checking-in.  I'm working extra hard to keep clear of these objects, work on shorter leash, boost our pace, etc.  Have also been giving him extra time initially upon arrival to explore and desensitize (chilling at a bench) before we get down to business.  Also worthwhile to note, that after some time has passed and repeated exposure, Harris can work quite nicely on LLW.

FoodType: Science Diet Lamb and Rice Puppy
GeneralComments: Pernault has never taken place in a homeswitch or an overnight. He is a very good pup who really wants to play with the resident cat (cat wants nothing to do with him). He has never shown any aggression towards the cat, just wants to play. He will bring the cat toys and she will respond in a negative way. He is a very social pup who loves to be around people. Because of this, I am finding it a little difficult to be able to train him to be in his kennel when left alone or when I walk in and out of the room without barking or whining or throwing a tantrum.

GeneralComments: In March he went to Virginia and was amazing with the long car ride, my Aunt's 190 pound St. Bernard, fire alarms, the hotel, traveling to museums and going to restaurants! This past week we were house/farm sitting and he was able to get closer to the horses then the last time we watched the property and he didnt bark or growel at them this time! He also lived through his first tornado experience, he was paniced and worried with the wind blowing against the house (we were in a very old home), but calmed down when we got to safety. He even alerted me to a wild snake in the room we were in and was cool and collected while i screamed and freaked out because of it being in the house (I have a really bad fear of them).

Serena is a very good girl. I'd say her biggest issue is a kind of lackidaisical response to commands. She will freeze at times and refuse to respond without a treat incentive. She is a bit more timid than other dogs I have raised, but shows nothing I see as problematic. Serena needs work on patience. She gets bored easily when asked to settle for more than a few minutes (although she has no problem sleeping in her comfy bed for hours at a time ; ) ), and will begin to whine and pop up from a sit or down. She is a very good loose leash walker, which makes raising her a much more pleasant experience!

ExerciseType: walks, hikes, play w/ other dogs
GeneralComments: 1) Moxie has had excellent health since the day she left the CDC. Other than 2 brief cystitis/urethritis episodes when younger which responded immediately to antibiotics, she has had no health issues. Her stools have been perfect, 1st on Purina Lg Breed Puppy Chow, and now on Purina ProPlan Lamb & Rice. She has never missed a meal!  2) Lots of body handling & massage, wearing tank tops and then the longer puppy coats for eating, playing, bone-chewing, hanging out, etc.  seem to have helped with much of her body sensitivity, though she will still occasionally briefly turn to nose her apparel or stop to scratch at it briefly (1 to a few seconds).  3) She has a pleasant energy level and can readily settle in any environment I have exposed her to, loves to work, appears to love and have endless energy for learning & for rising to new challenges in skills, activities, and environmental exposures. She is motivated by handler praise & interaction, food, toys, go sniff command, and many life rewards.  4) She has extremely quick reactions which makes teaching her easy, but also can work to her detriment if she thinks she should be in charge. While action and movement excite and arouse her, for the most part she can split attention and resume/maintain focus on the handler and the activity or work ay hand. She will respond readily to direction in almost all situations so far with the exception of some dog interactions I have described above - I understand she may be making her best guess/choice at behavior, but I would like help with teaching her better choices if that is at all possible. Having expressed that concern, I can also say that she is quick to lower her arousal and work with me offering requested behaviors at a relatively short distance as well as to appear to relax very nicely with massage. I am not sure whether this inappropriate play arises from being single female with six male sibs, whether estrogen effect after 1st heat will be beneficial, or whether she is uncertain with some dogs and wants to settle or dominate the action - and maybe none of that makes a difference.   5) Moxie is overall a lovely, fun pup to raise and have around. She is teaching me a lot and is giving me and her other 2 raisers, Maura Cornish and Ellen Joseph, much pleasure in the process.

GeneralComments: 1) Moxie has had excellent health since the day she left the CDC. Other than 2 brief cystitis/urethritis episodes when younger which responded immediately to antibiotics, she has had no health issues. Her stools have been perfect, 1st on Purina Lg Breed Puppy Chow, and now on Purina ProPlan Lamb & Rice. She has never missed a meal!  2) Lots of body handling & massage, wearing tank tops and then the longer puppy coats for eating, playing, bone-chewing, hanging out, etc.  seem to have helped with much of her body sensitivity, though she will still occasionally briefly turn to nose her apparel or stop to scratch at it briefly (1 to a few seconds).  3) She has a pleasant energy level and can readily settle in any environment I have exposed her to, loves to work, appears to love and have endless energy for learning & for rising to new challenges in skills, activities, and environmental exposures. She is motivated by handler praise & interaction, food, toys, go sniff command, and many life rewards.  4) She has extremely quick reactions which makes teaching her easy, but also can work to her detriment if she thinks she should be in charge. While action and movement excite and arouse her, for the most part she can split attention and resume/maintain focus on the handler and the activity or work ay hand. She will respond readily to direction in almost all situations so far with the exception of some dog interactions I have described above - I understand she may be making her best guess/choice at behavior, but I would like help with teaching her better choices if that is at all possible. Having expressed that concern, I can also say that she is quick to lower her arousal and work with me offering requested behaviors at a relatively short distance as well as to appear to relax very nicely with massage. I am not sure whether this inappropriate play arises from being single female with six male sibs, whether estrogen effect after 1st heat will be beneficial, or whether she is uncertain with some dogs and wants to settle or dominate the action - and maybe none of that makes a difference.   5) Moxie is overall a lovely, fun pup to raise and have around. She is teaching me a lot and is giving me and her other 2 raisers, Maura Cornish and Ellen Joseph, much pleasure in the process.

ExerciseType: Walks, hikes, swims, plays w/ dog pals
GeneralComments: Overall, Moxie is a very nice puppy and seems reasonably confident. She is quite body sensitive and tolerates, but does not appear to enjoy, purposeful body handling. She does a lot of licking of people when greeting people - I am assuming it is a stress reliever. She will still occasionally airsnap, but it is much improved - again, I believe it is a stress reliever. She is most successful when training or socialization outings are kept quite short, 20 minutes or less. She is progressing nicely and seems age-appropriate in all aspects. It would be helpful to have a jacket for her at this point in her raising, so that we can start exposing her to indoor quiet public places, work automatic doorways, etc.

ExerciseType: walks, running on beach, playing in yard
GeneralComments: Kiley continues to have major distraction problems but we are making some headway.  I have discovered that doing puppy sit-ups helps her to tune back in to what we are doing.  Birds are really difficult for her - any size, shape or color.  She wants to be able to fly with them as she sometimes jumps way up in the air to try to reach them.  We spend quite a bit of time sitting and watching the birds waiting for Kiley to tune back in - some of the small sparrows come within a foot of her front feet - she mostly holds her sit tho her attention is solely on them.

Kelley is a great dog. She lives for her treats. She isn't too good with stand she will stand for a few seconds but if you hold off on the treat she thinks she should do something else and will race around doing sit, down , close, heal looking for anything that will get her a treat.    She loves to play and walk on the long lead.     Dosn't come all the time off lead. So I try to say lets go or this way if I think she is too intereste in something else.     go place// likes to be rewarded a lot. Will stand up and settle again to get your attention and hope for a treat.       rides good in the car at the passenger spot but can not be trusted in the car alone other than for me to walk around to the other side and get her.    She is a joy to have around.

She has also been to Karen Seifert's home for 2 nights, but that was when she was only a few months old. I'd like her to go on more overnights or home switches, but her constant need to be on crate rest really interferes with that.

Harper is a joy & now that his GI issues are gone he is doing better.  In his familiar environment he listens very well.  Out & about he does well for the most part but he seems to have an animal distraction right now and we are working on that. If he is tired he needs alot of jollying to get up and get moving but once up he goes into good dog mode.  He works at a slower pace than most of the labs we've had which makes for a very plesant energy level for us..  Looking forward to seeing you in a couple weeks..

FoodType: Nutro Natural Choice Lamb and Rice
ExerciseType: walks, hiking, play w/other dogs, some biking
GeneralComments: Dean is a teenager!!  He is still a wonderful dog, and very easy to live with, but has more issues with distraction and excitement than he did a few months ago.  I have been using a prong collar on him some of the time (especially when I know we are going to an area with high distraction), and he is excellent when it is on.  With just the martingale, he is harder to control, and doesn't listen as readily.  HIs confidence is great, and his temperament is phenomenal.  I think it is mostly age related.  I'm trying to up his exercise, and have begun biking short distances with him, which he loves and is very well behaved when doing.  His biggest issue is that he gets overly excited when playing with other dogs, and starts neck biting and barking.  I am interrupting play frequently, and not letting the energy level get up there, but it is challenging.  I'm looking forward to you seeing him, Jane, and getting your opinion on how he's doing!

ExerciseType: walk, fetch w/ a chuck-it, play w/ GEB released Frannie,exposure
GeneralComments: Dave is a very sweet, smart boy.  We are working on holding sits with people walking by and helping him not to initiate his own people greet.  He works well with raisers and sitters if they give him good feedback and don't "beg" him.  When Dave gets excited or we are close to home he will pick up his pace so we need to work on getting him to try to not to go to the end of the leash. Dave will pull on Frannie's collar to initiate play but will stop when I say his name.  He doesn't bother my senior sheltie.  He is a total joy to be with and handsome too!

ExerciseType: 1 mile Walk each day and plays in large fenced yard with two other labs
GeneralComments: Clark is a sweetheart . His "greeting challenge" has made it hard when we are out and about. He's so darned handsome he draws people to him. But other than that he's been a joy. We have never seen Clark "mark' and he does not sniff and pull excessively like other mature males we've raised. He's quite expressive and full of fun.  We hope his excitability is just the puppy in him and the training staff will be able to help him overcome this behavior. No matter what's in his future I'm sure he'll make us proud as he enters the next phase of this journey.

ExerciseType: 1 mile Walk each day and plays in large fenced yard with two other labs
GeneralComments: Clark is a very sweet young man.  Very low key at home.  Once he's had his exercise you don't even know he's around. He enjoys working and practicing position changes in all types of environments.  Walks beautifully on  leash and catches on to training very well.  He can be inconsistent when we are out and about.  Now that autumn is here he's quite distracted by blowing leaves but we are seeing improvement in that area.  However, his biggest challenge has been and continues to be greetings.  We took him out for socialization this weekend.  At the mall he was wonderful. We put him in a down stay, sat down on a bench a leash length away, all kinds of people walked by and he didn't move. Then we went to Loews and he tried leaping toward people as we walked passed them.  I would really appreciate some extra help with this even if it means we need to send him to someone who's really great at teaching greetings and can work with him.  He will turn his attention to us if someone approaches and we offer wonderful rewards, but this too gets him overly excited.  HELP!

He enjoys working and practicing position changes in all types of environments.  Walks beautifully on  leash and catches on to training very well.  He can be inconsistent when we are out and about.  Now that autumn is here he's quite distracted by blowing leaves but we are seeing improvement in that area.  However, his biggest challenge has been and continues to be greetings.  We took him out for socialization this weekend.  At the mall he was wonderful. We put him in a down stay, sat down on a bench a leash length away, all kinds of people walked by and he didn't move. Then we went to Loews and he tried leaping toward people as we walked passed them.  I would really appreciate some extra help with this even if it means we need to send him to someone who's really great at teaching greetings and can work with him.  He will turn his attention to us if someone approaches and we offer wonderful rewards, but this too gets him overly excited.  HELP!

ExerciseType: walking, hiking, light jogging, puppy play on the beach
GeneralComments: Boise is a gem! We continue to work on body handling daily.  She has low distraction around other animals and dogs - not so much with her GEB friends -  but focuses in on me when asked. She has been pausing a little longer to look at the seagulls on the beach lately however  when I say "lets go" she responds instantly and moves along with me. So she's gaining confidence - is much more aware of her world and her place in it - but has the self control to reign it in and stay on message when asked. I continue to work mostly long line except in public place and really busy traffic areas.  I continue to work with paw handling and her nail clipping - she thinks its all great fun until we get down to brass tacks - patience is the key - I'm trying to take my time, little steps and not shoot for the moon - some days we clip, some days not. One nail at a time is my mantra!!!  Thanks Kerry!!

ExerciseType: walking, hiking, light jogging, puppy play, fetch
GeneralComments: Boise continues to amaze and delight! She's just an awesome pup - great energy level - incredibly easy to work with - learns new things at a drop of a hat - eager - willing - confident - adapts well to new situations and has a genuine zest for life and all things fun!!  Would like some pointers in terms of helping her to settle when I need her to. She's great at just chilling and hanging out at home but when out and about, she tends to think she's  to be in work mode and doesn't always find it easy to settle  - for example while sitting in a waiting room.    Between her heat and her eye, the importance of body handling has really hit home. We continue to work on it daily basis, here, there and everywhere. I'm also trying to work with her in terms of her comfort level with nails -  Kerry's work with Tessi has inspired me!!

GeneralComments: Alise has calmed down considerably. She still gets excited in new places, but settles quickly, then works beautifully. Many thanks to Sherry for letting her attend her classes.

Alise is awesome in so many ways, but I continue to struggle with LLW; keeping her tuned in especially around animals. When we go to a new place it takes her several minutes to get comfortable and tune in.  She does well at ballgames with people and loudspeakers.  If we walk in a shopping center she does well around people and traffic, but starts to air sniff the pet stores from about 2 stores down even if there are no dogs outside.  Neighborhood walks are difficult because of all of the barking dogs, loose cats, etc. She will now "Go Place" while I vaccuum, sweep, etc. which is a huge accomplishment.

ExerciseType: 3 walks per day, backyard time with release dog Denton, fetch, toys in house
GeneralComments: Amigo continues to be a delightful puppy...smart, well-behaved and sweet.  He has a problem with dog-distraction which gives us trouble in class but generally not noticed when out in jacket.  Have on 2 occasions come nose to nose with other service dog in stores and Amigo has lost composure...settled but with effort.  Have decreased use of food rewards as it was becoming a problem, what I call BBD, beg, bark, drool!  Amigo will do beautifully until food is introduced and then he becomes focussed on the food with disasterous results.  He is happy working for praise until food appears.  Food quickly becomes an obsession.  Love this dog.  Amigo can live with me forever if he chooses not to work.

ExerciseType: LLW at least twice a day and fetch
GeneralComments: I have only had Camille for 5 weeks. I am a novice handler, but she is doing very well. The only incident of concern was when Camille got out of her crate when I was gone for three hours and she got into her food. She had diarrhea or at least loos stool the next day. She was fine after that and has not tried to escape from her crate since then. Camille had free reign of the house and did not chew or destroy anything or get into the garbage on the kitchen floor. She could have done some real damage to the house and  or herself, but luckily did not.

ExerciseType: dog play, bone chewing, fetch, hiking
GeneralComments: Phoebe is an absolute delight, lover girl with personality plus! She is a very smart quick study and a sponge for learning.  It's been great fun keeping her challenged while honing her newly learned skills!  Phoebe has a great energy level and is very well behaved in the house.  She goes everywhere with us and loves riding in the car in her crate and is silent while crated!  When out and about, she appears confident with new exposures - with the exception of truck air brakes which we are working on.  She is very friendly when greeting strangers and other dogs, but not overly exuberant which makes it very easy to manage her obedience skills set when faced with high levels of distractions.  Phoebe likes her poops.  She even likes to turn around and watch herself poop.  If given the opportunity, she will probably delight in its delicacy. Rest assure, she will never be given that opp!  ; )

She is very friendly when greeting strangers and other dogs, but not overly exuberant which makes it very easy to manage her obedience skills set when faced with high levels of distractions.  Phoebe likes her poops.  She even likes to turn around and watch herself poop.  If given the opportunity, she will probably delight in its delicacy. Rest assure, she will never be given that opp!  ; )

ExerciseType: walking, playing fetch, playing with my dog
GeneralComments: Noel is a wonderful puppy and is very well-behaved for her age. She enjoys moving my footwear around the house but she has yet to chew on or destroy anything. She can be very playful but will also pick up a nylabone and go sit on her dog bed to chew it quietly by herself. She gets along well with my dog but can tend to get a little nervous around some other dogs (barks at them as she backs away). This improved considerably between her first puppy class and her second. She has been very friendly with every person she has met. If I leave the bathroom door open, she will grab the end of the toilet paper roll and run through the house (like on that commercial!) but otherwise her house manners are excellent for such a young puppy. Noel is very sweet and I am very much enjoying raising her!

ExerciseType: walking, running, playing with my dog
GeneralComments: Noel is a very sweet puppy. She can tend to sometimes get over-excited, especially when we are about to go out for a walk. She has always been a big fan of my treadmill so over the past month or so I have been letting her walk on it. If she does 5 minutes or so, this settles her enough to be able to walk calmly outside. She is getting more curious, jumping up on the tables and counters. She doesn't take anything, just looks around then jumps back off. I've been working on this a fair amount and it is improving. She tends to be hesitant at first when she encounters something new but she is quite willing to explore anything with a little patience and encouragement. She is very well-behaved on outings for such a young puppy. We need to work on more outings where she stays still for a time because she has a tendency to grow impatient and bark sometimes. Other than the jumping and occasional chewing, her house manners have always been quite good. She likes to be in whatever room I am in but she'll usually carry a nylabone along with her and play quietly while I am cooking, cleaning, etc. I am very much enjoying raising Noel.

Marcus is very bright. He's reached an age where he needs to be mentally and physically stimulated more. He's not destructive, which is good. Marcus loves to run, and as such his leash walking isn't that great. I'm a little worried with his class behavior. It's gotten progressively worse. He gets very intense about other dogs and must be redirected, otherwise he will bark and pull towards them. Generally, Marcus is very chill, but he's started to get more and more excited when people visit. He has had some problems with vomiting (usually late in the day before dinner). Overall though, he's an excellent pup and very connected to his handler. He likes to be close with people at all times.

Generally, Marcus is very chill, but he's started to get more and more excited when people visit. He has had some problems with vomiting (usually late in the day before dinner). Overall though, he's an excellent pup and very connected to his handler. He likes to be close with people at all times.

She is so wonderful about so many things but just does not seem to be able to over come getting overly excited around people and dogs.  I take her out almost daily to busy places and I see some progress but it continues to be a concern.  She is very, very attached to me and when I put her on a long lead outside and I work in my flower gardens if I am not right near her all the time she barks and jumps up and down.  After being outside for 30 to 40 mintes she will finally stop that behavior.    She has been having an issue with high salvia production when she first gets into my car.  So, I have started taking her to fun plays in the car instead of always going in the car and working.

ExerciseType: walks, chasing toys, playing with dogs
GeneralComments: Hopi is a very sweet puppy.  She loves to be handled and will let you do almost anything to her body.  Nail clipping is easy as long as you don't do too many at any one time.  She learns by watching what we do to our own dog - and then lets us to the same to her - such as rinsing eyes with warm water, liquid tears eye drops, wipe out ears, brushing, etc.  On the other end of the spectrum - she is very strong willed.  If there is something she does not wish to do, she will ignore your command.  Then it is a waiting game - sometimes she wins and sometimes I do!

As instructed we have introduced Freesia to many other dogs of all sizes and except for submissive peeing sometimes at first greeting she's been doing just fine.   We've also traveled all up and down the East Coast with her and find she adapts very easily to new people and places.   This is a smart little pup who learns things quite easily although she can be thrown off track by smell and dog distractions.

Dash is the sweetest dog in the world. Yet, he is also pretty excitable and highly stimulated by sounds. Music and clapping are a big challenge.   He is a typical shepherd in that he monitors environment, worries over children who are moving around, running or crying, and responds to movement.  Dash has a habit,though it is improving greatly, of holding his urine and refusing to GB. He will hold his urine for upwards of 24 hours. Due to this he misses outings at times as we are waiting on the GB before he leaves for a socialization outing.   As he is a fully adolescent male loose leash walking has entered a challenging phase, he is more distractable and wanting to sniff frequently. Lots of stopping and waiting on Dash to connect back to handler.  Overall he is the sweetest boy in the world and we are blessed to have had the opportunity   to raise him.

'Back' is fair but not solid.    Dash appears to be maturing slowly but steadily.

Dash is doing well overall. He has excellent house manners, does not bark too much. He does have some issues with dog distractions. Loose leash walking was going very well but he is in a distracted phase at the moment. Working on no sniffing and not pulling ahead if he is excited in a new location. Dash very much enjoys getting out and about, he will wait and ask for outings. The more he gets out the more settled he is and less excitable. He is a very sweet and affectionate dog, a bit of a softy for such a big guy. He has not shown any signs of dominance despite heading into adolescence.

ExerciseType: retrieve ball, run & play w/ our other dogs, walks w/ me,
GeneralComments: Looking back over this, I feel like my own evaluation of Barb has been harsh.  But, these observations are accurate.  Barb is a smart dog w/ great potential.  Things that may startle or concern many dogs don't phase her, like the moving Halloween mannequins in the stores.  Self control is her biggest problem.  She's been with me ~10 wks, & is finally showing signs of being more connected w/ me. If given the choice, would still pick dogs over people.  To avoid reinforcing unwanted behavior, haven't walked her thru the neighborhood behind my home in over a month.  Continued failure. Have to work/walk in more controlled setting, where I know there will not be many visual dog distractions. Want to help her grow w/o pushing her over her threshold.  She's been one tricky girl, but a sweet, smart, & worth the work!

ExerciseType: Walks, Jogs, Play with other dog
GeneralComments: We love Bangle! We have found that Bangle needs a lot of exercise; we aim for 4 miles plus dog playtime/day.  If she gets this, she is very pleasant around the house.  If she doesn't, she is less pleasant and occasionally gets into trouble. Bangle is truly amazing in office settings; people in meetings with her forget she's there.  She stays on her go place mat while I am using the copier, etc. If she gets support and guidance while meeting people and walking around squirrels and dogs, she can do well. She will not walk on grates. She seems fine on other odd surfaces and I'm confident we can work up to that. On her 2nd time riding an elevator, the elevator began making a very unpleasant high-pitched noise.  Since then, Bangle has not been willing to ride in elevators.  She does not seem stressed around an elevator with an open door.  We plan on going very slowly and with one of my dogs who is good in elevators.

She stays on her go place mat while I am using the copier, etc. If she gets support and guidance while meeting people and walking around squirrels and dogs, she can do well. She will not walk on grates. She seems fine on other odd surfaces and I'm confident we can work up to that. On her 2nd time riding an elevator, the elevator began making a very unpleasant high-pitched noise.  Since then, Bangle has not been willing to ride in elevators.  She does not seem stressed around an elevator with an open door.  We plan on going very slowly and with one of my dogs who is good in elevators.

It has encourage me to help Simba over come some bad habits..eating everything on the ground, barking, pulling,  patience, confidence and helping him focus while other puppies are near by. Currently need help with getting Simba to work closer to my side (tends to be a little in front of me), sharper communication with commands. ..catch myself saying FREE then YES?!!  I continually try to provide positive outings to encourage confidence..back off as needed, use treats and try to return the next day. Walks; Run with others in fenced yard
GeneralComments: Lincoln is a fun-loving, exhuberent worker. He loves working and interacting with handler, and enters each day full of enthusiasm!!!! He does seem immature for his age at this point- both mentally and physically, and did spend significant time in previous quarter on crate rest due to Pano...  His greatest challenges are: He still requires "direction" when free in house to settle and relax-- for example, he will relax if given a "go place", but left to his own devices, tends to pace, carry bone around, and get up to investigate movment...He is also extremely agile, and left to his own devices would be up on and exploring furniture, etc...Again, he is showing improvement thru training, but his natural tendency is to be "up"..  I have seen improvement in these areas over the past few weeks, and believe as he matures and gains experience, he will continue to improve...

GeneralComments: Lincoln is a very willing, solicitous pup. Can worry and show concern if not understanding the task at hand. Often "goldenlike" in his temperment-- lots of carrying toy to show family, pacing, using paws to solicit attention, clowning around when confused, etc...  He does best with clear direction, and still a bit immature when left to his own devices to make the best decision :) That said, he sure is a loving, caring, giving, always smiling pup!!!!

ExerciseType: Walks, Run in field with other GEB pups
GeneralComments: Lincoln is an enjoyable pup, willing and loves to work. He has a soft, sweet temperment.   With consistent direction and clear handling, he is nicely manageable for his age. In new situations, can initially show high arousal, easily stimulated, but settles nicely as socialization period progresses...  Have noticed a stronger distraction, especially toward small animals in motion, in past month- working on re-directing his focus during these times.

ExerciseType: walks, run, fetch with soccor  ball, play dates with other GEB pups
GeneralComments: Kinley is a very sensative pup, he doesn't seem to like change, but he is working pretty hard.  Since his return in March, Kinley has settled down alot, he stills wants to be with me all the time but he can be with the kids while I do errands and such with out much concerns.  He has also made great leaps at class and how he behaves.  We have been trying to get him more excercie and outings.  He gets out and about at lease 5 or 6 days a week.  He has alot of exposure to children in our different home school groups and even did a presentation for an additional Home School group of 20+ kids and 6+ adults.  He did great.  He is coming along and we have not had to many issues with the peeing since he has been on the meds.  Thanks for all your help.  Bernadette Turner

Jenny has grown in confidence and energy level. She is testing both me and the other dogs. She is no pushover. She is very smart and is a thinker and problem solver. However, what she considers a problem is not always what I consider a problem. It is fun to watch her wheels turn. She thinks she can talk and tries her best to communicate with me. She is very connected and tuned in.    The major thing we are working on is having her settle while I disconnect from her. She would prefer to keep moving, and if we arenÆt moving that I at least engage her and feed her treats. She considers æsettlingÆ a problem that she would like to fix. She is making good progress though. She is now letting me sit and disconnect without doing all kinds of behaviors to get my attention. She still doesnÆt lay down and settle for long without getting ansy, but itÆs a process.     Jenny walks well in all environments and shows good confidence. She is fabulous with noises and has very low small animal distractions. She is great around other dogs and children. She is observant and pays attention to her environment. IÆm very excited about Jenny because she has some real potential to be a fabulous guide.

When they told me she was very active and quite dominant I was expecting someone 'spunky' and full of herself. Well.. maybe it's just who you have had before, but I find her to be rather low key, easy going, and very interested in pleasing the people in the house. She likes the people better than the dogs. She can hang out with me for long periods while I study - she just sleeps and snores loudly. lol She is very, very sweet and affectionate. She is very tuned in and tries hard to do what you ask of her. I haven't had time to have her out and about extensively, but everywhere I have taken her she has done and excellent job. Having her is rather like having another 3 yr old dog in the house. Thank you for my 'nice easy pup',

Joy is doing very well and we are really pleased with her progress. At times she does get overly interested in people we see on walks or when we're out and about and become so focused on them that she tunes me out and lunges for them.  But, we are working on this and with verbal redirection, she does come back to me fairly well.  She is a sweet, sweet girl who is very smart and willing!

Joy is doing very well though she does get very excited to see people and has a hard time calming down (this includes our family when we come home from being out).  She loves to lick people when they visit with her and it is hard for her to resist this urge.

ExerciseType: Walking, play w/ other dogs, hike on drag line
GeneralComments: Gladys has made vast improvement in many areas. 1) A diet change has resulted in a healthy weight gain and 1-2 normal bowel movements/day compared to several soft ones/day when she 1st arrived.  2) She is now housetrained and goes to the door or comes to me or paces around when she needs to go out & get busy - she would sometimes urinate and defecate indoors when she 1st arrived and was often too distracted outdoors to relax &get busy on request. She has always kept her crate clean.  3) Gladys responds well to clear expectations - will work for food, toys, play, life rewards. While she has shown a quick and sometimes marked startle response, she is extremely resilient - has never "shut down," and has always been willing to "go check it out." And repeatedly approach from different directions, etc. When she 1st came to me, my assessment was that she had high visual, auditory, and olefactory distraction - probably contributing to the difficulty Lucille had in getting her house-trained. She does well with slow and careful exposures, and I have found short outings and watching her body language carefully is important - she will start to pant, occasionally yawn, sniff more, move more quickly and lose focus and connection if she is unsure of herself. Some of her social outings have included 3 different post offices, CVS drugsore in quiet times, a church service concert and coffee hour (many people greetings) afterwards, library, 1/4 mile track in Yorktown, settling at staff meetings and committee meetings, quiet residential neighborhoods in White Plains, bigger street in White Plains on Sunday morning - minimal traffic, Yorktown, Shrub Oak, Mt. Kisco, Katonah, Briarcliff Manor, Brewster, New Paltz, shopping center parking lots and walking in front of store fronts, automatic doors. I think she needs time to take new things in with ALL of her senses, and I tried to keep outings limited to 20 minutes or less so that she would get new exposures without feeling overwhelmed. I think she is still a fairly immature 9 month old, but has made great progress. She does very well with support - how she will do when she doesn't have that support, I don't know, because she still seems pretty young to me. She is a very sweet, very pleasant pup, loves to run and play, but has also done very well "hanging out " when I am at work and did fine with almost no exercise for several days in a row. She continues to improve re dog distraction, and will offer auto checkins some of the time if the dog-dog distance is appropriate. High value treats get her interest readily. There is probably more I could write but I am sure I have gone on long enough, other than to add that she needs a very patient raiser.
