GeneralComments: Floyd is a powerful pup; He enjoys working with handler but needs to limit sessions to small slices to avoid increase in his stress level. He is easily aroused, and tends to be very olfactory in new environments. Once he is familar thru repeated exposure, he will reduce amount of sniffing and drooling... He has a sensitive side, and is reachable, but needs time to take in things slowly with repeated exposure prior to moving on. Initially uncomfortable with new experiences at times. He has shown improvement during his time here, and his ability to handle the environment in a relaxed manner is improving over time :)

Claude is a very sweet and smart boy. He knows his stuff and has a great personality but his dog distraction is very high and his excitement level can escalate quickly. He is improving but LLW and getting him into class can be challenging.

Claude is a very sweet and smart boy. He knows his stuff and has a great personality but his dog distraction is very high and his excitement level can escalate quickly. He is improving but LLW and getting him into class can be challenging.

Claude is very strong willed. He is also physically strong and a big boy. He loves meeting people, smelling/picking up everything and seeing other dogs. However, these represent mighty distractions for him resulting in difficult LLW even with alot of high value rewards. Often his training (out in public) and his socialization is a battle of wills. On the other hand, Claude has a wonderful temperment and personality when distractions are reduced. He has good house manners and can be handled easily, he enjoys it and is easy to groom. He likes to "work", has no trouble with commmands and will follow up to ten commands without being rewarded. He is loves to cuddle, play and interact. Claude is a bit like Dr. J and Mr. H!

ExerciseType: dog play, fetch, hiking, bone chewing
GeneralComments: Patrick has recently entered into a phase where I am finding it difficult and frustrating to get and maintain a connection during obedience exercises when certain female dogs are close-by.  Any other time, he works beautifully.  He does not lift his leg or hump, but does lung to lick, but not all, certain females.     His recent bad behavior in class during play session resulted in a time-out.  After discussions with Roberta, playtime will be more closely controlled with limited access to the other dogs.  I will continue to work very closely with Patrick to reinforce training; step-up his activity level since his energy level seems to be higher and he is taking fewer naps; ramp-up and enforce PPP (NILIF!).

ExerciseType: Walks, play with other dogs, run outside on long leash
GeneralComments: It has been difficult to do an exposure. Due to the recent snow- he is more interested in running and playing in the snow then walking properly and staying connected. The rule of three did not work and we had to end the exposure rather soon. It's really difficult to keep my footing and have him listen and stay away from the snow!! Tried store fronts,  snow is literally everywhere and he doesn't want to listen. Do they forget everything they learned? Or turn a deaf ear and just do what they want to? I never really had a problem with exposures before now, as a resulte this months exposures have been less then before and a smaller duration as well :(

ExerciseType: long line, tennis court running, walks
GeneralComments: We are still working on loose leash walking. It has gotten better but he is still pulling. We have worked on our connection as well and parties which make walking better and he listens and pays attention and keeps connected. Stairs are going really well. I did notice recently he is fine until the last step going up and he wants to run up to get to the top now. But going down he is fine. He is really good with the new way of holding the leash and walking up the stairs as well; he did pretty good at class. The only problem we had again was running to get to the top step.

North is a strong, occasionally willful puppy with a pleasant energy level.  He is always up for an adventure and settles easily in social environments including the mall, restaurants, the office,the train and church settings where he has been exposed to people of all ages.  He is confident on all underfootings and takes traffic and noises in stride.  North continues to need work on loose lead walking as he will pull if allowed and dog distraction.  We are working on exposing him to other dogs while staying connected with his handler on walks.  He has no problem quickly acclimating to and working alongside other familiar and unfamiliar jacketed pups on program, on outings. North is a large,strong puppy who will take advantage of an inexperienced handler but responds very well to consistent, clear direction.

some things unchanged - mainly his over excitement around other dogs and the strength of his scent drive. when his desire to smell is greater than his desire to not choke himself on his own leash, it can be tough. understanding, the scent drive is natural, the leash it not. we're doing our best to be patient and consistent in these situations, but are struggling to make progress.  house manners are improving greatly. removed the baby gate blocking access to our upstairs without any issue. his improved ability to settle himself inside makes him much more pleasant to have at home in recent weeks. still not perfect, but is headed in the right direction and should get there with time.   begun exposing him to the insides of stores (Home Depot, Walmart etc.). overall been quite good save for the abundance of squeaker noises coming from the infant/toddler section at Walmart.  recent GEB Annual Report cover dog. has signed on IMG as an agent and is accepting endorsement deals.

ExerciseType: We play fetch and go for a walk every day. Major also goes to class with me 5 days a week.
GeneralComments: Major is very successful with his commands.  He still loves the game of fetch and chase.  He still has to overcome his obsession with taking things that do not belong to him and his counter jumping problem.  Major needs to be touching a part of someone whenever he is asked to sit or lie down whether that meansresting his head on someone's foot or cuddling up on someone's lap.  He has too much energy for his own good and needs to be walked everyday or he is restless and whiny.  I think Major loves his training and puppy classes!

ExerciseType: Walking, throwing tennis ball, frisbie, etc
GeneralComments: I am concerned about the sniffing.  It really started just before she came into heat.  Sometimes she is just so intent and has to get to that smell (I'm guessing it's other dogs.) and she strains so hard and does not even respond to food, high end.  I've been working with her a lot, pulling her head up shen she goes to sniff while walking.  It's getting better, but it is still difficult in an area like around my work where a lot of people walk their dogs.  She can get very excitable, especially when she sees someone she is very fond of.  (Like when she comes into puppy class--she loves everyone there and there are certain people she responds to who come into work)  She'll "sit" but she is just shaking all over with excitement she just can't get into a full sit.  I appreciate the tremendous amount of support from Maureen and Maria.  They are both very encouraging and have been extremely helpful.

ExerciseType: long lead walk/run, fetch, yard play
GeneralComments: Irby is a fun guy and seems to rise to whatever level is required of him. He has been going back and forth to maryland with me. in MD he's in a dog-friendly apt building where there are some well-socialized dogs and some not so well socialized dogs. The former, we can share an elevator, the latter-- we don't even try. Anyway, he's had two very different home environments and adapts well. Clearly on his overnight recently, he learned a lot (good) and we'll do it again. He is still reactive to reactive pups. Once he's figured out that it's not play time with other dogs (as in class) he settles down fairly quickly. We've worked on doors everywhere.   See you soon!

Occasional sniffing/ drooling on workouts if stressed, but also showing improvement in that area with repeated exposure.

I received Denton for 5 wk puppy sitting on 1/4/10.  He was highly excitable, exhibited demanding behaviors including  muzzle nudging and barking.  Would not return items - played keep away.  Become very excited and try to hold me down if I played with him on the floor.  We have bonded well w/ significant breakthrough on day 6.  Very biddable & responiding well to training  & increased exercise.  learning to self-modulate - demanding behaviors much improved.  Good maners at home and work.  More accepting of body handling.  Takes some time to settle in new environments.  Needs work on dog/dog interactions and generalization of self-modulation.  Needs work on lose lead walking w/ progressive increase in distractions.  Probably needs to work on spending time in crate - have not evaluated.  I am very pleased w/ the progress he has made in 5 wks.

GeneralComments: Cecil is by far the most difficult dog I've ever worked with. That being said, I want you to know I love him to pieces. He's such a sweetheart he's just...very much a puppy. We work well together I think, he reminds me of Sabrina at times. Whenever I get frustrated with him I try and think about how she was when I got her and to how she behaved when I took her to NY.    I was disappointed in the lack of information I recieved about him beforehand though. If I had been told about his bad habits (peeing in the house, garbage diving, energy level, stubbornness etc.) I can't say I would have agreed to take him. But he is here now and I plan on working through all of this with him. I do not like to quit the things I've started.    Thank you for this opportunity to raise again, he's a fantastic guy and I look forward to getting him into shape (:

Waffle came to live with us this past August, when she was 9 months old.  She has a good understanding of all the commands and responds very well when at home.  She is easily distracted by other dogs and by scents that she picks up when outside.  These are our biggest challenges as we work to help her stay focused and connected when at class and when we are out walking or socializing.  Waffle has an absolutely lovely temperament, is overall very well behaved and has formed solid connections with each of our family members.

FoodType: Chicken Soup for the Pet Lover's Soul
ExerciseType: Walking, chasing balls, playing with other dogs
GeneralComments: Pablo is a sweet, willing, and lovable pup who is a little sensitive. His house manners are outstanding and he is enjoyable company in the home. He is a pleasure to take to work and well liked by staff who reward his visits with treats. He can get a little anxious when he is separated from his raiser, even with someone he knows, but can be redirected with a to, task, or treat.   He is eager to please and will do what he is asked whether it is to jump onto a low wall or climb a ramp.  Sometimes he can be a little too excitable in attempting to comply with his standard (sit, stay, heel, etc.) requests by offering behavior different than that requested in his desire to earn the treat reward; he can be calmed down with a patient attitude and redirection.  Pablo has a very sensitive stomach and did not thrive on IAMS (dandruff, licking paws, diarrhea) and had a long transition to his new food. He is more likely to have soft stools when given a treat that another Lab eats without any effect.    He is a beautiful dog, runs like the wind, swims without fear, loves us completely, and we are going to miss him terribly when his time comes.

ExerciseType: Walking, chasing balls, playing with other dogs
GeneralComments: Pablo is a sweet, willing, and lovable pup who is a little sensitive. His house manners are outstanding and he is enjoyable company in the home. He is a pleasure to take to work and well liked by staff who reward his visits with treats. He can get a little anxious when he is separated from his raiser, even with someone he knows, but can be redirected with a to, task, or treat.   He is eager to please and will do what he is asked whether it is to jump onto a low wall or climb a ramp.  Sometimes he can be a little too excitable in attempting to comply with his standard (sit, stay, heel, etc.) requests by offering behavior different than that requested in his desire to earn the treat reward; he can be calmed down with a patient attitude and redirection.  Pablo has a very sensitive stomach and did not thrive on IAMS (dandruff, licking paws, diarrhea) and had a long transition to his new food. He is more likely to have soft stools when given a treat that another Lab eats without any effect.    He is a beautiful dog, runs like the wind, swims without fear, loves us completely, and we are going to miss him terribly when his time comes.

ExerciseType: walking, playing with pet dogs, mental games
GeneralComments: Fay is a very pleasant dog to have around. She is low energy until you ask her to "perform" and then she stays right with you. She has bonded very closely to me (her primary handler) and takes some of her confidence from mine. Because of this attachment, she can become upset when I leave her. She will bark until/unless she is distracted from my leaving. She is very sweet and people oriented. She loves to play with other dogs and is usually very respectful of them. She also enjoys keeping herself occupied with her toys. She has great house manners and I have left her alone (out of the crate) on numerous occasions with much success. On outings she is very well-behaved and I can trust her anywhere.
